9	10	allin_amy_5621777.pdf	\N	December 16, 2024\nTexas A&M University\nSchool of Law\n1515 Commerce St.\nFort Worth, TX 76102\nRe: Non-Tenure: Adjunct Professor of Law application- Cover Letter\nDean Ahdieh:\nI respectfully request your consideration of my application for the adjunct professor position. Over the last two\nyears, I have supervised and mentored new lawyer and it has impassioned me to get involved with the\neducation of our rising attorneys and future leaders.\nIf granted the opportunity, my ideal course would be as follows:\nVoir Dire: Where Cases are Won and Lost (1 to 2 lecture hours). A well-executed voir dire may\nnot always secure a trial victory, but a poor performance can almost guarantee defeat. The first\nportion of this course will focus on a comprehensive understanding the laws that apply to jury\nselection from juror qualifications and the examination process outlined in the Code of\nCriminal Procedure to the case law essential to all trial attorneys. Next comes the “do’s and\ndon’ts” of voir dire with how to avoid pitfalls that could lead to a case being overturned and\nhow to preserve error for appeal when things go awry. After mastering the law, the course shift\nto the practical trial skills essential to picking the right jurors for a case. What questions should\nbe asked in voir dire? What does the ideal juror look like? Most trial teams don’t have a Dr. Bull\non retainer, but at the end of this course, students will be the next best thing.\nSo often developing trial attorneys build a curriculum around criminal or civil procedure, evidence, trial\nadvocacy, and trial rights, but mastery of all the above is only effective if you have the right jury to hear your\ncase. While most students graduate with a basic understanding of voir dire, picking a jury is truly an art and\ndeserves a thorough exploration of the applicable law and the social science at play.\nI am confident that I am best suited to teach on the topic after my eight years as a trial attorney with the\nTarrant County Criminal District Attorney’s Office. During my time at the Office, I have tried over 50 jury trials,\nranging from misdemeanors to capital murder. In 2022, I tried 11 felony jury trials, more than any attorney in\nthe Office’s recent history for a calendar year, and earned the distinction as Prosecutor of the Year. This year I\nspent six weeks doing individual voir dire of 160 prospective jurors on a death penalty case, allowing for years\nof voir dire experience to be done in less than two months.\nIn addition to voir dire, I also have a passion for crimes against women and would love to be involved in the\ndeath penalty seminar course. Should the Law School have more immediate needs in either realm, I would love\nto develop a course proposal for your review.\nI welcome the opportunity to further discuss my qualifications with you. I can be reached at (214) 460-4375 or\nby email at amyallin1015@gmail.com. I have attached my resume and references; please let me know if there\nis anything else I can provide. Thank you in advance for your time and consideration, I appreciate you.\nRespectfully,\nAmy Allin\n\nAmy E. Allin\n214.460.4375 ǀ AEAllin@tarrantcountytx.gov\nCurrent Position\nTarrant County Criminal District Attorney’s Office Fort Worth, Texas\nAssistant Criminal District Attorney February 2017- Present\n• Current assignment: Chief of Criminal District Court No. 2\n• Prior assignments: Intimate Partner Violence Unit, Adult Sexual Assault Unit; Assistant Chief of Misdemeanor\n• 22 felony jury trials; 33 misdemeanor jury trials\n• Criminal Prosecutor of the Year, 2022\n• Prosecutor assigned to represent the State of Texas in the Public Safety Employees Treatment Court (PSETC)\nExperience\nTarrant County Defense Attorneys Fort Worth, Texas\nLaw Clerk May 2016 – January 2017\n• Prepare cases for docket and assist with trial preparation\n• Meet with client to discuss legal issues and potential resolutions\n• Served as co-counsel on secured acquittals on two felony jury trials\nMaryland Judiciary Rockville, Maryland\nMontgomery County District Court Law Clerk August 2015- May 2016\n• Review cases submitted for affidavit judgment to assure cases are adequately prepared for judgment\n• Prepare memoranda outlining relevant law for upcoming motions and hearings\n• Research complex legal issues that come before the Court\nOffice of the State's Attorney for Prince George’s County Upper Marlboro, Maryland\nRule 16 Student Attorney January 2014- May 2015\n• Prosecute misdemeanor crimes, including twenty-seven bench trials and one jury trial\n• Investigate cases, negotiate plea agreements, and interview witnesses for weekly dockets of approximately 30 cases\n• Screen over 200 incoming citizen complaints to determine if the matter should be pursued by the State\nMariam A. Valoy, PLLC Washington, DC\nLegal Intern February- August 2013\n• Conduct legal research pertaining to land transactions with a focus on landlord and tenant relations\n• Draft office memorandums on research findings and the effects of the findings on clients’ cases\n• Attend meetings with potential and existing clients to formulate strategies to combat their legal issues\nEducation\nThe Catholic University of America, Columbus School of Law, Washington, DC\nJuris Doctor May 2015\n• GPA: 3.515; Cum Laude\n• Catholic University Law Review, Associate\n• Moot Court Association, Chancellor\nUniversity of Illinois, Champaign, IL\nBachelor of Science in Advertising May 2012\nMinor in Communication\n• GPA: 3.30\n• Varsity Women’s Tennis, Team Captain, All-Big Ten, highest ranking: 19\nBar Admission\nTexas- admitted and in good standing since December 2016\nMaryland- admitted December 2015 and currently inactive (MBE score: 166; top 5% nationwide)\n\nDecember 15, 2024\nTexas A&M University\nSchool of Law\n1515 Commerce St.\nFort Worth, TX 76102\nRe: Non-Tenure: Adjunct Professor of Law application- Personal Statement\nDean Ahdieh:\nTwelve years ago, I started my first year of law school unsure of what career I wanted to pursue. I’d always had\na passion for criminal law but was interested in the financial appeal of the private sector. However, any\nuncertainty dissolved when I took criminal procedure with Professor Leary. I didn’t only want to practice\ncriminal law, I wanted to be her. I wanted to be a prosecutor like her, I wanted to be a role model to my\ndaughters like her, and I wanted to inspire others to be their best self like she did for me. I am coming up on a\ndecade since law school graduation, and yet I completed a death penalty case this month and wanted to let her\nknow because I still practice each day to make her proud. She is the reason I want to teach.\nMy road to where I am today is not the conventional path of most lawyers. I was born and raised in Dallas with\na family of tennis players. My maternal grandfather was the men’s tennis coach at TCU, and his first recruit was\nmy dad. My dad married his coach’s daughter and together my parents raised three collegiate tennis players. I\nwas the youngest and attended the University of Illinois on a tennis scholarship. While at the U of I, I was\nunsure of what life looked like for me after graduation. I always wanted to be a lawyer but was too intimidated\nby the prospect, so I majored in advertising after enjoying an introductory course. During my junior year, I\nexperienced significant personal growth on the tennis court when I went from being out of the lineup my\nsophomore year to the top player and an All Big Ten honoree the following season. It was this new-found\nconfidence that inspired me to chase the law school dream.\nI attended law school at the Catholic University of America, Columbus School of Law. This was the first time I\nwent to school because I wanted to be there and wanted to learn. I loved my classes, my professors, and the\nlaw. In addition to my studies, I interned with the Office of the State’s Attorney for four semesters, served as\nChancellor of Moot Court, spent a year as an associate of the Catholic University Law Review, worked as a\nresearch assistant, taught high school students though the Street Law program, assisted with coaching the\nmen’s and women’s tennis team, and worked as a LexisNexis representative.\nAfter law school, I took the Maryland Bar Exam and worked as a judicial law clerk while waiting for bar results. I\nhad every intention of applying for the State’s Attorney’s Office where I interned, but my family lead me back to\nTexas. As a strong believer in “everything happens for a reason,” I was driving the U-Haul from DC to Texas and\nstopped in Nashville for a weekend with friends and met my future husband there.\nOnce back in Texas, I had to take the Texas Bar Exam so I worked for some criminal defense attorneys to get\nexposure to the courthouse so that I would know my way around when it came time to apply to the District\nAttorney’s Office after passing the bar.\nI have now been with the Tarrant County District Attorney’s Office for nearly eight years and it feels like I have\nfound my calling. After working my way through the misdemeanor section and an introduction to felony, I got\nassigned to the Intimate Partner Violence (IPV) Unit. This was my first real exposure to crimes against women\nand the complex dynamics at play in domestic abuse cases. It was eye opening to see how many domestic\nviolence victims and cases are mishandled and made me passionate about spreading the message about all\nthat I was learning. I then promoted to the Adult Sexual Assault Unit, a team that was established to address\nthe lack of prosecution for these offenses. Because sexual assaults were so rarely investigated, filed, and\nprosecuted, this unit was a test pilot and I will proudly say that our office is second to none when it comes to\n\nprosecuting these cases today. After spending the second half of 2023 as a supervisor to the misdemeanor\ndivision of ap