vironmental actions in California state\nand federal courts.\n Counsel permit applicants in California under a variety of land-use and\nenvironmental laws, including the Coastal Act, CEQA, the Endangered\nSpecies Act, and the Clean Water Act, as well as under the Takings\nClause.\n Represent nonprofit associations in range of industries as “friends of the\ncourt” in precedent-setting takings and environmental cases in federal\nappellate courts and in the United States Supreme Court.\nAlston & Bird LLP\nPartner (Jan. 2018 – Nov. 2019), Counsel (Jan. 2015 – Dec. 2017)\n Co-chaired the Coastal Land Use Group, leading the Firm’s land-use\npermit and litigation practice in California’s coastal jurisdictions.\n Litigated and counseled permit applicants on takings, land-use, and\nenvironmental issues in California.\n\nPacific Legal Foundation, Sacramento, CA\nPrincipal Attorney (Oct. 2007 – Dec. 2014); Staff Attorney (Oct. 2003 –\nSept. 2007)\n Chaired the Coastal Land Rights Project, heading the Foundation’s\nlitigation against abusive land-use laws and actions affecting coastal\nlandowners.\n Supervised and litigated dozens of trial-level and appellate cases against\ngovernment entities in state and federal courts across the country,\nincluding under the Takings Clause, and a variety of federal, state, and\nlocal laws and regulations.\n Successfully briefed and argued Koontz v. St. Johns River Water\nManagement District, 570 U.S. 595 (2013), in the United States\nSupreme Court, establishing that monetary exactions as the condition of\nland use and development trigger heightened scrutiny under the Takings\nClause.\nHennigan, Bennett & Dorman, Los Angeles, CA\nLitigation Associate (Nov. 2001 – Oct. 2003)\nLatham & Watkins, Los Angeles, CA\nLitigation Associate (Aug. 2000 – Oct. 2001)\nADMISSIONS California Bar; Texas Bar (inactive); United States Supreme Court; United\nStates Court of Appeals for the Fifth, Ninth, Tenth, D.C., and Federal\nCircuits; United States District Court for all Districts in California; D.C.\nDistrict Court\nMEMBERSHIPS Federalist Society\nEDUCATION Cornell University, Ithaca, NY\nDegree: J.D., May 2000\nHonors: John M. Olin Foundation Student Scholar in Law and\nEconomics, 1998-2000; CALI Award for Highest Grade in\nLaw & Economics Seminar\nActivities: Cornell Law Review, Managing Editor\nLatino Law Students Association\nFederalist Society\n\nUniversity of California, Los Angeles\nDegree: B.A., cum laude, Economics & English Literature (double\nmajor), June 1997\nHonors: Economics Departmental Honors; English Departmental\nHonors; UCLA College Honors (Letters & Science); Dean’s\nList; Economics International Honor Society; Sigma Tau\nDelta English Honor Society\nUniversità Commerciale Luigi Bocconi, Milan, Italy\nVisiting Student in Economics, 1995-1996\nPUBLICATIONS “Is a Broad Clean Water Act really necessary (or relevant) to protect water\nquality? The Lake Champlain Basin as a case study” (in progress, with co-\nauthor, Damien Schiff) [Paper presentation in progress], The Clean Water\nAct and Lake Champlain Basin: Origins, Implementation, Impact\nWorkshop at State University of New York College at Plattsburgh (Nov.\n3-5, 2022)\n“Supreme Court Ruling Could Dramatically Change the Playing Field for\nTakings Claims, JD Supra, June 27, 2019 (with co-author, Matthew\nWickersham)\n“California Issues Expansive ‘Wetland’ Regulations as Federal Agencies\nWork to Narrow Clean Water Act Jurisdiction,” JD Supra, April 24, 2019\n(with co-author, Gina Angiolillo)\n“Property owners have the right to a fair hearing first,” Daily Journal, April\n10, 2019 (with co-author Damien Schiff) (discussing their constitutional\nchallenge to a California law giving the California Coastal Commission\nunilateral power to impose penalties on landowners)\n“Preemption at Midfield: Why the Current Generation of State-Law-Based\nClimate Change Litigation Violates the Supremacy Clause,” 49 Envtl. L.\n853 (2019) (with co-author, Damie