my classroom, I strive to present learning materials in an objective and balanced manner.\nI believe that education should be a platform for the free exchange of ideas, where students feel\ncomfortable expressing diverse viewpoints. To achieve this, I incorporate a variety of perspectives\ninto my curriculum, ensuring that all voices are heard and respected. For example, land-use\npermitting and litigation often pit property-rights advocates against government agencies and even\nmembers of the community; it is essential to present—and validate—all viewpoints in what is\noften a contentious battle over the use and development of land. By presenting multiple sides of\nan issue, I encourage critical thinking and help students develop their own informed opinions. This\napproach not only enriches the learning experience but also prepares students to navigate the\ncomplexities of the legal field with an open and analytical mind.\nFundamental Understanding of Key Land-Use Principles\nA primary goal of my teaching is to ensure that students complete the course with a solid\ngrasp of key land-use principles. Land-use law is a critical area that impacts various aspects of\nsociety, from urban planning to environmental conservation. It touches everyone. To facilitate a\ncomprehensive understanding, I employ a combination of lectures, case studies, and practical\nexercises. These methods allow students to engage with the material actively and apply theoretical\nconcepts to real-world scenarios. By the end of the course, students will have a foundational\nknowledge of land-use law that they can build upon in their future careers.\nEncouraging a Love for the Law\nBeyond imparting knowledge, I am passionate about inspiring a love for the law in my\nstudents, with a particular emphasis on land-use law. I believe that enthusiasm is contagious, and\nI aim to convey my own passion for the subject through dynamic and engaging teaching methods.\nI incorporate current events, landmark cases, and interactive discussions to demonstrate the\nrelevance and impact of land-use law in everyday life. By connecting the material to students'\ninterests and experiences, I hope to ignite a lifelong curiosity and appreciation for the legal field.\n\nIn conclusion, my teaching philosophy is centered on creating an inclusive and stimulating\nlearning environment where students can explore diverse perspectives, gain a fundamental\nunderstanding of key land-use principles, and develop a passion for the law. I am excited about\nthe opportunity to contribute to the academic community as an adjunct professor and to inspire the\nnext generation of legal professionals.\nSincerely,\nPaul Beard II\n\nPaul Beard II\n205 N. Hill Ct., Double Oak, TX 75077\n818-216-3988\nPauljamesbeard2@gmail.com\nNovember 26, 2024\nSent Via Interfolio\nTexas A&M University Law School\n1515 Commerce St.\nFort Worth, TX 76102\nRe: References for Application for Non-Tenured Adjunct Professor Position\nTo Whom It May Concern:\nYou may contact the following individuals as references in connection with my application\nfor an adjunct professorship:\n1. Larry Salzman, Vice President for Litigation, Policy & Research, Pacific Legal\nFoundation. Phone: 619-569-8062. Email: LSalzman@pacificlegal.org.\nI have known Mr. Salzman professionally for almost 20 years, and he recently served\nas co-counsel in my United States Supreme Court case, Sheetz v. County of El Dorado.\n2. Irene Oria, Founding Partner and Co-Chair of Class Action Defense, Pierson Ferdinand\nLLP. Phone: 786-873-4603. Email: irene.oria@pierferd.com\nI have known Ms. Oria for over 25 years, and she currently is my partner at Pierson\nFerdinand.\n3. Andrew Grow. Phone: 805-903-2836. Email: andrew@injectorsdirect.com.\nMr. Grow is my client in a major land-use litigation that I am handling in California. I\nhave known him for approximately 3 years.\nSincerely,\nPaul Beard II\n\nApplication Forms\nFoster Child Form\nFoster Child\nI was not a 