te University\nBachelor of Science - BS, Economics with Econometrics focus · (2002 - 2005)\nPage 3 of 3\n\nPersonal Statement\nAs an experienced legal professional and educator, my teaching philosophy is rooted in accountability,\nclear and frequent communication, individualized engagement, and adaptability to diverse learning\nstyles. I strive to create an online learning environment that promotes critical thinking, encourages\nprofessional dialogue, and prepares students for practical applications of legal and ethical concepts. Over\nthe next several years, I plan to continue teaching in a part-time capacity, focusing on online education\nwhile maintaining my full-time professional legal career with the Department of Defense. My ultimate\ngoal is to expand my teaching portfolio to focus on world-class institutions such as Texas A&M University.\nI emphasize accountability as a cornerstone of my teaching approach, setting high academic and ethical\nstandards while providing students with structured course materials, well-defined objectives, and\ncontinuous feedback to guide their progress. At the same time, I recognize that effective communication\nis essential in an online learning environment. I encourage students to actively engage in discussions,\nseek clarification on complex topics, and voice any challenges they encounter. By fostering an open and\nprofessional dialogue, I ensure students receive the necessary support while upholding academic\nintegrity and institutional expectations.\nUnderstanding that students learn differently, I integrate various instructional methods to enhance\ncomprehension and engagement. Case studies, interactive discussions, multimedia content, and real-\nworld scenarios help make course material more accessible and practical. By exposing students to\nmultiple perspectives on complex legal, ethical, and policy issues, I aim to develop their analytical skills\nand critical thinking abilities. Additionally, I challenge students to con