dience in American sports with emphasis on\nHBCUs. HBCU-Athletic Research Consortium Conference (HBCU-ARC): Houston, TX, (2016).\n1st Annual Sports Negotiation Skills Competition, Director HBCU Athletic Research Consortium Conference\n(HBCU-ARC): Houston, Texas, (2016).\nMEMBERSHIPS/PROFESSIONAL AFFILIATIONS\n• The American Bar Association\n• The Houston Young Lawyers Association\n• The Society for Public Health Education (Houston Chapter)\n• The Journal of Nutrition Editor/Reviewer\n• Kappa Alpha Psi Fraternity, Inc. (Houston Alumni)\n• Texas African Chamber of Commerce Treasurer & Board of Director\n• Ghana Houston Chamber of Commerce (Past Vice-President)\nCOMMUNITY SERVICE\n-- 4 of 11 --\n\n5\n• 2021-Present: Ghana Association of Houston--President\n• 2019-Present:Texas West Africa Chamber of Commerce---Executive Board Member\n• 2018-Present: Ghana Houston Chamber of Commerce ---Vice Chairman\n• 2018-Present: Kappa Alpha Psi Fraternity, Inc.---Houston Alumni Member\n• 2018-Present: Ghana Association of Houston: Internal Affairs Director & Legal Advisor\n• 2015-2019: NIKE+ Football Regional Camp---Coach and Coordinator: Defensive Backs\n• 2015-2017: Young Women’s College Prep Academy---Volunteer Coach Track and Soccer\n• 2014- 2017 Positive Coaching Alliance (PCA)-Houston Chapter---Board Member\n-- 5 of 11 --\n\nNana K. Asare\n4617 White Rock Street\nHouston, TX 77051\nNanasare12@gmail.com\nDear Hiring Committee,\nPlease accept this letter for consideration for my application as an Adjunct Professor of Law at\nTexas A&M University. In support of my application, I have included examples of my scholarship\nwhich includes teaching, research and service at Texas Southern University as well as within the\nnational and international community for your review.\nI have had the honor and privilege of serving as an Assistant Professor in the Department\nof Health, Kinesiology and Sport Studies within the Department of College of Education, a\nposition I’ve held for the past seven years, after teaching as an adjunct in the HKSS department\nfrom 2013-2014.\nAcademic Leadership\nPrior to beginning my appointment as a faculty member at Texas Southern University, I\nworked in various industries including law, healthcare, research, academia, sports and\nentertainment as well as the information technology industry which I believe prepared me well\nwith not only practical experience but also an understanding of the everchanging work\nenvironment that our students are preparing to enter. Due to this practical experience, I am an\ntransformative intellectual who seeks to engage, inspire and most importantly challenge each and\nevery student that I teach through the use of my dynamic lectures and in class debates mixed with\nwhat some of my students have dubbed as “real world” class assignments. Some examples of my\ncontribution to enhancing the learning experiences of our students include the following a)\nincorporating the Negotiation Skills Competition as part of the Sport Ethics and the Law course\nb) teaching and incorporating business concepts as well as urging students to consider\nentrepreneurial paths by creating a business plan in my Leisure and Recreational Activities course\nand finally c) Collecting and Analyzing data for research purposes in Tests and Measurements.\nScholarship and Research\nI am aware that Texas A&M University aims to attract and retain proven scholars and researchers\namongst its faculty. As a result, I have remained active with students and colleagues in pursuit of\ngoals that produce relevant and scholarly research. For example, as part of my Tests and\nMeasurements class, I’ve incorporated a Data Collection Research Study into the course which\nrequires students to collect data on their daily physical activity/energy expenditure as compared to\ntheir daily caloric intake/energy consumption. With over five semesters of data collected and more\nthan one hundred participants, I hope to analyze and publish the findings in one of the premier\njournals in Nutrition or Obesity Research.\n-- 6 of 11 --\n\nNana K. Asare\n4617 White Rock Street\nHouston, TX 77051 Nanasare12@gmail.com\nAs a faculty member who teaches across a wide range and spectrum of courses offered within the\ndepartment. My research interests also reflect the diverse range of educational training as well as\ncareer experiences. I’m a regular guest speaker on local and national sports radio shows where I’ve\ndiscussed issues surrounding FIFA’s policies and expansion goals, World Cup soccer bidding and\nthe requirements for host nations/cities as well as the SWAC athletics conference expansion and\ncontractual obligations. My past research in the areas of Body Composition and Human Nutrition\nhave been cited in journals such as the American College of Sports Medicine, Medicine and\nScience in Sports and Exercise, Federation of American Societies for Experimental Biology. Most\nrecently, I was selected by the Journal of Nutrition as a Peer Reviewer and contributed to the\nevaluation and consideration for various articles for publication.\nService to the Community\nThroughout my academic career, I have consistently pursued collaborations with a multitude of\nuniversity and community stakeholder organizations, (non-profit board memberships, conducting\nresearch for private foundations and consulting for government organizations). With each\nleadership role in the community, there comes opportunities to build relationships with others\nthereby opening new synergistic opportunities for myself, my colleagues and my students. A great\nexample of this was evidence when I acted as an International Consultant to the Ghana Football\nAssociation in 2017 when the Ghana Men’s National Team, (the Black Stars) toured the U.S.\nwhile playing two FIFA friendly international matches against the U.S. Men’s National Team\n(Uncle Sam’s Army) and the Mexican Men’s National Team (El Tri). With this role, I was able to\nintroduce and in