 of Law, August 2023 – August 2024\nManaged JD Flex hybrid program by selecting courses, recruiting instructors, creating semester course schedules, and\nworking with multiple departments to organize core curriculum for each class. Planned law topic events for student\neducation and attorney MCLE. Worked closely with CAPLaw to create online Canvas materials for individual classes.\nManaged a yearly budget, advised students academically, and supported professors with their course needs. Taught\nMock Trial, Advanced Mock Trial, and Introduction to Litigation courses.\nDirector of the Litigation Program & Visiting Professor of Law, July 2020 – August 2023\nInterim Director of the Litigation Program & Visiting Professor of Law, March 2020 – June 2020\nAssociate Director of the Litigation Program & Visiting Professor of Law, May 2019 – February 2020\nManaged the Litigation Center by hiring adjuncts, selecting offered courses, supervising teaching assistants, securing\nspeakers, and coordinating events. Leader of the annual Summer Trial and Evidence Program (STEP), which\nimmersed 1L students in an intense boot camp to master their litigation skills. Taught technical skills for all phases of\ntrial, including writing and arguing pre-trial motions, how to conduct effective examinations of a variety of witnesses,\ntrial preparation, opening statements, and closing statements. Executed the annual In Vino Veritas National Mock\nTrial Competition and one-time Texas Young Lawyers Association (TYLA) Competition. Sat on the following faculty\ncommittees: Curriculum, Academic Standards, and Accelerated Bar Exam Task Force. Faculty Advisor for the Student\nAnimal Legal Defense Fund, Society of Litigators, and an Environmental Law Journal writer. Co-founded “Clothing for\nClosing” donation closet for students to receive free courtroom attire. Assisted in the creation of the Gabriel\nFernandez Scholarship to award students who advocate for abuse victims. Redesigned the Litigation Center website\nand produced a seasonal newsletter. Taught Introduction to Litigation, Trial Advocacy and Advanced Trial Advocacy,\nMock Trial and Advanced Mock Trial, Evidence in the Courtroom, and Effective Brief Writing & Motion Advocacy.\nNapa County District Attorney’s Office, Napa, CA\nDeputy District Attorney, March 2015 – May 2019\nLitigated 21 jury trials, including charges such as child annoy/molest, driving under the influence (DUI), destruction\nof evidence, drug possession, resisting arrest, trespass, public intoxication, and more. Lead attorney in the Juvenile\nUnit for one year and in the DUI unit for two years, which involved handling all phases of a case from charging\nthrough sentencing and appeal. Conducted 15 felony preliminary hearings, including evading police, DUI, grand theft,\nchild abuse, and more. Researched and drafted motions on evidence suppression, plea withdrawal, and more. Featured\npresenter for several alcohol and marijuana DUI trainings for law enforcement and prosecutors.\nSacramento County District Attorney’s Office, Sacramento, CA\nDeputy District Attorney, December 2013 – December 2014\nConducted 10 misdemeanor jury trials, including charges of battery, DUI, petty theft, and more. Handled a vehicular\nmanslaughter court trial. Performed hearings such as evidence suppression, preliminary, speedy trial, and demurrer.\nResearched and drafted various motions, including evidence suppression, lack of venue, and restitution.\nEDUCATION\nGolden Gate University School of Law, San Francisco, CA\nJ.D. (specialization in litigation, criminal law, and public interest law), May 2013\nHonors: Honors Lawyering Program, Dean’s List, CALI Excellence Award for Alternative Dispute\nResolution, Environmental Law Scholarship, ALDF Advancement of Animal Law Scholarship\nLeadership: Founder and Director of the California Annual Animal Law Symposium, President of the Student\nAnimal Legal Defense Fund, Environmental Law Society Communications Officer\nActivities: Evidence Teaching Assistant for Professor Keane, Research Assistant for Professor Duramy,\nAssociate Editor for the Environmental Law Journal, Pro Bono Honors Society\nSan Francisco State University, San Francisco, CA\nB.A., cum laude, Criminal Justice, January 2010\nThesis: “The Challenges of Community Policing”\nAWARDS & PUBLICATIONS\nPublished Articles for NITA: Opening, Closing, Cross Exam, Experts, Harmful Evidence, Trial Preparation (2021 – 2024)\nTop 40 Young Lawyer on the Rise, American Bar Association (ABA), San Francisco, CA, 2022\nOutstanding DUI Prosecutor, Mothers Against Drunk Driving (MADD), Pleasanton, CA, 2019\nTrial Attorney of the Year, District Attorney’s Office, Napa, CA, 2018\nYoung Lawyer of the Year, Napa Young Lawyers Division, Napa, CA, 2018\n-- 2 of 8 --\n\nPersonal Statement for Texas A&M University Law School:\nTeaching Philosophy and Plans\nDear Hiring Committee,\nI am excited to apply to Texas A&M University School of Law and share my teaching\nphilosophy, which focuses on creating an inclusive, engaging, and practical learning\nenvironment that prepares students for success in the legal field.\nI value teaching a diverse group of students, including those with military and various\ncultural backgrounds. I have had the privilege of working at a law school ranked among the\nmost diverse in the United States, where military-connected students make up nearly one-\nthird of the student body. I believe that students' unique life experiences bring valuable\nperspectives, especially in assessing legal cases.\nTo maintain student engagement, I incorporate activities, polls, short clips, and group\ndiscussions to help students stay focused and absorb material effectively. I also balance\ntheoretical knowledge with practical experience by using real-world cases and current\nevents to help students understand the intersection of law and public policy. In trial\nadvocacy courses, students first read about courtroom practices, then dive deeper into the\nmaterial during lectures, and finally apply what they’ve learned through hands-on\nexercises. This approach exposes them to tangible legal challenges and helps them\ndevelop as advocates.\nClear communication is central to my teaching philosophy. I ensure students understand\ncourse objectives and have a clear path to success through regular check-ins, office hours,\nand online forums for clarification and support. I also provide detailed, constructive\nfeedback on assignments, exams, and presentations, highlighting strengths and areas for\nimprovement. This approach fosters growth as legal thinkers and communicators,\npreparing students for the demands of legal practice.\nIn summary, my teaching philosophy emphasizes both theoretical knowledge and practical\nskills within an inclusive and engaging environment. By embracing diverse perspectives,\nusing interactive methods, and offering clear communication and feedback, I aim to help\nstudents become thoughtful, effective, and socially conscious legal professionals.\nThank you for considering my application to Texas A&M University Law School.\nSincerely,\nRachel Brockl\n-- 3 of 8 --\n\nContact Reference Page\nMark Yates\nTitle: Law School Dean\nOrganization: Golden Gate University (GGU)\nLocation: San Francisco, California\nEmail: myates@ggu.edu\nPhone: 415-374-0093\nRelationship: Former Supervisor (GGU)\nJody Mask\nTitle: Civil Attorney\nOrganization: Mask and Guerrero Law Firm\nLocation: McAllen, Texas\nEmail: jody@masklaw.com\nPhone: 956-221-1619\nRelationship: Professor Colleague (GGU)\nCurtis Briggs\nTitle: Criminal Defense Attorney\nOrganization: Briggs Law\nLocation: San Francisco, California\nEmail: briggslawsf@gmail.com\nPhone: 415-205-7854\nRelationship: Professor Colleague (GGU)\n-- 4 of 8 --\n\nApplication Forms\nFoster Child Form\nFoster Child\nI was not a foster child\n-- 5 of 8 --\n\nVeteran Status/Identification Form\nVoluntary Self-Identification of Veteran Status\nI do not identify a