37	63	brody_david_5618043.pdf	\N	David Brody\nÜniversite Caddesi, No:35-37 Cell: +90 (534) 835-0315\nAğaçlı Yol, Bornova-İzmir-Turkey davidsbrody@gmail.com\nDecember 22, 2024\nTexas A&M University School of Law\n1515 Commerce St,\nFort Worth, TX 76102\nDear Search Committee Chair and Members:\nI am very pleased to apply for a position as an Adjunct Professor of Law. After many years of\nteaching abroad, I am currently planning to return to the United States to continue my career\nthere, and I am currently looking for part-time positions teaching legal writing and legal English,\nboth in-person and online. I think that I could be most useful teaching students from civil law\ncountries who are studying in an LL.M. program, or helping J.D. students who are struggling\nwith legal writing to bring their work up to the level that law school study requires.\nI currently work at Yaşar University in Izmir, Turkey, as a full-time lecturer in law and a\ncontributing member of the School of Foreign Languages. In addition, I have recently started\nworking part-time in the online Legal English Certificate Program at the University of Houston,\nwhich is primarily aimed at students entering their LL.M. program.\nIn my courses at Yaşar, I teach basic skills such as how to read and brief a case, IRAC form\nand other fundamentals of legal writing, oral presentation skills, as well as standard academic\nessay writing. The fact that the students are undergraduates studying in a civil law system,\ncombined with the fact that they are not native speakers, has meant that I have had to adapt a\nlot of the existing legal writing materials to their needs, and that I have had to create a lot of\nmaterials from scratch. Over the last two years, a colleague and I have written a workbook\nbased on what we have developed, both individually and together. This workbook is being\nprepared for publication by University of Michigan Press, and is due out in August of 2025.\nI hope you decide that my experience and skills could be useful to the School of Law, and that\nwe will be able to discuss a position in the near future.\nSincerely,\nDavid Brody\n-- 1 of 9 --\n\nDavid Brody\nÜniversite Caddesi, No:35-37 Cell: +90 (534) 835-0315\nAğaçlı Yol, Bornova-İzmir-Turkey davidsbrody@gmail.com\nPROFESSIONAL EXPERIENCE\n____________________________________________________________________________________\nUniversity of Houston Law Center, Houston, TX 3/24-present\nInstructor\n• Online instruction in the Legal English Certificate Program\nYaşar University Faculty of Law, Izmir, Turkey 9/10-present\nLecturer\n• Three Excellence in Teaching awards.\n• Currently teaching in the fields of comparative law, legal English, and legal research and writing.\n• Law faculty coordinator for the Erasmus+ international educational exchange program.\nDavid Brody, Attorney at Law, San Francisco, CA 3/08-8/10\nSolo Practitioner\n• Solo practice focused on criminal appellate law\nLaw Office of Cliff Gardner, Oakland, CA 7/05-2/08\nAssociate\n• Duties included research and writing of briefs for cases on direct appeal and preparing petitions\nfor writ of habeas corpus in both California and Federal courts\nContra Costa County Public Defender, Richmond, CA 8/04-7/05\nLaw Clerk\n• Duties included legal research and writing of motions and petitions\nKent English, Ankara, Turkey 8/96-8/97,\nEFL Instructor 1/01-6/01\n• Taught English as a Foreign Language to adult students\nEDUCATION\n____________________________________________________________________________________\nUniversity of San Francisco School of Law, San Francisco, CA\nJuris Doctor, May, 2004\n• Cum Laude\n• Two CALI Awards for Excellence: one in Legal Research and Writing and one in Constitutional\nLaw.\nBilkent University, Ankara, Turkey\nMaster of Arts in International Relations, September, 1999\n• Full Scholarship and Stipend\nUniversity of Oregon, Eugene, OR\nBachelor of Arts, Philosophy, September, 1987\nPUBLICATIONS\n____________________________________________________________________________________\nCollins, I., & Brody, D. (2025). The English Language Common Law Workbook: A resource for students studying\nEnglish-medium law degrees. University of Michigan Press. https://press.umich.edu/Books/T/The-English-\nLanguage-Common-Law-Workbook. (In press).\nBrody, D., Collins, I., & Akdemir Kamalı, T. (2021) The Yaşar University Legal English Center: A Response to the\nChallenges of Providing Legal English and English as a Medium of Instruction in Law Courses. John Marshall\nLaw Journal 14(2) 234-247. https://www.johnmarshall.edu/lawreview/wp-content/uploads/2021-AJMLS-\nSpring-Journal-XIV2-Brody-et-al..pdf.\n-- 2 of 9 --\n\nTeaching Statement\nA colleague of mine at the Turkish university where I work characterizes my job, which is\nteaching law in English, as teaching about something Turkey does not have in a language that\nmy students do not speak. He exaggerates a bit on both counts, but there is some truth to what he\nsays. Firstly, Turkey’s legal system definitely suffers from some serious problems. These stem\nfrom a number of causes, but the one that concerns and affects me directly is that Turkish legal\neducation puts a lot of emphasis on memorizing, and very little on developing skills. Although\nmy job teaching law and legal skills in English to undergraduate students is supposed to broaden\ntheir education and give it an international dimension, it is, sadly, true that my students generally\ncome to me without the necessary foundation of legal research and writing skills in their own\nlanguage. On top of that, the English level of many of my students is really below where it needs\nto be. The upshot of all of this is that in all of the courses that I give, whether they are legal\nEnglish or substantive law courses, my goals always include building skills, and no matter what\nmy goals are, I also need to be a language teacher if I want to achieve them.\nWhat this means in practice is that materials from law courses and legal writing courses in the\nUnited States can seldom be used without serious modification. Generally, I have had to create\nmy own materials, either by myself or with other instructors. As I mentioned in my cover letter, a\nworkbook of materials that I have developed with another instructor is due to be published by\nUniversity of Michigan press in August, 2025.1 The main justification for the existence of the\nbook is that students coming from many other civil law countries to study in LL.M. programs in\nthe United States come from educational backgrounds that are quite similar to those of my\nTurkish students, and will be able to benefit from some of the same teaching techniques and\nmaterials.\nTo give some examples about how I integrate skills into my substantive law courses, in my\nAmerican Constitutional Law course I teach students the IRAC form, and the rubric gives points\nfor proper use of this form, as well as for grammar and mechanics. In order to address language\nissues like blocking vocabulary, I generally create language and comprehension-focused\nworksheets to accompany assigned readings. I also try to use a variety of teaching methods\nduring each lesson. While there is nothing wrong with giving a lecture, most students –\nespecially non-native speakers – will learn better if they are also given a video to watch, a hypo\nto work on with a group, or even a game to play. In short, mixing things up results in lessons that\nare more engaging and effective.\nMany of my courses, such as Legal English I and II, are already explicitly focused on legal\nwriting, speaking, and reading skills. In these courses I teach statute and case reading, case\nbriefing, speaking, and presentation skills, among others. Of course, all of these skills have to be\ntaught keeping in mind the students civil law background, the low emphasis on skills in their\nTurkish courses, and the fact that the students are non-native speakers of English.\n1 Collins, I., & Brody, D. (2025). The English Language Common Law Workbook: A resource for students studying\nEnglish-medium law degrees. University of Michigan Press. https://press.umich.edu/Books/T/The-English-\nLanguage-Common-Law-Workbook. (In press).\n-- 3 of 9 --\n\nAn important change in my teaching over the years is that I now much more regularly use\nformative assessment. For example, at the beginning of many lessons, I start with a quiz using\nthe Kahoot or Quizizz app, to gauge how much the students have retained from previous lessons.\nWhen assessing whether students have understood an assigned reading, in addition to the\nlanguage and comprehension worksheets mentioned above, I also provide questions for small\ngroup discussions that I assess by circulating around the room to interact with students, and for\nwhole class discussions that I assess by eliciting responses in class.\nAlthough I began designing curriculum on my own when I started my university teaching career,\nI have since sought out opportunities to collaborate with others. For example, I created the Legal\nEnglish I and II program at our university along with a colleague from the School of Foreign\nLanguages, and I teach my sections of these courses in coordination with him and another\nlecturer according to a shared syllabus. The redesign of these courses was carried out under the\nauspices of the Unit for Legal Education in English, which my colleagues and I created to serve\nas a hub for all of the English-language activities of the Law Faculty and the School of Foreign\nLanguages. If possible, my preference is to find a position where there will be more such\nopportunities for collaboration.\n-- 4 of 9 --\n\nReferences\nAs I have not discussed my job search with my current employer, please do not contact my references\nwithout informing me first.\nIan Collins\nLecturer\nAssistant Director of the School of Foreign Languages\nian.collins@yasar.edu.tr\n+90 232-570 9804\nBurcu Dönmez\n