at the same time is\nthat I have seen what works and what does not work, both as a learner and as an instructor. My approach to\nteaching leverages all that I have learned in the decades spent as a student and as an instructor, recognizing that\nI will continue to learn and grow with my students. Above all else, I want my teaching style to inspire my\nstudents.\nAsynchronous online learning does require professors to adapt their own materials and teaching style to\nmeet student needs, despite the absence of real-time interactions. During my 14 years of asynchronous course\ndesign and instruction, I have learned to connect with students by leveraging the strengths of online learning\nplatforms. It is true that students may not see or hear me in real time (except during scheduled meetings), but I\nhave found that by enriching the basic course content with my own video lectures, actively participating in\ncourse discussions, and grading submitted work in a timely fashion, students feel less distant from the material\nand from the course. Something as simple as responding to all emails within 24 hours can make the instructor\nfeel less distant.\n-- 4 of 9 --\n\nThe Honorable Chad Louie, California Superior Court Judge\nChad.louie@kern.courts.ca.gov\nThe Honorable Jason Webster, California Superior Court Judge\nJason.Webster@kern.courts.ca.gov\nThe Honorable Wendy Avila, California Superior Court Judge\nWendy.Avila@kern.courts.ca.gov\nDr. Mark Martinez, political science chair at California State University Bakersfield\nmmartinez@csub.edu\n-- 5 of 9 --\n\nApplication Forms\nFoster Child Form\nFoster Child\nI do not wish to specify\n-- 6 of 9 --\n\nVeteran Status/Identification Form\nVoluntary Self-Identification of Veteran Status\nI identify with one of more of the veteran classifications listed above\nSurviving Spouse of a Veteran\nI am not a surviving spouse of a veteran\nOrphan of a Veteran\nI am not an orphan of a veteran\n-- 7 of 9 --\n\nClery Act\nAcknowledgement:\