ration | Columbia, SC\n• \tMagna Cum Laude\n-- 3 of 22 --\n\nDARREN S. CHIAPPETTA | RESUME \t3\nTEACHING\nEXPERIENCE\nSpring/Fall Semesters\n2009\nUniversity of Central Florida | Orlando, FL\nAdjunct Professor, Rosen College of Hospitality Management\n• \tTaught Hospitality Communications, a senior-level undergraduate course\naveraging 50 students per semester at UCF’s Rosen College, ranked #1\nfor Hospitality and Tourism Programs in U.S. and in top five globally.\no \tHighly-interactive course navigating the various types of business\nand professional communications - verbal and written – that\nstudents could expect in their first Hospitality supervisory role.\no \tCurriculum emphasis on the relationships and interactions\nstudents would have with guests, employees, fellow co-workers,\nand upper management throughout a Hospitality organization.\no \tCreated and revised syllabus each semester based on feedback\nand personal observation, ensuring effective/engaging material.\no \tDeveloped, reviewed, and graded individual and team-based\nprojects, in-person presentations, assignments, and final exam.\nSPEAKING\nENGAGEMENTS\nDec 2023 \tDeveloping Diverse Leadership from the Start\nFrom Day One – LA Conference | Los Angeles, CA\nDec 2022 \tInclusion: It’s about Evoking a Culture Change – Not Just\nChecking Boxes\nFrom Day One – LA Conference | Los Angeles, CA\nOct 2014 \tEthical Considerations in Employment Investigations and\nLitigation\nAssoc. of Corporate Counsel Annual Meeting | NOLA\nOct 2012 \tDon’t Bite the Hand that Feeds You: Navigating the Legal -HR\nRelationship\nAssoc. of Corporate Counsel Annual Meeting | Orlando, FL\nREFERENCES \tDr. Fevzi Okumus \tCFHLA Preeminent Chair Professor, Hospitality Services\nUniversity of Central Florida\nRosen College of Hospitality Management\n9907 Universal Blvd, Orlando FL 32819\nFevzi.Okumus@ucf.edu\n407.903.8177\nMadeline Mercier \tDirector, Employee Relations | Universal Music Group\n1900 E. Ocean Blvd #312\nLong Beach, CA 90802\nmerciermadeline32@gmail.com\n714.931.4456\nKatrina Lindsey \tChief Legal Officer/General Counsel | Casey’s General Stores\n410 W. First Street\nAnkeny, IA 50023\nkatrina.lindsey@caseys.com\n515.446.6579\n-- 4 of 22 --\n\n1.29.2025\nDARREN CHIAPPETTA: Personal Statement / Philosophy and Plans for Teaching\nArt imitates life. For more than a decade, I had amazing opportunities to serve as Labor & Employment\ncounsel and Head of Employee Relations/HR Compliance for industry-leading Hospitality and\nEntertainment corporations. Each day that I spent working with major “Hollywood” Studios (NBC,\nNetflix, CBS, Sony Pictures) I saw, first-hand, how talented, creative artists told a myriad of stories\nthrough Film, TV, and other media genres, bringing together people from all generations and\nbackgrounds.\nWhile at the Studios, my team became the proud owner of mandatory “respect in the workplace”\ntrainings, including anti-harassment/anti-bullying/non-discrimination in-person and online sessions for\nFilm/TV actors and crew. Notoriously, this audience is salty, jaded from yearly corporate “respect”\ntrainings, and not afraid to voice or show outward disinterest or disdain. If I showed up at a soundstage\nof tenured actors and crew wearing a suit, dressing “corporate,” quoting laws or court cases, or using\ntraditional “office based” examples in the material, I would lose my audience before I even began.\nI took inspiration from my earlier career at Disneyland/Walt Disney World, where we facilitated classes\nand training in the same manner Walt Disney entertained and educated so many over the years – by\nsimply telling a story. And interactively telling stories to storytellers is akin to speaking a language only\nthey can understand. By using relevant, tailored, and real-life stories or examples to bring the\ninformation to life, we transformed dreaded anti-harassment trainings into memorable, impactful\nsessions. This ideal – bringing educational concepts to life interactively through the power of story – is\nat the core of my teaching philosophy and instructional style.\nProudly, I had the honor of being the “conscience” (Head of ER/Employment Law) of the following\ncompanies: The Disneyland Resort, Darden Restaurants, NBC Entertainment, Netflix, CBS Television\nStudios, Universal Music Group, Sony Pictures Entertainment, and most recently, Roku. As an\naccomplished corporate attorney and leader, I like to prepare students for their next (or first) corporate,\nbusiness, or organizational roles by viewing and treating them the same way I lead and treat my direct\nreports at work. And just as I did as the company’s “conscience,” I ensure ethics, integrity, and\nprofessional responsibility concepts/examples are highlighted for my students throughout the course.\nAs this very moment, labor and employment law regulations and principles are experiencing a period of\nunique change. As an Adjunct Professor in this space, I would plan for the unexpected. Cases within\ncourse materials could be overturn, principles studied could be called into question by inconsistencies\nfrom state-to-state or agency-to-agency. It’s an exciting time to facilitate these discussions with\nstudents, as it reinforces that laws are neither static nor cemented in time. Well-settled laws or well-\naccepted concepts can – and will – change. Therefore, if/when “breaking news” impacts our studies, I\nwould love the flexibility to introduce current, real-time, and relevant materials, resources, or guest\nspeakers that can further reinforce the students’ understandings of what and why, should covered\nconcepts meaningfully evolve or change at any time throughout our class.\nSimply stated, I am excited about the chance to use my experience and expertise as a springboard for\nscholarly discussions and debate. I appreciate the consideration and hope to hear from you soon.\nSincerely,\n-- 5 of 22 --\n\nDarren S. Chiappetta\n-- 6 of 22 --\n\nDARREN S. CHIAPPETTA, ESQ.  REFERENCES 1\nDarren S. Chiappetta\nEMPLOYMENT ATTORNEY  GLOBAL ER & HR COMPLIANCE EXECUTIVE\nL O S A N G E L E S, C A • 4 0 7 . 4 2 1 . 4 8 5 8 • D S C H I A P P E T T A @ GM A I L . C O M • L I N KE D I N PR O FI L E\nACADEMIC\nREFERENCES \nDr. Fevzi Okumus CFHLA Preeminent Chair Professor, Hospitality Services\nUniversity of Central Florida\nRosen College of Hospitality Management\n9907 Universal Blvd, Orlando FL 32819\nFevzi.Okumus@ucf.edu\n407.903.8177\nMadeline Mercier Director, Employee Relations  Universal Music Group\n• Former Adjunct Professor, Entertainment and Tourism\nManagement  California State University, Fullerton\n• Current Adjunct Professor, Human Resources\nManagement  Concordia University – Irvine CA\n1900 E. Ocean Blvd #312\nLong Beach, CA 90802\nmerciermadeline32@gmail.com\n714.931.4456\nKatrina Lindsey Chief Legal Officer/General Counsel  Casey’s General Stores\n410 W. First Street\nAnkeny, IA 50023\nkatrina.lindsey@caseys.com\n515.446.6579\n-- 7 of 22 --\n\nThe Florida Bar\n651 East Jefferson Street\nTallahassee, FL 32399-2300\nJoshua E. Doyle\nExecutive Director\n850/561-5600\nwww.FLORIDABAR.org\nState of Florida )\nCounty of Leon ) In Re: 0015118\nDarren Scott Chiappetta\n853 N Detroit St\nLos Angeles, CA 90046-7607\nI CERTIFY THE FOLLOWING:\nI am the custodian of membership records of The Florida Bar.\nMembership records of The Florida Bar indicate that The Florida Bar member listed above was admitted to\npractice law in the state of Florida on .\tSeptember 27, 2005\nThe Florida Bar member above is an active member in good standing of The Florida Bar who is eligible to\npractice law in the state of Florida.\nDated this day of .\t27th November, 2024\nCynthia B. Jackson, CFO\nAdministration Division\nThe Florida Bar\nPG:R10\nCTM-318990\n-- 8 of 22 --\n\n\n-- 9 of 22 --\n\n\n-- 10 of 22 --\n\nHFT 4286: Hospitality Communications (Section 62)\nRosen College of Hospitality Management, University of Central Florida\nCOURSE SYLLABUS – SPRING 2009\nInstructor: Darren S. Chiappetta\nInstructor: Darren S. Chiappetta Term: Spring 2009\nOffice Hours: Following each class session, location TBD Class Meeting\nDays:\nMonday/Wednesday\nPhone: 407.828.2061 (W) Class Meeting\nHours:\n4:30 pm – 5:45 pm\nE-Mail: dschiappetta@yahoo.com Class Location: RSH 210\nI. Welcome!\nOne of the most important skills for today’s Hospitality leaders to possess is the ability to communicate – effectively,\ninclusively, and professionally. HFT 4286 is a highly interactive class that focuses on the four cornerstones of\ncommunication: Reading, Writing, Listening, and Speaking. Along the way, we will explore all of these aspects of\ncommunication with respect to leaders’ relationships and interactions with guests, employees, fellow co-workers,\nand various levels of management throughout an organization.\nII. University Course Catalog Description\nHFT 4286 Hospitality Communications: Communication exchanges in the hospitality industry for effective\npresentations, conflict resolution, and report writing. Emphasis on inter-departmental dependence by managers in\nhospitality enterprises in the areas of reading, writing, speaking, and listening.\nIII. Course Objectives\nBy the end of this course, students should be able to:\n1. Recognize the importance of active listening and develop heightened listening techniques\n2. IMPROVISE! Students will have the opportunity to watch and participate in improvisational activities.\n3. Provide coaching, counseling and feedback – even in situations that could be challenging or difficult.\n4. Understand the importance of diversity and inclusion in communication and how these strategies translate to\ntoday’s Hospitality organizations.\n5. Identity their own professional strengths, talents, and personality traits\n6. Develop and deliver spoken presentations\n7. Work as an inter-disciplinary team to develop action plans and draft written communication in order to\neffectively respond to real-world Hospitality issues.\n8. Fine tune resumes, cover letters, and interviewing skills\n-- 11 of 22 --\n\nIV. Course Prerequisites\nHFT4286 is a seminar course with limited enrollment. Please refer to the UCF Course Catalog for any official\nprerequisites.\nV. Course Credits\nHFT 4286 is a 3 credit-hour course\nVI. Required Texts and Materials\nREQUIRED TEXT: Strengths Finder 2.0, Tom Rath, Gallup Press, 2007. YOU WILL NEED TO PURCHASE A NEW COPY.\nThere is an individual exercise in the book, and each student will need their own personal access code in order to\ncomplete the assessment.\nVII. Supplementary (Optional) Texts and Materials\nEssentials of Business Communication, Seventh Edition, Mary Ellen Guffey, Thompson South-Western, 2007. While\nthis book is only recommended, it is a great resource and can be used as a reference manual for many types of base-\nline sample communication techniques, templates, and best-practices.\nVIII. Basis for Final Grade\nThe table below provides a snapshot of the assignments that will be due this semester and the accompanying\npercentage that each comprises your final grade.\nAssignments\nPercent of Final Grade\nClass Participation 20%\nHotel Group Memorandums 10%\nImprovisation Activity and Paper 10%\nPowerful Visual or Verbal Presentation 10%\nResume & Cover letter preparation 5%\nGuest Speaker Reflection/Impact Journal 5%\nIndustry Project 10%\nHotel Group Communication Presentation 15%\nFinal Exam 15%\nTOTAL PERCENTAGE 100%\nAll projects and exams will be graded by assigning point values equivalent to the percentage of values listed above. At the\nend of the term the points will be added and combined with the points earned from class participation and a final grade will\nbe assigned based upon the following scale:\nGrading Scale (%)\n94-100 A\n90-93 A-\n87-89 B+\n84-86 B\n80-83 B-\n77-79 C+\n-- 12 of 22 --\n\nGrading Scale (%)\n74-76 C\n70-73 C-\n67-69 D+\n64-66 D\n60-63 D-\n0 - 59 F\nIX. Grade Dissemination\nPapers and Journals will be graded using the following criteria:\n1. Does the paper contain the information requested?\n2. Does the paper flow in a logical sequence?\n3. Were proper grammar, spelling, syntax and structure used?\n4. Were non-internet sources used (if applicable)?\n5. Was there a section of the paper devoted to the group’s thoughts on the topic and on the research?\n6. Does the paper include a strong opening and a solid summary of the entire project?\nX. Course Policies: Student Expectations\nAttendance Policy/Class Participation: As an aspiring Hospitality leader, it is important to be present and actively\nengaged in all aspects of your professional – and academic – life. Consequently, attendance is mandatory, and\nparticipation in class is required , and essential, to stimulate learning. Because HFT 4286 is highly participatory,\n20% of students grades will be based upon class participation. Simply showing up for class is not enough to earn\nthe full 20%. Every student begins with 14 out of 20 points. Active participation will add to your points and\nabsences or little/no participation will subtract from the overall 20 points.\nProfessionalism Policy: Every time that we meet, appropriate professional behavior is expected. Remember,\nestablishing your professional network begins during your academic studies. The student next to you, behind you,\nor across the room from you may one day be your peer, your direct report, your leader, or even the HR\nprofessional deciding whether or not to hire you into an organization. Your professional “brand” will follow you\nthroughout your career. Make sure the perception that you create is the perception that you want others to\nremember.\nIn addition, per university policy and classroom etiquette, mobile phones, iPods, etc. must be silenced during all\nclassroom discussions, guest lectures, and class presentations. There is no need for LAPTOPS in this course;\ntherefore, laptops are not to be used during the course of normal class discussion. However, laptops will be\npermitted for groups that are presenting materials to the class (for the express purpose of delivering the class\npresentation).\nGroup Work Policy: Everyone must take part in a group project. All members of a group will receive the same\nscore; that is, the project is assessed and everyone receives this score. However, that number is only 90% of your\ngrade for this project. The final 10% is individual, and refers to your teamwork. Every person in the group will\nprovide the instructor with a suggested grade for every other member of the group, and the instructor will assign a\ngrade that is informed by those suggestions.\nExamination Policy: All students are required to take examinations at the date and time they are scheduled. No\nmakeup examinations will be given other than in cases of serious emergencies. Any makeup exams must be\napproved and scheduled by the Department Chair. Conflict with work schedules will not be accepted as a reason\n-- 13 of 22 --\n\nfor being unable to attend a scheduled examination period. Students arriving late to examinations will not be\nallowed to take the exam.\nAcademic Conduct Policy: Academic dishonesty in any form will not be tolerated. If you are uncertain as to what\nconstitutes academic dishonesty, please consult The Golden Rule, the University of Central Florida's Student\nHandbook (http://www.goldenrule.sdes.ucf.edu/) for further details.\nXI. Schedule\nDate Class Content Assignments Due\n1/7 W \nWelcome! First day of class – Setting the Stage and Course\nOverview\n1/12\nM\nImprovisation – Discussion and Importance\n1/14\nW\nListening: Discussion and Exercises Improv Activity Description DUE\nGroup Memo #1 ASSIGNED IN CLASS\n1/19\nM\nMartin Luther King Day (No Class)\n1/21\nW\nDiversity in Communication\nIMPROV ACTIVITY – TEAM #1\nTurn in Resume #1\n1/26\nM\nStrengths Finder: Process Assessment and Themes\nIMPROV ACTIVITY – TEAM #2\nComplete Strengths Finder Assessment before\nClass 