emos as well as intra-\ngroup correspondence, is due on April 27.\nIMPROVISATION ACTIVITY/PAPER (10%)\nWorking in teams of 2 or 3, you are responsible for finding an improvisational activity that can be facilitated to the\nclass on the group’s scheduled IMPROV ACTIVITY date (see calendar). All teams must submit a one-page\ndescription of their activity at the beginning of class on Wednesday January 14. Although improvisational activities\nmay be similar in nature, each team must have an original activity to present (subject to the instructor’s\ndiscretion).\nTeams must also write a 3-page research paper on why Improvisation techniques are important to teach to\nemployees in the Hospitality industry. The paper is due at the beginning of the class on Wednesday, February 4.\nPapers should be double-spaced, done in 12-point font, and following APA style. A minimum of 3 reference\nsources must be used (sources including Wikipedia and the dictionary will NOT be counted), including the\nreference for the activity that will be shared with the class. This assignment is worth 10% of your final grade – 5%\nfor the activity and 5% for the paper.\nPOWERFUL VISUAL OR VERBAL COMMUNICATION PRESENTATION (10%)\nYou will be required to do an individual presentation on either (1) a speech that was powerful to you (powerful\nverbal communication) OR (2) personal examples of visual communication that was effective and visual\ncommunication that was not effective (powerful visual communication). For the powerful verbal communication\noption, choose a speaker or speech that was motivating to you and discuss what you found moving or powerful\nabout the speech/speaker (Students may not use the MLK “I Have a Dream” speech or JFK’s “Ask Not…” speech).\nFor option two, the examples of effective/non-effective visual communications should be individual to you and\ndrawn from experiences in your personal life (such as your observations at a hotel, restaurant, career fair, exhibit,\netc…)\nPresentations to the class will be for five (5) minutes. You will be penalized for ending your discussion in less than\n4.5 minutes, and you will be cut off after 5.5 minutes – so practice is definitely essential to a successful\npresentation! Your presentation will be videotaped, and you will evaluate your performance and turn in that\n-- 16 of 22 --\n\nevaluation before you receive your grade. Therefore, you will need to provide a VHS tape for this purpose. The\nuse of PowerPoint or any other visual aids should be kept to a minimum. Professional dress and demeanor is\nexpected of each presenter. This presentation amounts to 10% of your total grade.\nGUEST SPEAKER REFLECTION/IMPACT JOURNAL (5%)\nThroughout the semester, you will have the opportunity to listen to several guest lecturers talk to the class about\nspecific topics in hospitality communications. Following each guest speaker session, students will be required to\nwrite a one-page reflection journal (minimum of 250 words), professionally prepared, on the impact of the guest\nspeaker’s discussion. Essentially, you should REFLECT on what the speaker said and discuss its IMPACT on you.\nWhat was the main topic(s) the speaker covered? What will you remember about the discussion? How will you use\nthe speaker’s information/advice in relation to your work experience? How will you use the information/advice in\nthe future? Make sure to list the 3 MOST IMPORTANT THINGS that you learned from listening to the specific\nspeaker. The Reflection/Impact Journals are worth a combined total of 5% of your grade.\nRESUME/COVER LETTER PREPARATION (5%)\nAn important part of communicating effectively is the ability to communicate pertinent information about yourself\nin concise and strategic ways, such as the information conveyed on a resume and cover letter for a potential\nemployer. Each student will turn in 3 versions of their resume. Each version will be reviewed and returned with\ncomments. The third (and final) version of the resume also needs to be accompanied by a cover letter that is\ntailored to a specific job with an actual employer. Students are expected to use the newspaper, online sources\n(careerbuilder.com, hcareers.com, employer’s career websites, etc.) the Rosen College Placement Office, or any\nother job placement source to craft a letter of application transmitting resumes to them for a management\nposition. Include a copy of the advertisement for the position with your final resume and cover.\nEach student should have a two-pocket folder with your name and PID on the front cover. You will turn in each\nversion of your resume in the folder and the final resume/cover letter will be returned with your grade in the\nfolder. This assignment is worth 5% of your final grade. Although the individual assignments will not be graded,\nnot meeting the deadlines and not improving your resume over the semester will detract from the 5%.\nCOMMUNICATIONS PROJECT & PRESENTATION (15%)\nEach “Hotel Group” will be required to do a group presentation on the topic of your choice (see list below for some\ntopic ideas that you might want to consider). The topic should either be (1) an overview of a real-world\ncommunication issue or topic from a workplace (but DIFFERENT from the Industry Project). It should be a\nhospitality business-related topic created specifically for HFT 4286; OR (2) an overview/discussion of the\ncommunication concepts, strategies, and best-practices of a Hospitality or Entertainment organization. Every\nmember of the group must contribute to the project, and every member of the group must present a portion of\nthe information to the class.\nPresentations to the class will be for fifteen (15) minutes. You will be penalized for ending your presentation in\nless than 14 minutes, and you will be cut off after 16 minutes – so, again, practice is essential! Your presentation\nwill be videotaped and you will evaluate your performance (as a group) and turn in that evaluation before you\nreceive your grade. You will need to provide a VHS tape for this purpose. Keep the use of PowerPoint and visual\naids to a tasteful moderation – do not allow your visual aids to “upstage” you or detract too much attention from\nyour message. Professional dress and demeanor is required for all presenters.\nTopics must be selected NO LATER than February 9. See Darren to sign-up for your topic. Each group must cover a\ndifferent topic or organization, so sign-up early for a better chance of obtaining your group’s first choice.\nGeneral Topics to Consider:\n- The impact of Diversity & Inclusion on communications\n- Designing and Communication a Recognition program\n- Challenges associated with electronic communications in an organization\n- Listening\n-- 17 of 22 --\n\n- Terminating an individual’s employment\n- Conducting a daily or pre/post shift meeting with a team of employees\n- Communicating immediate and appropriate “service recovery” to guests in difficult guest situations\n- Performance Management\nINDUSTRY PROJECT (15%)\nDuring the semester you need to identify a real world project that is associated with the purpose of this class and\nsolve this communication challenge at your job or for a future employer. Once you have found the hospitality\ncommunication problem to improve, develop a proposal and timeline for success. Create materials to support\nyour effort, work with your management team (at work) for implementation, and not the effectiveness of your\napproach. You may do this project as an individual OR work with one other person in the class. Topics and teams\nare subject to the discretion and approval of the instructor. Please note the calendar for deadlines to receive both\nteam and topic approval. Set up times with me as soon as possible to discuss your ideas.\nProcess:\n1. Meet with your manager at work to determine your project or develop a concept of your\nown.\n2. Prepare a written proposal and timeline.\n3. Meet with Darren to review your pr