41	67	cketter-pjmlaw-com_christian_5656434 - Copy.pdf	\N	C H R I S T I A N K E T T E R\n(773) 383-4089 | cketter@pjmlaw.com\nJanuary 3, 2025\nDean Robert Ahdieh\nTexas A&M University School of Law\n1515 Commerce Street, Fort Worth, TX 76102\nDear Dean Ahdieh:\nI am writing in application of the position of Non-Tenure: Adjunct Professor of Law to teach remote\ncoursework in subjects of constitutional theory, administrative law, criminal procedure, civil procedure, or\nlegal writing. Legal education is a passion of mine and has remained a fixture of my career. My teaching\nexperience, my ongoing legal scholarship, and my own continuing education as a practicing lawyer allow\nfor me to be an accessible and pragmatic instructor to students. My work in private practice demonstrates\npractical applications before state and federal trial courts and appellate courts as well as the Illinois Supreme\nCourt. And my publications reflect my serious commitment to academics, teaching, and researc h. Most\nrelevantly, they demonstrate a necessary background in constitutional theory and administrative law.\nI am able to communicate a clear understanding of legal writing and its application to core legal principles—\nwith active practice in constitutional law, tort law, criminal law, contract law, and administrative law. I\nbegan my career as a prosecutor in Illinois, after having served as a judicial intern on the U.S. Court of\nAppeals for the Seventh Circuit to Judge William J. Bauer. From there, I went into private practice as a\nlitigator, defending matters involving federal civil rights, personal injury, municipal law, and commercial\nlitigation.\nI began my teaching career in Chicago, Illinois at Morton College—teaching criminal procedure to\nundergraduate students. As a result, I know how to make complicated legal material tangible and\nunderstandable—even to nonlawyers. Presently, I am on faculty at University of Illinois at Chicago School\nof Law. I teach a course on Academic Skills, covering a wide array of legal topics and case brief driven\ncoursework. I am also a member of the American Association of University Professors. In private practice,\nI work as an attorney in commercial litigation and appellate work with Peterson, Johnson & Murray LLC\nand administrative law and TCPA litigation with Gonzales Taplin P.A. Currently, I am part of a litigation\nteam in the Eastern District of Texas, actively navigating new administrative waters following Chevron’s\noverturn. I find scholarly publication to be the most fulfilling form of continuing education and regularly\nwrite for journals and law reviews nationwide. Proudly, I have an upcoming article with Journal of Law &\nCivil Governance at Texas A&M, focused upon constitutional theory, principles of the legal profession, and\nrecurring themes stemming from the Founding. Among my volunteer work, I serve as: the Vice-Chair for\nthe Illinois State Bar Association’s Federal Practice Section; Associate General Counsel to the DuPage\nCounty Bar Association; as Editor-in-Chief for the Bar Association’s Journal, the DCBA Brief; and as the\nSponsorship Committee Co-Chair for the Appellate Lawyer’s Association.\nMy skills and resources allow me to effectively and successfully teach coursework as an adjunct professor\non constitutional theory, administrative law, legal writing, and civil or criminal procedure. Enclosed please\nfind my curriculum vitae. I would appreciate the opportunity to meet with you to discuss the possibility of\nemployment at Texas A&M University School of Law. Thank you for your time and consideration.\nSincerely,\nChristian Ketter\n-- 1 of 13 --\n\nC H R I S T I A N K E T T E R\nAttorney At Law | Adjunct Professor of Law\nEXPERIENCE____ Licensed to practice: Illinois and Michigan\nUniversity of Illinois Chicago School of Law Adjunct Professor of Law (2022-Present)\n• Instructing students and maintaining lesson plans on academic success for SCALES program.\nPeterson, Johnso