w to bring those principles into practical real-world practice. The law is no different.\nIn my teaching, I focus on imparting the fundamental aspects of the law—whether it’s Blackstone,\nSir Edward Coke, the Federalist Papers, the text of the U.S. Constitution, or landmark cases like\nMarbury v. Madison. However, I believe that the key to truly understanding the law lies in\nproviding students with greater context. While I support the use of case briefing as an instructional\ntool, I emphasize that any capable law student can read a textbook to grasp legal principles. To\nmake the material come alive, students must see how individual cases fit into a broader historical\nand judicial context. This requires more than just understanding the holding of a decision—it\ninvolves understanding the reasoning and the context.\nFor example, students should consider the year of a decision, the historical backdrop, and the\ncourt’s goals. The failure to guide a student to consider this context is a failure in teaching. By\nconnecting cases and themes, I help students see how various areas of law—whether property,\ntorts, criminal law, or constitutional law—are intertwined. This larger perspective sparks curiosity\nand critical thinking, encouraging students to draw connections and think more deeply for\nthemselves as they leave the classroom and venture to the courtroom.\nThe classroom should be a space where students feel comfortable asking questions and challenging\nlegal thinking. I want my students’ questions to lead each class to better explanations, and I believe\nthat if one student has a question, others likely do as well. I strive to establish clear expectations\nwithout overburdening students with unnecessary rules. In law, however, deadlines and procedural\nrules can have significant consequences—affecting jurisdiction, determining case outcomes, or\neven deciding the course of a legal argument. I make it clear that in law school, as in practice, the\ndetails matter. Careful reading and attention to deadlines are essential skills for the legal\nprofession.\nMy growth as an educator is propelled by my ongoing scholarship and practical application. I see\nthe law as an evolving field—grounded in well-settled principles but always adapting to new\nchallenges and contexts. My long-term vision as an instructor is to equip students with the tools to\nunderstand legal history while preparing them for the ever-changing future of the profession. At\nthe same time, I want to ensure that students retain their intellectual freedom—thinking critically\nand developing, but continually testing, their own conclusions as they engage with the law.\nIn my approach to teaching law, whether the course is focused on administrative law, constitutional\ntheory, or criminal and civil procedure, I prioritize starting with the rules and governing principles,\nas well as straightforward defined concepts. A strong foundation in these principles is crucial for\nstudents to understand the broader concepts of the law. My goal is in creating a syllabus is that the\n-- 7 of 13 --\n\nmaterial must be structured in a logical, progressive way, moving from fundamental concepts to\nmore complex applications. By organizing the content in this manner, students can better\ncomprehend the relationship between ideas and see how legal doctrines evolve over time.\nAn essential part of my teaching strategy is to help students see the value in reading cases that\nillustrate the development, refinement, and sometimes eventual overturning of legal doctrines.\nOften, students may initially struggle with the dense, intricate case law that can seem to lead\nnowhere once it is overturned. However, I stress the importance of a lineage of cases, where\nstudents learn that it is not merely about memorizing rules but understanding how courts build and\nrefine doctrines over time. By reading cases, students are exposed to the evolution of legal thought,\nlearning why certain rulings were made, how those rulings were challenged, and why they were\nultimately reconsidered or overturned. This process teaches students how to advocate for reasoned\nand workable outcomes in their own legal analyses and arguments.\nI believe that the final assignments in a course should challenge students to integrate the concepts\nthey have studied and apply them in practical, real-world contexts. Through assignments that\nrequire students to synthesize the material, I encourage them to think critically about the\napplication of legal doctrines and the arguments behind them. This not only reinforces their\nunderstanding of the law but also teaches them how to advocate for their position using logical,\nwell-supported reasoning.\nThrough this method of instruction, I aim to equip students with the tools they need to succeed\nboth in their academic studies and in their future careers as legal practitioners. They leave my\nclassroom not only with knowledge of the law but with the ability to reason through complex legal\nissues and effectively advocate for justice.\n-- 8 of 13 --\n\nC H R I S T I A N K E T T E R\n(773) 383-4089 | cketter@me.com\nReferences\n1. Samuel V. Jones\nAssistant Dean: University of Illinois at Chicago School of Law\n315 S. Plymouth Court\nChicago, Illinois 60604\n312.427.2737 ext. 866\nsvjones@uic.edu\no Present supervisor at UIC Law.\no Employed research assistant to Samuel V. Jones: January 2017 -December 2018.\no Credited research in Police, Heroes, and Child Trafficking: Who Cries When Her\nAttacker Wears Blue?– Jones, Samuel V. NEVADA LAW JOURNAL: Vol. 18: Iss. 3, Art. 9\no Courses in criminal law and contract law, January 2016-December 2016, earning an\naward for Highest Grade Earned in Criminal Law (December 2016).\no Served as teaching assistant for contract law January 2017-January 2018.\n2. Kaleah M. Ault\nAttorney at Law: Hervas, Condon & Bersani, P.C.\n333 Pierce Road Suite 195\nItasca, IL 60143\n(785) 424-4989\nkault@hcbattorneys.com\n