ck trial all four years, and enrolled\nin all law-related classes available, including Criminal Law and Criminology. Upon entering law\nschool, I took all classes offered in the area of Criminal Law and Procedure, and was a student\nattorney in the General Practice Clinic. I participated in Moot Court and was a member of the Trial\nTeam. I also obtained an internship at a criminal defense firm the summer between my 1L and 2L\nyear, and continued working there until I graduated in 2008.\nUpon my admission to the Bar in 2008, I immediately began representing indigent defendants\nappointed to me by the Court with the firm at which I had interned during law school. After my\nson was born, I was offered a position in Maine’s busiest prosecutor’s office. For an assortment of\npersonal reasons, as well as an interest in utilizing my already established sense of justice in a\nprosecutorial role, I “switched sides” in January 2016.\nIn my position as a prosecutor, I created trainings for law enforcement on the law and procedure as\nit pertains to them and the cases they present to the DA’s office, which starts the formal criminal\n-- 1 of 12 --\n\nlitigation process. I also created a three-hour “courtroom testimony” training, that was presented at\nmultiple departments and at the Maine Criminal Justice Academy. I also was the “go-to” person in\nthis DA’s office regarding questions about procedure rules and deadlines throughout the life of a\ncase.\nIn addition to my practical experience in the criminal law field, I am also currently an adjunct\nprofessor at Maine Law, serving in the capacity as Trial Team coach. I have had the honor of\nworking with 2L and 3L students each year from November to February, doing an intensive dive\ninto the world of trial advocacy. My experience teaching the trial team is something that I treasure.\nBeing able to pass on the knowledge and experience I have regarding courtroom advocacy has been\na great honor, and one I hope to continue for many years. To have the opportunity to teach\nstudents in that practice area and/or in the criminal law academic subject area would not only fulfill\nme professionally, but also benefit the students as future practitioners.\nAs I have outlined, to be employed as an Adjunct Professor at your School of Law would add to\nmy experience and provide me with an opportunity to apply my unique set of skills, high level of\nprofessionalism, and love of these subject areas to the benefit of the students and school. You will\nlearn from my resume, and any reference calls you should make, that I have been entrusted early\nand often in numerous leadership positions. My background includes positions with varied\nassignments and vast responsibility, in both independent and collaborative environments. My\nhistory of performance, teamwork, and professional etiquette already blend nicely at Maine Law in\nmy current adjunct role, and transitioning these attributes at Texas A&M School of Law would\nguarantee that I am a valued team member and trusted employee.\nI believe that both my work and academic experience has given me the skills necessary to be an\neffective and memorable trial practice, criminal law, or criminal procedure professor. If selected to\nbe an adjunct for these practice areas, I will apply all my enthusiasm, experience, and work ethic,\nto the role. I welcome the opportunity to discuss my qualifications with you.\nThank you for your time and consideration. I look forward to speaking with you in the near future.\nSincerely,\nAmanda J. Doherty\n-- 2 of 12 --\n\nAMANDA J. DOHERTY ESQ.\n7 Abigail Way| Scarborough, Maine 04074| (917) 533-2615 | DohertyEsq@aol.com\nED U C A T I O N\nUniversity of Maine School of Law, Portland, ME\nJuris Doctor; May 2008\n Moot Court (Co-Chair); Trial Advocacy Team (2008 National Trial Competition Regional Finalist)\n Recipient: Gignoux Award for Appellate Advocacy\nCertificate in Compliance; May 2021\n Maine Law sponsored attendee\nFordham U