on for criminal law started at a fairly young age and is intertwined with my\nlove of courtroom advocacy. I first wanted to be a trial attorney when I was ten-years old, when\nmy social studies class did a mock trial to assist in learning about the Judicial Branch (it was a\ncriminal trial related to the Jack and the Beanstalk story). In high school, I attended the National\nStudent Leadership Conference for Law and Advocacy, spending two-weeks learning and\nperforming mock trial exercises, culminating in a final trial. Upon my return from that conference,\nI assisted in creating a mock trial program at my high school, and led this team with success at the\ncity, county, and state levels. In college, I participated in mock trial all four years, serving as\nCaptain for three of those years, and making it to the National competition one year. My\nsophomore year I took an undergraduate Philosophy class, taught by a lawyer, titled “A Theory of\nJustice” and it was a discussion in that class that narrowed my career path to want to be a criminal\ndefense attorney. I enrolled in all law-related classes available (including Criminal Law and\nCriminology) and wrote my senior thesis on the evolution of the insanity defense. Upon entering\nlaw school, I took all classes offered in the area of Criminal Law (Criminal Law, Criminal\nProcedure-Investigation, Criminal Procedure-Adjudication, Juvenile Justice, and a Battered\nWomen & the Law). I also joined the Moot Court Board as a 2L, offering guidance to 1L students\nengaging in their first moot court exercise, and then competing at the Craven Competition on\nConstitutional Law as a 3L. I was a member of the Trial Competition Team, placing third at our\nRegional Tournament for the National Trial Competition. I also was a student attorney in Maine\nLaw’s Legal Aid Clinic. Upon graduation I was awarded the Gignoux Award for Appellate\nAdvocacy. Outside of the classroom, I also obtained an internship at a criminal defense firm the\nsummer between my 1L and 2L year, and continued working there until I graduated in 2008, and\nwas offered a full-time attorney position at that same firm.\nAs my resume and cover letter attested, I have been an adjunct professor at Maine Law, serving in\nthe capacity as Trial Team Coach for over a decade. My teaching philosophy at present, that would\ncarry over to any adjunct position that I may be offered at Texas A&M School of Law, is\n-- 6 of 12 --\n\nstraightforward. We start with the fundamentals of the subject area, and then build on that\nfoundation to the more complex areas, with regular feedback and evaluations of the knowledge and\ncomprehension. Specifically, we spend the first month working on the procedural components –\ntrial structure, rules of evidence, objections, evidentiary admission process, procedural rules, etc.\nThen we apply all of that to the fact pattern and turn it into courtroom advocacy for the February\ncompetition. I believe that it is important to not only explain what is done in practice, but why it is\ndone, and how to argue points effectively. Both criminal law and procedure, as well as trial\npractice, requires an overlap understanding of the Rules of Evidence and Constitutional principles,\nwhich are interspersed in my lessons.\nOne of the primary things I want students to leave my classes understanding is that the criminal\njustice system is not just about the extreme view of prosecution versus defense -- prison versus\ndismissals. It is about understanding the required criminal procedure starting at the investigatory\nstage and carrying on through the adjudication phase, in light of the Constitutional directives\nguiding law enforcement and prosecutors, to ensure the rights of all defendants. The goal of the\ncriminal justice system should be one in which we recognize the necessity of punishment for\nwrongdoings, but do not diminish the rehabilitative nature of sentencing to lower recidivism that is\noften distinctive to each defendant.\nThe other most significant principle that I want my students to grasp, is the importance of\ncourtroom fundamentals. Anyone can read a book or a case. But only some can truly take the\ncontent of the information they have reviewed and turn it into a case theory, and advocate at every\nstage of the process of the side they are hired or assigned to represent. In the trial setting, being\nable to know what happens at each procedural stage, and be able to do so confidently and correctly,\nno matter the fact pattern, is a true skill. Some comes from natural abilities related to public\nspeaking, but the rest of it is understanding the how and why, and repetitive hard work.\nI look forward to speaking with you in consideration of employment with your law school and am\nhappy to address my teaching philosophy further.\nSincerely,\nAmanda J. Doherty\n-- 7 of 12 --\n\nAMANDA J. DOHERTY ESQ.\n7 Abigail Way| Scarborough, Maine 04074| (917) 533-2615 | DohertyEsq@aol.com\nREFERENCES\n1. Kevin Moynihan, Esq.\nTrial Attorney\nRichardson, Whitman, Large, and Badger\n207-604-8164\n2. Heather Gonzales, Esq.\nAssistant Federal Defender\nDistrict of Maine\n207-439-4502\n3. Stephen Shea, Esq.\nAdjunct Professor, Maine Law\nTrial Attorney, Shea Law Office\n207-205-5037\n-- 8 of 12 --\n\nApplication Forms\nFoster Child Form\nFoster Child\nI was not a foster child\n-- 9 of 12 --\n\nVeteran Status/Identification Form\nVoluntary Self-Identification of Veteran Status\nI do not identify as a veteran\nSurviving Spouse of a Veteran\nI am not a surviving spouse of a veteran\nOrphan of a Veteran\nI am not an orphan of a veteran\n-- 10 of 12 --\n\nClery Act\nAcknowledgement:\nI acknowledge that I have received the above information regarding the Clery Act\n-- 11 of 12 --\n\nNotice of Non-Discrimination\nAcknowledgement:\nI acknowledge that I have received the information above regarding notice of non-discrimination and abuse\n-- 12 of 12 --\n\n	2025-10-12 01:08:38.007325+00	[-0.01422382