48	74	foley_jordan_5707608.pdf	\N	Jordan J. Foley, LCDR, U.S. Navy, Judge Advocate General’s Corps\n(724) 355-2891 | jjf99@georgetown.edu\nHiring Committee\nTexas A&M University, School of Law\n1515 Commerce Street\nFort Worth, TX 76102\nSubject: Application for Adjunct Professor of Law Position\nDear Hiring Committee,\nI am writing to express my interest in the Adjunct Professor of Law position at Texas A&M\nUniversity School of Law. With a robust background in national security law, international law,\ntechnology policy, and military legal operations, I am eager to contribute my expertise to the\nuniversity’s esteemed law program and mentor the next generation of legal professionals.\nAs a Judge Advocate in the U.S. Navy, I have advised senior decision-makers on complex issues\ninvolving national security law, the law of armed conflict, emerging technology regulations, and\ninternational legal frameworks. My tenure as the Pentagon’s Operational Law Branch Head\nprovided me with invaluable experience in legal policy development, compliance assessments\nfor advanced weapon systems, and strategic engagements with allied nations. Additionally, my\nacademic credentials—including a Juris Doctor from Georgetown University Law Center, a\nMaster of Arts in Defense and Strategic Studies from the Naval War College, and dual Master of\nScience degrees from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology—have given me a\ncomprehensive legal and policy foundation that aligns with the rigorous academic standards of\nTexas A&M University School of Law.\nI am particularly interested in teaching courses related to National Security Law, International\nLaw, Technology and the Law, and Military Justice. My experience working at the intersection\nof law and technology, including expertise in artificial intelligence and space law, would allow\nme to offer students a forward-looking perspective on emerging legal challenges. Additionally,\nmy commitment to fostering analytical thinking and ethical leadership in legal education aligns\nwith Texas A&M’s dedication to academic excellence and practical training.\nBeyond teaching, I am passionate about mentoring students and guiding them in their career\ndevelopment. I have a strong record of leadership, having served as an advisor to military\nofficers, policymakers, and legal professionals. I look forward to bringing this mentorship\nmindset into the classroom, providing students with the critical skills necessary to navigate the\nevolving legal landscape. I would welcome the opportunity to discuss how my experience and\nexpertise can enhance Texas A&M University School of Law’s curriculum. Thank you for your\ntime and consideration—I look forward to the possibility of contributing to your esteemed\ninstitution.\nSincerely,\nJordan J. Foley, LCDR, U.S. Navy\n-- 1 of 10 --\n\nJordan “JJ” Foley\nLieutenant Commander, U.S. Navy, Judge Advocate General’s Corps\n(724) 355-2891 | jjf99@georgetown.edu | LinkedIn Profile\nJ.D. M.S. M.A. B.S. | Maryland State Bar Member | TS//SCI | Mandarin Chinese\nLCDR Jordan “JJ” Foley is the Department of Defense Fellow to Senator Mazie K.\nHirono (D-Hawaii). He most recently served as the Pentagon’s Operational Law\nBranch Head at the Office of the Judge Advocate General International and\nOperational Law Division. Foley holds dual warfare qualifications in Submarine\nWarfare (Officer) and the Navy Space Cadre. Foley graduated with distinction and\nfirst overall for Military Order of Merit from the U.S. Naval Academy in 2012 where\nhe earned a Bachelor of Science in Chinese and served as Brigade Commander. At\nthe U.S. Naval Academy, Foley served on a student-exchange program for eight months in Beijing, China at Capital\nNormal University. Foley was selected for the Immediate Graduate Education Program and earned a dual Master\nof Science degree in Political Science (Technology Policy) and Space Systems Operations from the Massachusetts\nInstitute of Technology while serving as Naval Liaison to Lincoln Laboratory’s Space Systems Analysis Group. In\n2014, Foley attended Beijing University of Aeronautics and Astronautics as part of a research fellowship. His\ngraduate thesis focused on the Chinese space program political economy where he provided the only English\ntranslations of thousands of pages of Chinese text. During this tour, Foley fully qualified as a Space Cadre\nOperations Officer. Following graduate school, Foley completed the Advanced Naval Nuclear Power Course in\nCharleston, SC and was assigned to the USS Annapolis (SSN 760) in 2015 where he earned his “dolphins” and\nfully qualified as a Submarine Officer. He earned his Sea Service Deployment ribbon while serving as the\nAnnapolis’ Communications Officer in the Pacific Theater. In 2018, Foley was selected for the Law Education\nProgram and graduated from Georgetown University Law Center in 2021 as a Global Law Scholar with a focus on\nChinese Comparative Law. After graduating from Naval Justice School, Foley served as an initial tour judge\nadvocate at Region Legal Service Office Southeast Detachment Pensacola. In 2022, Foley completed a Master of\nArts from the Naval War College in National Security Studies with an Asia Pacific focus as part of his Joint\nProfessional Military Education.\nGEORGETOWN UNIVERSITY LAW CENTER Washington, DC\n▪ J.D. | Juris Doctorate May 2021\nAwards: International Academy of Trial Lawyers Award for excellence in the art of advocacy\nActivities: Class President of Global Law Scholars | National Security & the Law Honors Program\nMASSACHUSETTS INSTITUTE OF TECHNOLOGY Cambridge, MA\n▪ M.S. & M.S. | Masters of Science in Political Science & Technology Policy June 2014\nNAVAL WAR COLLEGE Newport, RI\n▪ M.A. | Master of Arts in Defense and Strategic Studies (Asia Pacific) June 2022\nUNITED STATES NAVAL ACADEMY Annapolis, MD\n▪ B.S. | Bachelor of Science in Mandarin Chinese May 2012\nAwards: Valedictorian (1 of 1,135) for Military Order of Merit\nActivities: Brigade Commander (Spring 2012)\nLEGAL EXPERIENCE\nSECRETARY OF THE NAVY, OFFICE OF LEGISLATIVE AFFAIRS Washington, DC\n▪ Legislative Fellow (Sen. Maizie Hirono (D-HI)) November 2024 – Present\nLiaison Affairs & Strategic Counsel | Selected as one of 22 Naval Officers to serve as a military liaison on a high-\nprofile Senate staff. Directly advised the Senator on Armed Services Committee hearings by drafting memorandums\nand policy documents, and authoring public statements on her behalf.\nEDUCATION\n-- 2 of 10 --\n\nU.S. NAVY, JUDGE ADVOCATE GENERAL’S CORPS Pentagon, DC\n▪ National Security & International Law Attorney July 2023 – November 2024\nForeign Affairs & Strategic Counsel | Responsible for the Navy’s pre-fielding reviews of complex weapons systems\nincluding those using advanced autonomy and artificial intelligence. Coordinated and executed multiple key leader\nengagements. Developed lasting relationships with Allied and partner nations. Planned talking points, deliverables,\nand after-action reports for the Judge Advocate General of the Navy.\nU.S. NAVY, JUDGE ADVOCATE GENERAL’S CORPS Naval Air Station Pensacola, FL\n▪ Staff Attorney August 2021 – July 2023\nOversight & Ethics | Advised executive level decision makers at three Naval Installations in charge of over 6,000\npersonnel on issues related to government ethics, administrative procedures, organizational policies, consequential\npersonnel decisions, contracts, and community engagement.\nMILITARY OPERATIONAL EXPERIENCE\nU.S. NAVY, SUBMARINE OFFICER Naval Base Point Loma, CA | Portsmouth Naval Shipyard, ME\n▪ Division Officer July 2014 – May 2018\nDeployment & Operational Experience | Served as Communications Officer and Reactor Control Assistant leading\ntwo divisions totaling 45 Sailors in all aspects of submarine operations from supervising the reactor plant to running\nthe ship both in-port and at-sea. Coordinated a change of homeport via Panama Canal transit with zero incidences.\nIn shipyard construction, served as the Quality Assurance Officer during a major engineering overhaul.\nU.S. NAVY, SPACE CADRE Hanscom Air Force Base, MA\n▪ Naval Liaison and Space Operations Officer July 2012 – July 2014\nOperational Experience & Liaison Affairs | Served as a Department of Defense representative in a 100-person\ndivision advising the Senior Executive Service Director of Lincoln Laboratory’s Space Systems Analysis Group.\nSpecialized in space operations “red teaming” by simulating adversarial People’s Republic of China offensive and\ndefensive space capabilities.\nU.S. NAVY, PERSONNEL EXCHANGE PROGRAM Dalian Navy Base, People’s Republic of China\n▪ Exchange Naval Officer | People’s Liberation Army Navy June 2012\nForeign Affairs | Selected for a high-visibility officer exchange program with the People’s Liberation Army Navy.\nCOMMUNITY LEADERSHIP EXPERIENCE\nLET’S CHOW | ROBERT IRVINE FOUNDATION’S FOOD TRUCK PROGRAM National Nonprofit\n▪ Founder January 2020 – Present\nLeadership & Fundraising | Founded a nonprofit providing services in culinary education and business management\nfor military veterans through food truck training. Raised over $1 million to support purchase of six food trucks\nnationally assisting over 40 veteran owned businesses.\nFREDERICK COUNTY PUBLIC SCHOOLS BOARD OF EDUCATION Frederick, MD\n▪ Ethics Panel Member June 2024 – Present\nOversight & Ethics | Appointed by the President of the Board of Education to serve a three-year term advising the\nBoard on ethics issues and maintain public trust as an oversight mechanism.\nMAYOR-ELECT TRANSITION TEAM Pensacola, FL\n▪ Staff Member September 2022 – January 2023\nLeadership | Selected by the Pensacola Mayor-Elect to lead the public safety and military-community affairs teams.\nANNE ARUNDEL COMMUNITY COLLEGE BOARD OF TRUSTEES Arnold, MD\n▪ Board Member July 2021 – July 2022\nOversight & Ethics | Appointed by the Governor of Maryland to serve a one-year term exercising fiscal and\nadministrative oversight to ensure the college meets its mission, goals, and provides the best educational\nopportunities for all students.\n-- 3 of 10 --\n\nPUBLICATIONS\n▪ “Multi-Domain Legal Warfare: China’s Coordinated Attack on International Rule of Law,” Lieber Institute –\nWest Point - Articles of War, May 28, 2024 (link)\n▪ “China’s Authoritarian Grip: How China Reinforces Social Control, Cultivates a Climate of Fear, and\nMinimizes Dissent,” Journal of Indo-Pacific Affairs, Vol. 6, No. 8 (Nov–Dec 2023), Nov 15, 2023 (link)\n▪ Chemistry Kids, Jordan J. Foley (Author), Laura Baer (Illustrator), April 3, 2023 (link)\n▪ “The Supreme Court Should End Male-Only Selective Service Registration,” USNI Proceedings Magazine,\nMay 19, 2021 (link)\n▪ “Orbital Dynamics for National Security Lawyers,” Space Education & Strategic Applications, Feb 2021 (link)\n▪ “Strategy for International Cooperation in Planning the Chinese Space Station,” MIT Press, May 1, 2014 (link)\nPROFESSIONAL CERTIFICATES & QUALIFICATIONS\nU.S. NAVY | Legislative Affairs Qualification January 2026\n▪ Earned subject matter expertise in legislative affairs demonstrating an understanding of Congress and the\nNational Defense Authorization Act process.\nU.S. NAVY | International Law Attorney Qualification June 2021\n▪ Earned subject matter expertise in national security and international law demonstrating the ability to advise\nDepartment of Defense decision makers on international and domestic authorities related to military\noperations.\nANNE ARUNDEL COMMUNITY COLLEGE | Certificates in Culinary Arts & Entrepreneurship June 2022\n▪ Completed 40 credit hours in hospitality industry operations, restaurant management, baking techniques,\naccounting, sales, marketing, and entrepreneurial skills.\nUNIFORM CODE OF MILITARY JUSTICE | Judge Advocate December 2021\n▪ Admitted to practice law under Article 27(b) of the UCMJ in Military and some Federal Courts.\nMARYLAND STATE BAR ASSOCIATION | Attorney & Counsellor December 2021\n▪ Admitted to the Maryland State Bar Association and licensed to practice law in the State of Maryland.\nU.S. NAVY | East Asia & Indo-Pacific Qualification June 2021\n▪ Earned subject matter expertise designation by completing levels of education, training, experience, and\ndemonstrated language ability (Mandarin Chinese) with a focus on East Asia.\nU.S. NAVY | Submarine Warfare (Officer) Qualification October 2017\n▪ Qualified to meet the high standards and special requirements of submarine duty to include ship driving,\nnuclear reactor operations, and leadership responsibilities.\nU.S. NAVY | Space Cadre Operations (Levels VS5 & VS6) Qualification June 2014 & August 2023\n▪ Earned subject matter expertise designation for completing a high level of education, training, and\nexperience integrating space capabilities.\n-- 4 of 10 --\n\nPersonal Statement – Teaching Philosophy and Plans\nJordan J. Foley, LCDR, U.S. Navy, Judge Advocate General’s Corps\nThroughout my career as a naval officer, attorney, and educator, I have embraced the philosophy\nthat education is not just about knowledge acquisition but about fostering critical thinking,\nethical leadership, and a commitment to lifelong learning. I believe that the best educators do\nmore than deliver information—they inspire curiosity, encourage diverse perspectives, and\nchallenge students to engage deeply with complex subjects.\nMy approach to teaching is shaped by my diverse experiences in the military, law, and\ninternational affairs. As an instructor, I strive to create an interactive and dynamic learning\nenvironment where students are encouraged to question assumptions, analyze real-world\nscenarios, and develop solutions to pressing legal and policy issues. Drawing on my background\nin international law, national security, and technology policy, I aim to connect theoretical\nknowledge with practical applications, ensuring that students are prepared to navigate the\ncomplexities of an evolving global landscape.\nA core component of my teaching philosophy is mentorship. Having served in leadership roles\nacross military, legal, and academic settings, I understand the transformative impact of a\ndedicated mentor. I am committed to guiding students not only in their academic pursuits but\nalso in their professional development. Whether through advising on research projects, offering\ncareer guidance, or facilitating networking opportunities, I seek to empower students to achieve\ntheir fullest potential.\nIn terms of teaching plans, I intend to develop courses that bridge law, national security, and\ntechnology policy, emphasizing interdisciplinary learning. My courses will integrate case\nstudies, simulation exercises, and guest lectures from industry experts to provide students with a\nwell-rounded perspective. Additionally, I aim to incorporate experiential learning opportunities,\nsuch as moot court competitions and policy analysis workshops, to equip students with the\npractical skills needed for success in their respective fields.\nUltimately, my goal as an educator is to cultivate critical thinkers, ethical decision-makers, and\nengaged citizens. By fostering an inclusive and intellectually stimulating classroom environment,\nI hope to inspire students to not only master their disciplines but also to apply their knowledge in\nways that contribute meaningfully to society.\n-- 5 of 10 --\n\nContact Reference Page\nTodd Huntley\nDirector, National Security Law Program\nLecturer in Law\n500 First Room 856\nGeorgetown University Law Center\n600 New Jersey Avenue, NW | Washington, DC 20001\nPH: (202)661-6553 | FX: 202-662-9487 | todd.huntley@law.georgetown.edu\nAnna Cave\nExecutive Director, National Security Law Program\n500 First Room 857\nGeorgetown University Law Center\n600 New Jersey Avenue, NW | Washington, DC 20001\nPH: (646)505-8811 | FX: 202-662-9487 | ac2137@georgetown.edu\nJudith Otter\nPresident,\nRobert Irvine Foundation\njotter@robertirvinefoundat