ich focused on interlocutory appeals, suppression\nof evidence, and motions for acquittal or reconsideration.\nJudicial Intern, June 2019 – August 2019\nTwentieth Circuit Court District, Canton, MS\n• \tResearched and drafted judicial orders under tight deadlines and contributed to decisions on\nmotions for summary judgments relied upon by judges.\n• \tSupported court administration by issuing status orders, e-filing documents, and assisting\ncourt staff in managing case workflows.\nBar Admissions: \tState of Alabama (2021 - Present) – Universal Bar Exam\nState of California (2021 – 2024) – Provisional License\nState of Texas (Pending) – Universal Bar Exam\nEducation: \tMississippi College School of Law, Jackson, MS\nDoctor of Jurisprudence, December 2020\nStudied Abroad - Winter 2019, Mérida, Mexico\nBenton Fellowship Recipient – Summer 2019\nUniversity of Mississippi, Oxford, MS\nBachelor of Science in Integrated Marketing Communications, May 2017\n-- 3 of 9 --\n\nPersonal Statement: Teaching Philosophy and Plans\nAs an attorney with over four years of litigation experience, I have developed a deep\nunderstanding of the legal profession and the practical skills required to succeed in complex legal\nmatters. My professional journey has equipped me with a passion for legal education, and I am\nexcited to share my expertise and experiences with the next generation of attorneys.\nI believe that teaching law is not just about imparting knowledge of statutes, case law, and legal\nprinciples, but also about fostering critical thinking, ethical reasoning, and a commitment to\njustice. My philosophy centers on the idea that the law is not only a set of rules but a dynamic\nfield that constantly evolves and interacts with society. I aim to engage students in this dynamic\nprocess, encouraging them to think critically about how the law shapes and is shaped by the\nworld around us.\nIn my classroom, I plan to emphasize the importance of practical, real-world experience in\nunderstanding and applying legal concepts. Given my background in litigation—ranging from\nmedical malpractice defense to commercial disputes and personal injury cases—I want to\nprovide students with concrete examples from my own experience to bridge the gap between\ntheory and practice. I believe that students learn best when they can connect the material to real-\nworld scenarios, and I will integrate case studies, current events, and problem-solving exercises\ninto my teaching approach.\nAdditionally, I am committed to creating an inclusive and supportive learning environment. I\nunderstand that law school can be challenging, and I want to encourage open dialogue and create\na space where students feel comfortable asking questions, expressing their opinions, and\nengaging in thoughtful discussions. Whether in a traditional classroom or through online\nplatforms, I plan to be accessible to students, offering guidance not only on academic matters but\nalso on their professional development.\nLooking ahead, my goal is to instill a sense of responsibility and ethical awareness in students,\nhelping them understand the weight of the decisions they will make as legal professionals. I also\nhope to inspire students to continually seek growth, both as scholars and as individuals,\nthroughout their careers.\nIn sum, my approach to teaching will be grounded in my practical experience as a litigator, a\ncommitment to fostering a collaborative and engaging classroom environment, and a passion for\ndeveloping future legal professionals who are both knowledgeable and ethically conscious.\n-- 4 of 9 --\n\nProfessional References\n1. \tSarah Butler\nStaff Attorney - 20th Circuity District Court\n(601) 855-5586\nsmbutler@rankincounty.or\n2. Richard S. Salinas\nPartner - Salinas Law Group\n(559) 438-2080\nrsalinas@salinaslg.com\n3. Stacy R. Lucas\nJunior Partner - Salinas Law Group\n(559) 438-2080\nslucas@salinaslg.com\n-- 5 of 9 --\n\nApplication Forms\nFoster Child Form\nFoster C