research, I have designed and taught courses on diverse topics, including International\nLaw, Maritime Law, and the History of Legal Doctrines. My pedagogical approach prioritizes critical\nthinking, the development of strong research and writing skills, and the ability to engage with complex\nprimary and secondary materials. These objectives reflect my dedication to fostering a rigorous and\nengaging learning environment. My teaching evaluations consistently highlight my effectiveness as an\ninstructor who is deeply committed to student success.\nBeyond the classroom, I actively contribute to the academic community through mentorship,\nparticipation in campus events, and collaboration on scholarly initiatives. I am particularly interested in\nopportunities to contribute to the vibrant intellectual life at Texas A&M University School of Law by\nengaging with students and colleagues in discussions about contemporary international legal issues and\ntheir historical underpinnings.\n-- 1 of 101 --\n\nThank you for considering my application. I am excited about the prospect of bringing my experience and\nenthusiasm to Texas A&M University School of Law. I look forward to the opportunity to contribute to\nyour esteemed institution.\nSincerely,\nIlan Fuchs, Ph.D., Esq.\n-- 2 of 101 --\n\nILAN FUCHS\nIlan.fuchs1@gmail.com\nCURRENT POSITION\nProfessor at American Public University\nEDUCATION\n2004-2009 Ph.D. Bar Ilan University (Ramat Gan, Israel)\n2009 Rabbinic Ordination by the Israeli Chief Rabbinate\n1999-2003 Bar Ilan University (Ramat Gan, Israel)\nL.L.B. / L.L.M. (passed Bar exam, October 2003)\n1999-2002 Bar Ilan University (Ramat Gan, Israel)\nM.A. in Jewish History\nThesis: Women's Torah Study in the Opinions of Three 20th Century\nAmerican Decisors\n1997-2001 Open University (Tel-Aviv, Israel)\nB.A. in Liberal Arts\nPUBLICATIONS\nBOOK\nThe Revolutionary Shtibel: Orthodox Approaches to Socialism (Texas Tech University\nPress forthcoming 2025)\nWomen’s Torah Study: 