e\npolitical controversy incurred when the United States decides to use force\nagainst a foreign nation).\n142. See Amos Guiora, Targeted Killing as Active Self-Defense, 36 CASE W.\nRES. J. INT’L L. 319, 334 (2004); Kretzmer, supra note 141143, at 171; Richard\nMurphy & Afsheen John Radsan, Due Process and Targeted Killing of\nTerrorists, 31 CARDOZO L. REV. 405, 405 (2009). See generally Orna Ben-\nNaftali & Keren Michaeli, ‘We Must not Make a Scarecrow of the Law’: A Legal\nAnalysis of the Israeli Policy of Targeted Killing, 36 CORNELL INT’L L.J. 233,\n335–38 (2006) (detailing a stricter model).\n143. See Ryan Goodman, The Detention Of Civilians In Armed Conflict, 103\nAM. J. INT’L L. 48, 48–49 (2009); Louis Rene Beres, The Legal Meaning Of\nTerrorism For The Military Commander, 11 CONN. J. INT'L L. 1, 2–6 (1995).\n144. See HCJ 769/02 The Public Committee Against Torture in Israel v.\nGovernment of Israel (2) IsrLR 459 [2006] ¶¶24–27 (Isr.), available at\nhttp://www.scribd.com/doc/68675324/Targeted-Killing-Case-Israel-High-Court-\nof-Justice-JUDGMENT-HCJ-769-02-The-Public-Committee-Against-Torture-\nin-Israel-v-Israel-13-Dec-2006.\n145. NILS MELZER, TARGETED KILLING IN INTERNATIONAL LAW (2009).\n146. See generally THOMAS B. HUNTER, TARGETED KILLING: SELF-\nDEFENSE, PREEMPTION, AND THE WAR ON TERRORISM (2007), available at\nhttp://www.operationalstudies.com/mootw/Targeted%20Killing%20Research%\n20PaperOS.pdf (noting the norms states use to justify targeted killing to\ncombat terrorism).\n-- 49 of 101 --\n\n2012] WEAK STATES AND TERRORISTS 135\nis important in a weak state scenario.147\nTerrorism is a direct attack on the sovereignty of the host\nstate. Because of this direct attack, it also demands an\nunderstanding of how to properly adjudicate counter-terrorism\nactivities. Due process serves not only the internal needs of rule\nof law but also offers protection to the host state’s sovereignty.\nWhile there are opinions that minimize the level of judicial\nintervention needed in counter terrorism operations and\nsuggest this function be delegated largely to the administrative\nbranch, this view is criticized for several reasons.148 Emanuel\nGross has suggested that a constitutional model is well\nequipped to deal with the war on terror.149 The Israeli Supreme\nCourt adopted this approach:\nFirst, the Court envisions the terrorist threat as an international -\nrather than a solely domestic - problem. Accordingly, the standards\nfor adjudicating counter-terrorism cases, as well those involving\nhuman rights and national security, are international standards.\nSecond, the war against terrorism is an exceptional circumstance but\nhas not been treated with exceptional law. The Court usually refers to\nexisting international law of war and human rights conventions. It\nhas not ruled that terror presents a unique situation outside the force\nof international law. Third, this three-tiered analysis actually\nreinforces human rights. In order to justify certain counter-terrorism\nmeasures, the state must prove that the operation or action taken is\nin accordance not only with the relevant direct law (be it detention\nlaw, military order or other regulation) but also with the Israeli\ncommon law and international law. Legality under one set of laws\ndoes not imply per se legality under another set of laws.150\nCritics of this view will state that this is a very optimistic\npicture of the war against terrorism and that this view forces\nall countries to use executive models of the war in some form or\nanother.151 But, in a weak state situation, this is pertinent\n147. See Bruce Ackerman, The Emergency Constitution, 113 YALE L.J.\n1029, 1029–30 (2004) (noting the issue from an American legal point of view);\nMurphy & Radsan, supra note 142144 (noting due process as an important\nneed).\n148. See Oren Gross, Chaos and Rules: Should Responses to Violent Crises\nAlways Be Constitutional?, 112 YALE L.J. 1011,1035–37 (2003) (suggesting\nthat public officials will not be bound by constitutional regulations but their\nactions will be regulated by the public).\n149. Emanuel Gross, The Struggle of a Democracy Against the Terror of\nSuicide Bombers: Ideological and Legal Aspects, 22 WIS. INT'L L.J. 597, 651–55\n(2004).\n150. Yigal Mersel, Judicial Review of Counter-Terrorism Measures: The\nIsraeli Model for the Role of the Judiciary During the Terror Era, 38 N.Y.U. J.\nINT'L L. & POL. 67, 101 (2006).\n151. See generally Daphne Barak-Erez, Terrorism Law Between the\nExecutive and Legislative Models, 57 AM. J. COMP. L. 877, 881–82 (2009)\n(explaining the United States’ executive model and its application to terrorism\n-- 50 of 101 --\n\n136 MINNESOTA JOURNAL OF INTL’ LAW [Vol 21:2\nsince oversight will ensure that actions will be taken based on\nrelevant evidence of an imminent danger. Moreover, this\napproach has a low chance of collateral damage. The lower the\ncollateral damage, the lower the impact will be on the host\nstate’s sovereignty.\nIt has been suggested that targeted killings are justified\nwhen they save the lives of soldiers,152 even if there is a small\nrisk of endangering civilians. Since targeted killings reduce the\nimpact on sovereignty, they are justifiable in a weak state\nscenario where a terrorist is not only attacking the intervening\npower but also infringing on the sovereignty of the host\ncountry.\nK. Precision Guided Munitions\nPrecision-guided munitions (“PGMs”) are weapons that\nposses the ability to strike targets with a high degree of\naccuracy.153 PGMs are usually referred to as “smart bombs”\nsince they possess technological elements (guidance systems)\nthat enable them to be guided or to independently direct\nthemselves towards their target. The need for PGMs became\nclear during World War II because conventional bombs—\nunguided bombs dropped from aircraft that follow their own\nballistic trajectory—were imprecise. Multiple bombing raids\nwere required to completely destroy a single target. This\nmethod was costly and placed crews and material in harm’s\nway. Brigadier General Anderson recounted in a letter to a\nfellow colleague:\nI participated in the Bremen operation where I saw sixteen B-17s\nknocked out of the air. However, if we had destroyed the factory\ncompletely it would have been worth fifty B-17s. We did accomplish\nabout 40% to 50% destruction . . . our computations indicated that it\nwould take three hundred bombers to destroy the target and we\ndispatched one hundred.154\nlaw).\n152. Solon Solomon, Targeted Killings and The Soldiers' Right to Life, 14\nILSA J. INT'L & COMP. L. 99, 110–11 (2007).\n153. See generally ROWLAND F. POCOCK, GERMAN GUIDED MISSILES OF THE\nSECOND WORLD WAR (1967) (noting the history of the development of such\nweapons); KENNETH P. WERRELL, THE EVOLUTION OF THE CRUISE MISSILE\n(1985) (discussing the history of the cruise missile); WILLIAM F. TRIMBLE,\nWINGS FOR THE NAVY (1990) (discussing naval history and their interaction\nwith ever increasing military technology, specifically bombs).\n154. PAUL GILLESPIE, WEAPONS OF CHOICE: THE DEVELOPMENT OF\nPRECISION GUIDED MUNITIONS 26 (2006) (citing Letter from Brigadier\nGeneral F.L. Anderson, 4th Bombardment Wing Commander, to Brigadier\nGeneral Eugene L. Eubank ( May 4, 1943), in BOX 76 PAPERS OF CARL A.\n-- 51 of 101 --\n\n2012] WEAK STATES AND TERRORISTS 137\nSome estimates show that in 1941, out of one hundred\nbombs dropped over a designated target during the daytime,\n10% fell precisely on target, 25% fell within 250 yards, 40%\nwithin a 500 yard radius and 90 percent within 1 mile of the\ntarget.155\nBombs with heightened precision were developed with two\ngoals in mind: (1) destroying enemy industries156 and (2)\ndestroying the enemy’s defensive capabilities.157 Achieving\nthese goals would reduce losses and bombing raids would be\ncarried out from lower altitudes while simultaneously\nenhancing precision and implementing a strategy of\nattrition.158 Furthermore, some had a third goal of using guided\nbombs to terrify, as shown by the motivations behind the\nbombs developed under the Aphrodite Project (“Project”).\nGeneral Spaatz from the Project wished to use heightened\nprecision bombs as an “irritant and morale-breaking weapon”\nagainst the German population and “to leave in the minds of\nthe Germans the threat of robot attacks against cities [by\nattacking] an industrial objective in a large German city as far\ninland as practicable.”159 General Spaatz stated: “My idea\nwould be to turn them loose to land all over Germany so that\nthe Germans would be just as much afraid of our war weary\nplanes on account of not knowing just where they were going to\nhit as are the people in England from the buzz bombs and\nrockets.”160\nPGMs can and have been used to meet the first two goals\nand even the optional third goal. For the third goal, weapons\nthat were not deemed to be precise enough or serviceable, such\nas the ones developed under the Project, were used as\ninstruments of psychological warfare. Current PGMs have\nunprecedented precision, be it in bombs, such as the Pave Way\nII and Pave Way III bombs but also in other types of\nSPAATZ, LOC).\n155. Id.\n156. It appears that during WWII one of the Allies’ priorities in the\nWestern Front was to bomb V-2 and V-3 sites that terrorized British citizens.\nThis is why the Allied Air Forces developed projects pertaining to the\ndestruction of these sites with PGMs creating the Aphrodite Project. The\nAphrodite Project proved to be promising with regards to possible future\ndevelopments of guided weapons, however the results on the ground fell short\nof destroying enemy V-2 and V-3 launching sites. See id.at 28.\n157. See generally id. at 25–26.\n158. See generally id. at 25–28.\n159. See GILLESPIE, supra note 154156, at 29.\n160. Id. (citing Letter from H.H. Arnold to Carl Spaatz (Nov. 23, 1944) in\nBOX 16 AND BOX 193 PAPERS OF CARL A. SPAATZ, LOC).\n-- 52 of 101 --\n\n138 MINNESOTA JOURNAL OF INTL’ LAW [Vol 21:2\nweapons.161 This level of precision was spurred by the\ntechnological revolution that introduced the laser and the\nsemiconductor integrated circuit.162 Now, air strikes can\neliminate with precision enemy threats without having to\ndestroy large areas surrounding the designated target. Thus,\nthe risk of collateral damage during a “surgical strike” is much\nless than the collateral damage in bombing raids during WWII.\nPGMs have numerous advantages besides reduced\ncollateral damage, which is part of the reason why the United\nStates uses such weapons against host nations. PMGs can\naccurately strike a defined target, pilots can deliver weapons\nwith minimal safety risk, and collateral damage is minimized.\nPGMs offer the opportunity to neutralize a threat, like\nterrorists in a weak host nation, without resorting to a full\nblown war and infringing upon a host nation’s sovereignty.\nThe inability of a weak state to act against domestic\nterrorists justifies the usage of PGMs. There are numerous\nbenefits to PGMs, but unfortunately, the use of PGMS is not\nalways purely beneficial. Critics state that many civilian lives\nare lost in the midst of military operations, mainly while\ncarrying out targeted killings.163 It is clear that some collateral\ndamage is unavoidable due to a long list of factors such as\nmistakes in assessing the situation at hand on the part of the\nstriking force, or because some targeted individual(s)\npurposefully live amongst civilians. However, the potential\noffered by PGMs to reduce civilian collateral damage and\nintrusion on the host state’s sovereignty make such munitions\na weapon of choice while undertaking preventive and\npreemptive strikes against terrorist entities.\nIII. Summary\nThis article introduces the weak state doctrine. We argue\nthat when a state does not have the ability to control parts of\nits territory which are under the control of terrorists—who are\n161. For instance, the XM-25 rifle is a prime example of how small arms\ncan also be developed to deliver utmost precision by using lasers in order to\ndetermine when a launched grenade should explode. See XM25 Individual\nSemi-Automatic Airburst System (ISAAS) Counter Defilade Target\nEngagement (CDTE) System Objective Individual Combat Weapon (OICW)\nIncrement 2, GLOBALSECURITY.ORG,\nwww.globalsecurity.org/military/systems/ground/m25.htm (last modified July\n7, 2011).\n162. See GILLESPIE, supra note 154156, at 70.\n163. See David E. Anderson, Drones and the Ethics of War, PBS.ORG (May\n14, 2010),\nhttp://www.pbs.org/wnet/religionandethics/episodes/by-\ntopic/international/drones-and-the-ethics-of-war/6290/.\n-- 53 of 101 --\n\n2012] WEAK STATES AND TERRORISTS 139\nusing it as a base of operation to launch attacks on a third\nstate—the attacked state has a right of self-defense against the\nterrorist organization residing within the weak host state.\nWhen a state loses its sovereignty to a terrorist organization\nand it cannot fulfill its stately duties, it forfeits some of the\nprivileges that sovereignty entails. However, since inaction by\nthe weak host state is not voluntary, actions by intervening\nnations against the terrorist organization that would infringe\non the sovereignty of the weak state should be gradual and\nallow the weak state the opportunity to resume its capacity as\na sovereign state. We suggest a list of tactical measures—non-\nkinetic warfare, blockade, targeted killing, and precision guided\nmunitions—that have a lesser effect on sovereignty and allow\nthe weak host state to choose between acting against the\nterrorist entity or allow the intervening force to do so on its\nbehalf.\nWe do not give a clear answer to the allotted time for the\nfirst stage of intervention. The question of when to move to\nmore drastic measures is not one that can be answered with a\nspecific timetable. There are situations that suggest more fierce\nmilitary action is necessary over a short time span—such as\nwhen there are hostages involved and any delay can put their\nlives in danger—and other situations that require a gradual\nescalation of military operations. Ultimately, the goal is that\nthe weak state will be able to enforce the rule of law on its\nterritory and against terrorists within its borders.\n-- 54 of 101 --\n\nHEBREW\nUNION COLLEGE\nANNUAL\nVolumes 82–83\nHebrew Union College Press\nUniversity of Pittsburgh Press\n2011–2012\n-- 55 of 101 --\n\n©2014 by\nHebrew Union College Press\nUniversity of Pittsburgh Press\nISSN 360-9049\nISBN 9780822944355\nTypesetting by Raphaël Freeman, Renana Typesetting\nPrinted in the United States of America\n-- 56 of 101 --\n\n119\nWomen’s Testimony in Jewish Law\nA Historical Survey\nIlan Fuchs\nThe Hadassah-Brandeis Institute, Brandeis University\nThis article explores Jewish legal rulings regarding women’s ability to give\ntestimony. It deals with the early stages of the legal sources and compares\nthe biblical and early tannaitic material to contemporary sources. I show\nthat there is no possible way to suggest what the reasoning was for the\nexclusion of women from giving testimony, and that reasons that have\nto do with women’s reliability only appear in later sources. I also discuss\nthe situations where women’s testimony was not barred.\nThis article goes on to focus on the late Middle Ages and examines\nthe textual sources and historical and cultural factors that influenced\nmedieval decisors in their rulings. The major changes in the scope of\nwomen’s ability to give testimony in European Jewish communities are\nexplained by discussing the historical context and the changing role of\nwomen in the public sphere.\nOne of the major questions occupying scholars of rabbinic law is the gap be-\ntween contemporary legal systems and halakhah. The early scholars of the field\nattempted to bridge the gap between these legal systems and, for many, there\nwas an underlying goal to integrate Jewish law into the legal system of modern\nIsrael. These attempts accentuated the differences between the systems, and a\nmajor focus of these attempts concerned the differences in evidentiary law. The\nunique characteristics of halakhic evidentiary law set a very high bar to prove a\ncase, and one example of this is the inadmissibility of women’s testimony. The\nhistorical development of women’s testimony in Jewish law is a microcosm of\nthe development of Jewish women’s roles in Jewish society. Rabbinic discourse\non this issue reflects historical changes in women’s rights and roles and brings\nwith it reinterpretations of canonical texts.\nLaws concerning what constitutes evidence are at the center of almost any\nlegal case. If there is agreement on a certain set of facts or conditions, all that\nremains is to resolve what legal instructions are applicable. If facts are disputed,\nhowever, a court must first determine the facts in accordance with laws of evi-\ndence – procedural rules to determine how claims of fact may be proven. The\nfirst issue is relevance: does particular evidence contribute to the determination\nof fact? This question is then examined specifically, but not exclusively, in terms\n-- 57 of 101 --\n\nIlan Fuchs\t120\nof credibility. The level of credibility a court attributes to evidence determines\nits weight when determining the facts of the case.\nBesides the question of weight, much legal discourse about rules of evidence\ncenters on admissibility. Rules of admissibility determine if certain evidence\ncan be submitted and given weight by the court. These rules can also determine\nthat relevant, credible evidence is not admissible and therefore cannot con-\ntribute to determining the factual basis of the case. Other interests besides the\ndiscovery of the truth may necessitate overlooking evidentiary material. If not\ngiven voluntarily, the testimony of a woman against her husband, for example,\nor children against their parents, is, in order to protect the social foundation\nof marriage and family, usually not admissible.\nDoron Menashe sees a legal integrity undergirding the rules of admissibility.\nHe argues that between the freedom to evaluate evidence and the freedom to\nprove legal arguments, criteria of admissibility are necessary to prevent errors\nthat harm the integrity of the legal system, even at the cost of undermining\nthe discovery of truth.1\nThe Perception of Laws of Evidence in Halakhah\nSome halakhic rules of admissibility may be explained as protecting interests\nother than the discovery of truth, though these interests may not be explicit.2\nAware of the difficulties arising from the halakhic rules of admissibility in the\nday-to-day activity of the legal system, Maimonides established the principle\nthat in monetary issues, the דיין (rabbinic judge) should act upon his own\njudgment based on the evidentiary material, even though some might be\ninadmissible.3 According to Maimonides, rules of evidence are only needed\nin monetary issues when the rabbinic judge is not convinced what the legal\nresult should be. In capital punishment cases, this rule does not apply, and,\naccording to all halakhic rules of evidence, conviction can only be obtained\nwith admissible evidence. 4\nMaimonides explains the difference between capital punishment cases and\n1 Doron Menashe, ראיות קבילות של הלוגיקה (Jerusalem: Magnes Press, 2009) 1–11.\n2 b. B. Bat. 159a. See also Maimonides, Sefer Hamitsvot Lo Ta’ase, 287.\n3 Mishneh, Torah Hilkhot Eidut 17, 1. See also Yaakov Blidstein, במשנת פסיקה ככלי הדיין של ״ה״אמת״\n״.ג-א ,כד סנהדרין להלכות :הרמב״ם, Dinei Israel 24 (2007) 119–160; Michael Baris, :עדות להלכות ״מבוא\nהרמב״ם״ בשיטת עיון – הלב ושכנוע נוקשים כללים, Mishpatei Eretz 2 (2005) 49. For another view of\nthe role of the rabbinical judge, cf. Shimshon Ettinger, בהלכה״ בית־דין של ופיקציה דין של ״פיקציה in\nודיון דיין ובהלכה עברי במשפט עיונים, ed. Yaakov Chaba and Amichay Radzyner, (Ramat Gan: Bar\nIlan Press, 2007) 9–28.\n4 Baris, “עדות להלכות מבוא,” 55. For a detailed discussion of Maimonides’ position see Yuval Sinai,\n“הרמב״ם הלכות גיבוש בדרכי פרק – ודרישות בדיקות ,חקירות,” Sidra 21 (2006) 35–50.\n-- 58 of 101 --\n\nWomen’s Testimony in Jewish Law \t121\nmonetary issues with a moral justification: “ . . . and when we determine the\nlegal requirements by use of analogy and אומדנא [lit. “estimation,” here based\non inadmissible circumstantial evidence], we will one day kill innocents .\nAnd it is better and desired to acquit 1,000 sinners than to one day kill one\ninnocent person.”5 Capital punishment was, of course, merely a theoretical\nissue in Jewish law.\nThe ability to use judicial discretion in certain cases is derived from the\nTalmud.6 Rabbi Isaac Alfasi (Rif), however, attributes to an anonymous gaon\nthe opinion that אומדנא (estimation) should not be used, and other rishonim\nadopted the same position.7 Although this seems like a clear ruling in favor of\nfirm laws of admissibility at the expense of the weight of evidence, the tension\nbetween the need to conduct a halakhic legal system and the restrictions of\nthe rules of evidence has remained part of halakhic discussions since the days\nof the rishonim.\nThe legal mechanism “מרומה דין” (the law of the cheater) allows rabbinic\njudges to use estimation that relies on inadmissible evidence. This rule applies\nwhen the rabbinic judges suspect that one of the parties is exploiting the laws\nof evidence to avoid paying debts. Maimonides maintains that in a case when\none is making use of “the law of the cheater,” the rabbinic judge should inves-\ntigate meticulously, and if he cannot make the determination he knows is true,\nhe can refuse to adjudicate the matter. Rabbeinu Asher (Rosh) holds that in a\ncase where “the law of the cheater” applies to the plaintiff exploiting the laws\nof evidence, then the rabbinic judge can excuse himself from adjudicating (and\nalso from giving a written decision to the defendant that he should be awarded\nrelief). Or when the defendant is suspected of cheating, then the rabbinic judge\ncan adjudicate according to his אומדנא (estimation).8 The Shulchan Arukh cites\nboth Maimonides and Rosh, and there are those who interpret the Shulchan\nArukh as saying that Maimonides does not disagree with Rosh and also allows\nin the case of “the law of the cheater” adjudication according to estimation. 9\nThe term אומדנא (estimation) not only refers to the use of inadmissible testi-\nmony, but also to the use of evidence derived from modern forensic tools like\naudio recordings, videos, and other forensic methods that do not adhere to\n5 Sefer Hamitsvot Lo Ta’aseh, 290, 288; Mishneh Torah, Hilkhot Eidut 5, 1.\n6 Yuval Sinai, העברי במשפט השיפוטי וההליך השופט (Jerusalem: Machon Harry Sacker, 2009) 385–413;\nUri Rotem, “עדות ללא דין הכרעת,” Mishpatei Eretz 2 (2005) 82–84.\n7 Rif, Ketub. 43b; See also Rash Ketub. 9, 6; Mishneh Torah, Hilkhot Sanhedrin 24, 2.\n8 Mishneh Torah, Hilkhot Sanhedrin 24, 3; Asher b. Yehiel Sanhedrin 4, 4; For a broad discussion\nof the different positions of tannaim, amoraim and rishonim see Sinai, השופט, 415–65.\n9 Rotem, “דין הכרעת” 94–96, see especially footnote 145 where he brings a long list of sources which\ndiscuss the use of estimation in this era.\n-- 59 of 101 --\n\nIlan Fuchs\t122\nthe halakhic laws of admissibility.10 Therefore, the term אומדנא is also relevant\nfor the testimony of inadmissible witnesses.\nWomen’s Admissibility to Give Testimony:\nBiblical and Tannaitic Sources\nWhile the Bible does not directly discuss women’s eligibility to testify, testimo-\nny itself is treated in Deut 19:15: “According to two witnesses or according to\nthree witnesses, matters shall be established.” Exclusion of certain witnesses is\nnot mentioned and there is no other reference to the admissibility of women’s\ntestimony in the biblical era. Yair Shiber argues, however, for a very different\ndevelopment. He asserts that a woman was eligible to give testimony because\nDeut 12:18–21 describes the trial of a “stubborn and rebellious son” wherein\nthe parents bring the son to the city gates to be judged before the elders, then\nexecuted. Shiber sees this description as a testimonial procedure including\nboth father and mother.11 The unusual occurrence of parents testifying against\ntheir children makes it difficult to learn much from these verses, much less to\nextrapolate from them to other cases. In fact, the parents’ role is not so much\ngiving testimony as lodging a complaint. Later, tannaitic sources will require\nwarning the rebellious son in front of witnesses; thus the parents themselves\ndo not serve as witnesses at all.12\nSources from other cultures in the biblical era do not form a clear picture\nof whether women were generally disqualified from giving testimony. Bruce\nWells argues that women could indeed give testimony and finds support in\nAssyrian, Babylonian, and Nuzian sources.13 It is unclear, however, whether\nwomen could give independent testimony in neo-Assyrian Nuzi (ca. 1500–1350\nBCE) or only corroborate the testimony of men.14 Athenian legal texts dating\nto 420–320 BCE suggest that, according to ancient Greek law, women could\nnot generally give testimony.15 Opinions differ on whether women could give\n10 Sholmo Daychovsky, “סתר האזנות,” Techumin 12 (1991) 300–6; Meir Batist, במשפט הראיות דיני ״על\nדמיאניוק״ הצורר, Techumin 9 (1988): 33–116. Rotem, “דין הכרעת,” 97–105. Rotem lists case law from\nthe rabbinical court and also modern responsa legitimizing evidence obtained by technological\nmeans; Chaim Chefitz, “העברי במשפט נסיבתיות ראיות של מקומן,” Mishpatim 1 (1968) 67–85.\n11 See Yair Shiber, “העברי במשפט בקידושין קיום ועדי עדות” (PhD diss., Bar Ilan University, 2003) 13–16.\n12 Shiber, “קיום ועדי עדות,” 17.\n13 Bruce Wells, The Law of Testimony, 51–53.\n14 Ephraim Zand, “הדין ופסקי המשפטי ההליך ,הניסוח :בנוזי הדין בתי תעודות” (PhD diss., Bar Ilan University,\n2000) 147–150.\n15 Sally C. Humphreys, “Kinship Patterns in Athenian Courts,” GRBS 27 (1986) 72; Louis Cohn-\nHaft, “Divorce in Classical Athens,” The Journal of Hellenic Studies 115 (1995) 12.\n-- 60 of 101 --\n\nWomen’s Testimony in Jewish Law \t123\ntestimony in murder cases, and it may be that their testimony was given by\nmale proxies under whose guardianship the women testified.16\nThe earliest Jewish text dealing directly with women’s testimony comes in\nthe Sifre:17\n“And they shall stand.” It is commanded that the defendants shall stand. “The\ntwo men,” this means not only when there are two men, but a man with a\nwoman and a woman with a man, and two women with each other. From\nwhere [do we learn this]? We learn this from [the verse]: “The two parties\nto the dispute.” Could it be that a woman is eligible to give testimony? It is\nsaid here “two,” and it is said there “two.” Since the two said here are men, not\nwomen, so the two mentioned there are men, not women [emphasis mine].18\nBy a standard שווה גזרה (verbal analogy) hermeneutic, the inclusive masculine\nbecomes exclusive by bouncing one biblical passage against another; but there\nis a question about which verse provides the exclusive interpretation. Finklestin\nthought that the two verses exegeted “here” and “there” were those mentioned\nin the Babylonian Talmud (Shevu’ot 30a), Deut 19:15: “A single witness may\nnot validate against a person any guilt or blame for any offense that may be\ncommitted; a case can be valid only on the testimony of two witnesses or more,”\n(NJPS Translation) and Deut 19:17, “The two parties to the dispute shall appear\nbefore the Lord before the priests or magistrates in authority at the time, and\nthe magistrates shall make a thorough investigation” (NJPS Translation). The ex-\nposition is on verse 17 and apparently relates to verse 15, but all the manuscripts\nreverse the order. Finklestin changed the wording in his edition so that “here”\nrefers to ver