te this]? – You might say, it is not usual\nfor a woman, because all glorious is the King’s daughter within, [therefore I\ngive the second deduction:] here it is said, “two,” and there it is said, “two”;\njust as there it refers to witnesses, so here it refers to witnesses.37\nThe conclusion of the exegesis is that the word ‘people’ refers to men, not women.\nTherefore, women’s testimony is inadmissible.38 Other amoraic sources state\n36 b. Shevu. 30a.\n37 b. Shevu. 30a.\n38 Mishneh Torah, Hilkhot Eidut 9, 2. Maimonides holds that inadmissibility is derived from the\nverse according to “two witnesses,” which is masculine, not feminine. Contrary to the Talmud’s\nposition just quoted, the Kesef Mishneh ad loc questions this position since the entire Torah is\ngiven in masculine form.\n-- 65 of 101 --\n\nIlan Fuchs\t128\nclearly that women are not allowed to give testimony. In tractate Bava Qamma,\nfor example, Ulla states:\nBut again would you now also say that according to the Rabbis, a slave would\nbe eligible to give evidence, since it says, “And behold, if the witness be a\nfalse witness and hath testified falsely against his brother?” – Ulla replied:\n“Regarding evidence you can surely not argue this. For his disqualification\nfrom giving evidence can be learned by means of an a fortiori from the law in\nthe case of woman: for if woman, who is eligible to enter [by marriage] into\nthe congregation [of Israel] is yet ineligible to give evidence, how much more\nmust a slave who is not eligible to enter [by marriage] into the congregation\n[of Israel] be ineligible to give evidence?”39\nThe Yerushalmi exegetes differently but reaches the same conclusion. Here,\nDeut 19:15 is accompanied by the verse in Numbers about Eldad and Medad.\nIn the amoraic material, the inadmissibility of women’s testimony is clear and\nagreed upon by all, but justification for this rule of admissibility is just as\nclearly absent.\nReasons for Women Not to Give Testimony\nThe exclusion of 