y because of the decree of biblical verses,\nwhile still others are unfit simply because they are not reliable.45 The forces\nthat marginalized women in Jewish society resulted in them being perceived\nas unreliable and that, according to Ettinger, led the Sages not to accept their\ntestimony.46\nEven though the major canonical sources do not explain the exegesis dis-\nqualifying women from testifying, there are more exegetical attempts to explain\nthis rule in the aggadah literature. Pirqe de Rabbi Eliezer (PRE) is a compilation\nedited in the Muslim period, but much material stems from earlier times and\nrelies mainly on traditions from Eretz Yisrael.47 In chapter 14, one of the curses\ninflicted on women after Eve’s sin was their being deemed unfit to give testi-\nmony.48 Ari Shvat suggests that Eve’s sin was the result of her giving in to the\nserpent’s evil persuasion, and since women are easily persuaded and not used\nto standing their ground like men, they are disqualified from giving testimony.\nConversely, women’s ability to compromise is a very important element of\nfamily life.49 In his interpretation of PRE, Rabbi Eliyahu Etamari explains that\nsince Eve introduced Adam to evil, which includes giving false testimony, it is\nfitting that she should not give testimony. Even though this exegesis has many\nparallels – Avot de Rabbi Natan, for example – the line concerning women’s\nunfitness to testify is not mentioned in any of them.50\n43 Albek, הראיות, 28–29.\n44 For example, women are lightheaded, b. Qiddushin 80b, or women are lazy, Pesach. 1,1 2a.\n45 Ettinger, “העברי במשפט ממונות בדיני כעד אשה,” Dinei Israel, 20–21 (2000–2001) 242.\n46 Ettinger, “כעד אשה,” 246. He learns this from the Tosefta concerning the beehive mentioned above.\nSee footnote t. Ketub. 34.\n47 Dinah Stein, העממית הספרות מחקר לאור אליעזר דרבי פרקי :מיתוס מגיה מימרה (Jerusalem: Magnes\nPress, 2005) 2–3. On the connection of the midrash to pseudo-epigraphy and other ancient\nmaterials 