 in Jewish Law \t131\nMidrash Yelamdenu dated 400–600 CE, alongside much later layers.57 Although\nBergman admits that the periodization of midrash from Tanhuma-Yelamdenu\nliterature is extremely problematic, the linguistic aspects of the midrash reflect\na later layer of Yelamdenu literature. Josephus’ position is likely reflected in\nlater texts influenced by Eretz Yisrael midrash. 58 Notions of “women’s nature”\nalso play a certain role in the discussion of women’s unfitness to give testimony.\nAggadic sources suggest that since the legal rule is already well-documented in\ntannaitic sources, the midrash is giving a post factum rationale for the legal rule.\nThe only sources that explicitly mention a justification for women’s unfit-\nness to give testimony are Josephus, PRE, and Midrash Yelamdenu; it is merely\nimplied in the Tosefta. It is difficult to come to a final conclusion, especially in\nview of the eternal question of whether the midrash served to initiate halakhah,\nor was merely an attempt to justify existing law. The perception of women as\nunreliable does, however, play a role in the discussion of women’s testimony.\nThis subtext also suggests that if perceptions of women change, then wom-\nen’s unfit status might change as well. However, since the justification for the\ninadmissibility of women’s testimony only appears in aggadic material, while\nthe Sifre and Talmud give no such rationale, the conclusion is that the rule is\ndecreed by the biblical text, which minimizes the hermeneutical space within\nwhich to reinterpret it and to thus claim that perceptions of women’s nature have\nchanged. The excerpts from the Talmud and the Yerushalmi attributing nega-\ntive qualities to women can also be explained against a historical background.\nHowever, these examples do not attribute an aspect of unreliability to women.\nWomen’s Testimony in Questions of Aginut\nand Other Personal Status Issues\nThe tannaim allowed women’s testimony in several cases that had serious\nramifications concerning women’s ability to remarry and the lineage of future\nchildren. One major exception to the rule excluding women’s testimony is a\ngroup of cases where women are in danger of not being able to divorce. The\nterm אישה עדות (literally “women’s testimony”) in halakhic literature refers\nto testimony given to resolve a situation of עגינות (literally, “chaining”) – of\na woman being unable to divorce her husband because he will not or cannot\nissue a get, a bill of divorce. This does not necessarily refer to a testimony giv-\n57 Marc Bergman, התהוותה בדרכי ועיונים נוסחיה תאור תנחומא־ילמדנו ספרות (Gorgias Press LLC, 2003).\nSee also Meron Bialik Lerner, “The Works of Aggadic Midrash and Esther Midrashim,” in The\nLiterature of the Sages, 150, 169–70.\n58 Bergman, תנחומא־ילמדנו ספרות, 176–80.\n-- 69 of 101 --\n\nIlan Fuchs\t132\nen by a woman, but rather to a list of cases where the Sages suspended their\nregular rules of evidence to release a woman from an unwanted marriage. The\nsource of אישה עדות is an enactment of Rabban Gamliel that determined that a\nwoman could be married based on inadmissible testimony.59 By analogy then,\nshe could be granted a divorce in the same fashion. Maimonides explains this\npolicy by noting that when dealing with the dissolution of a marriage, witnesses\nare not likely to lie, for example, about the death of a person.60 Some rishonim\nexplained reliance on testimony from ineligible witnesses as an exception to\nevidentiary laws, while other rabbinic authorities regarded it not as an act of\ntestimony, but rather a process of investigation of the truth.61\nThe Talmud explains that if a woman remarries and the testimony is proven\nuntruthful, then the second marriage and any children issuing from the union\nwill be deemed illegitimate. A woman who is released from her marriage will\nthus make an effort to bring forth reliable testimony in her favor and not rely\non suspicious testimony.62 A second explanation focuses on the eventual dis-\ncovery of untruthful testimony, so the woman who seeks divorce will make\nample attempts to validate it.63 Rashi suggests that since the Sages were able\nto annul a marriage, they allowed testimony of one witness and, according to\nthat testimony, invalidated the marriage retroactively.64\nThe Rabad (R. Abraham ben David [ca. 1120–1198]) holds that a woman will\nmake sure to carefully examine the testimony because of the possible ramifi-\ncations for her future children.65 Most of the rishonim adopted the Talmud’s\napplication of אישה עדות to monetary issues, thus there is no need for a metic-\nulous examination of the testimony. This does not, however, explain the legal\nbasis for the deviation from regular laws of evidence in אישה עדות, for example,\nthe acceptance of inadmissible witnesses.66\nIn Sinai’s analysis of the irrelevance of meticulous scrutiny of witnesses in\nmonetary cases, it seems that this irrelevance is the result of a procedural need\nand does not reflect on the credibility of the witnesses. The issue of credibil-\n59 m. Yevamot 16, 7.\n60 Mishneh Torah, Hilkhot Gerushin 13:29. For a discussion about the rationale and the development\nof this policy see Yuval Sinai, “עגונה עדי חקירת,” Shenaton HaMishpat HaIvri 22 (2001–2003)\n330–68. For a specific discussion on Maimonides see 350–55. For other opinions see Halacha\nPsuka Edut 30,1.\n61 M. Cohen, ושטרות עדות (Jerusalem: n.p, 1989) 265–76; Naama Sat, “אישה בעדות תומו לפי מסיח גוי,”\nIlanot 1 (2007) 80–81.\n62 t. Yevamot 88a.\n63 t. Yevamot 115a.\n64 Rashi Shabb. 145b. s.v. Eidut Isha. See also Cohen’s remark in Cohen, ושטרות עדות, 267.\n65 Sinai, “עגונה עדי חקירת,” 366.\n66 Sinai, השיפוטי וההליך השופט, 290\n-- 70 of 101 --\n\nWomen’s Testimony in Jewish Law \t133\nity is dealt with by the procedure of warning and interrogating the witness.\nVarious leniencies are thus a result of procedural needs and do not show that\nthe rishonim lowered the bar when it came to credibility.67 The acceptance of\ninadmissible evidence in the case of אישה עדות thus does not call into question\nthe reliability of those witnesses.\nAnother exception has to do with יבום (Levirate marriage). The Mishnah\nstates that a woman can testify on marital relations in the case of levirate mar-\nriage.68 The Talmud explains that this is not a matter of testimony, but rather\na case of discovery of truth. The Mishnah also allows reliance on disqualified\nwitnesses in a case of כהן אשת (a priest’s wife).69 In this case the Talmud explains\nthat in light of the ramifications, the Sages allowed inadmissible evidence.70 In\ntwo cases the Talmud suggested that women could give testimony according\nto the Bible itself. The first case is that of סוטה (suspected wife) and the second\nis the case of ערופה עגלה (beheaded calf).71\nThe testimony of a woman in the ceremony of סוטה (suspected wife) is accept-\ned when the testimony reveals knowledge of the wife’s infidelity. A woman can\nonly testify that the woman had intercourse with another man, which negates\nthe need for the ceremony.\nThese cases show that weight is given to women’s testimony when it serves an\ninterest the Sages deem extremely important, mainly, releasing a woman from\nan unwanted marriage, levirate marriage, or in the case of כהן אשת (a priest’s\nwife). These situations led to the enactment of Raban Gamliel and others to\naccept women’s testimony or other inadmissible evidence. Yuval Sinai points\nout that there were other opinions among the Sages, but that the dominant\nopinion was that there should be leniency in cases of עגונה (a chained wife). But\nsuch leniencies do not constitute a lowering of the standard of credibility. The\nquestion of credibility was thus never an acute one. Even in the case of עגינות,\nwhere dissolving a marriage due to factual errors could lead to grave results, it\ndid not stop the Sages from making major concessions in the rules of evidence.\n67 Ibid. 290–93.\n68 b. Yevamot 39b.\n69 m. Ketub. 2, 6–9. The wife of a kohen that was raped is forced to divorce her husband.\n70 b. Ketub. 27 b.; Shulchan Arukh Even Ha’ezer 7,1.\n71 m. Sotah 6,2; m. Sotah 9,8; b. Sotah 31a–b.\n-- 71 of 101 --\n\nIlan Fuchs\t134\nAccepting Women’s Testimony When Determining\nLineage and the Right of the Firstborn\nTractate Qiddushin discusses the trustworthiness of a midwife to give testimony\nabout the lineage of a newborn. Her testimony is sufficient as long as no one\nelse offers contrary information:\nOur Rabbis taught: A midwife is believed when she affirms, “This one is a\npriest, this one is a Levite, this one a נתין (a descendent of the Gibeonites)\nthis one a ממזר [a child born as a result of adultery or incest].” When is that?\nOnly if no protest is raised: but if a protest is raised, she is not believed. What\nkind of a protest? Shall we say, a protest by one person? Surely R. Yochanan\nsaid: A protest is invalid if made by less than two? Hence it means a protest\nby two. Alternatively, I may say [that] after all that it was a protest by one.\nYet when did R. Yochanan say: A protest is invalid if made by less than two?\nOnly where we have a presumption of fitness; but if there is no presumption\nof fitness, even one is believed.72\nThe Ran (Rabbi Nissim ben Reuven Gerondi [late fourteenth century])\nexplains the midwife’s eligibility as a matter of necessity: “Four women give\nbirth in one house: the wife of a priest, the wife of a Levite, the wife of a נתין and\nthe wife of a ממזר. It [the acceptance of the midwife’s testimony] is not from\nthe law, but the Rabbis believed her because in most cases it is impossible to\nfind out any other way.”73 Perhaps he meant this to be a rabbinical decree, but\naccording to the Rash (Rabbi Samson of Sens, ca. 1150–1230), this is a testimony\naccepted according to Torah law:74\n. . . and we did not find that a woman can give testimony, only the one [case]\nin Qiddushin 74 where he said three can testify on the firstborn: a midwife,\nhis father, and his mother. And there we learn we only say so because the\nTorah teaches us that the father makes him known to others; because the\nTorah believed the father even though he is related and a single witness, and\nthe reason is: there is no one else to testify and there is no one else that can\nknow him. From here we learn this is the same reason for the midwife and\nhis mother.75\nThis is not the only place where a woman can give testimony about issues\nthat have to do with medical examinations of women. In tractate Niddah, a\n72 b. Qidd. 73b.\n73 Ran on Rif Qidd. 31a.\n74 See Rabbi Yehoshoua Falk in his commentary Pnei Yehoshoua, ad loc.\n75 Shut Harosh (Responsa of Rabbi Asher ben Yechiel) 52b.\n-- 72 of 101 --\n\nWomen’s Testimony in Jewish Law \t135\nwoman may examine a girl to assess her age for different halakhic procedures\nsuch as the ability to marry etc., and then give testimony because she is the\nonly one who can supply the pertinent information. 76\nMaimonides rules that when a woman claims she has fulfilled all her marital\nduties and her husband denies it, a woman or neighbors should testify.77 Simi-\nlarly, Rif (Alfasi) rules that in a dispute between a woman and her mother-in-law,\nthe courts are to appoint a woman to investigate and then testify before the court\nabout the reasons for the quarrel.78 Rif calls this a custom of the courts, that\nis, it is lacking textual precedent. But the similarity to the case of the midwife\nsuggests a case where sheer necessity dictates accepting women’s testimony.\nIn light of this text the Shulchan Arukh rules: “He claimed that she does not\ndo and she says she does not refrain from doing. They put a woman among\nthem or neighbors.”79 Sixteenth-century rabbi Moses Isserles (the Rema) also\ndeals with the need to use women’s testimony in matters of domestic distur-\nbance in two different places: “ . . . and specifically, when the court sees that\nthere is a merit to