 Testimony in Monetary Issues\nin Ashkenaz between the Twelfth and the Fourteenth\nCenturies: Regulation versus Purposive Interpretation\nNot addressed in geonic sources, the question of women’s testimony does not\nreappear until the rishonic period, when it is discussed both in Ashkenaz and\nSpain. In Ashkenaz, rabbinic discourse makes exceptions to the exclusionary\nrule, although when this began is uncertain. Some opinions root the exceptions\nin an interpretation of the talmudic midwife debate, while others consider them\nan enactment of the early Ashkenazi rabbis.\nThe earliest source to discuss the issue at length is the fourteenth-century\nSefer ha-Agudah by Rabbi Alexander Suslin Hacohen. Since a midwife can give\ntestimony on personal status issues, then women may also testify on matters\nthat take place in the women’s section of synagogues, since women would be\nthe only ones present.82 Rabbi Hacohen sees this as a general principle that\napplies in any case where there is no admissible testimony; that is, he sees the\nability of women to give testimony in such a case not as a matter of enactment\nbut as directly derived from the talmudic discourse.\nA responsum by Rabbi Yisrael Iserline, in his compendium Terumat Ha-\ndeshen, discusses a dispute between two women over ownership of a seat in\nthe women’s section of a synagogue. In this scenario, which, as is most of the\nbook, most likely hypothetical, one woman has one male witness and the other\nhas two female witnesses. Whose testimony should be preferred? The answer\nrefers to the talmudic midwife debate and explains the rationale of the Talmud\nthat, absent male witnesses, testimony from women must be admitted even if\ndamages are awarded.\nThere is a similarity here to the position of the Agudah (Rabbi Alexander\nSuslin Hacohen), namely the element of women’s testimony in a situation where\nthere are no valid witnesses, but there is one major difference: this text is dis-\ncussing a tort case, and in tort cases there are sources which specifically prohibit\nthe use of inadmissible evidence. The Talmud on Bava Qamma 15a requires\nadmissible testimony in a tort case. This stipulation seems puzzling; after all,\nin all cases there needs to be admissible testimony. Maimonides explains that\na court cannot rely on inadmissible testimony since, in most instances, torts\ntake place in locations that will not have admissible witnesses:\n82 Sefer ha-Agudah, ed. Eliezer Brizel (Jerusalem: s.p. 1991); Qidd. 64.\n-- 74 of 101 --\n\nWomen’s Testimony in Jewish Law \t137\nSince we can only find in horses’ stables and the cows’ shed and in the pas-\ntures of sheep and goats only the slaves and the shepherd and others like\nthem, if they testified that this animal damaged another, we hear them. But if\nminors or women testified this man injured another or caused another type\nof damage, we do not rely on them and we do not award damages according\nto witnesses unless these witnesses are admissible . . . 83\nIn the responsum of Terumat Hadeshen and other rishonim, the Talmud’s\nrequirement for admissible testimony in tort cases stems from the frequency\nof such cases and the just as frequent lack of admissible testimony. Although it\nwould seem logical that in a case where there are no admissible witnesses the\ncourt would rely on inadmissible testimony, e.g. women, the Talmud negates\nthis line of thinking.\nBaris sees this responsum as based on Maimonides’ position that the major\nelement of evidentiary law is the internal conviction of the rabbinic judge, even\nif the testimony is inadmissible. In tort law, where the Torah forbids inadmissi-\nble testimony, there are thus no exceptions even if there are grounds to believe\nthe evidence. According to Maimonides, the ability to hear women’s testimony\nin monetary cases is quite minimal and confined to very specific occasions.84 In\nTerumat Hadeshen, Maimonides’ ruling is read as allowing women’s testimony\nas a random, ad hoc occurrence.\nOther texts from Ashkenaz base the admission of women’s testimony in\nmonetary issues on an ancient enactment. Louis Finklestein points out several\nmanuscripts where, in the case of a dispute with no admissible witnesses – only\nrelatives and women – their testimony can be accepted. This enactment is\nattributed to Rabbeinu Gershom Me’or Hagola (ca. 950–1028).85 Another en-\nactment noted in two manuscripts allows relying on the testimony of a relative\nor a woman when dealing with someone who turns Jews in to the non-Jewish\nauthorities.86 One manuscript attributes this enactment to Rabbeinu Tam\n(1100–1171).87 If the enactment indeed stems from Rabbeinu Gershom Me’or\nHagola, then it may be dated to the end of the tenth or the beginning of the\neleventh century.88\n83 Mishneh Torah, Hilkhot Nizkei Mamon\n84 Baris, “עדות להלכות מבוא,” 53. For a similar interpretation see the commentaries of Rabbi Yonatan\nEibeshutz, “Commentaries on the Shulchan Arukh,” Urim 35, 32.\n85 Louis Finklestein, Jewish Self-Government in the Middle Ages (New York: Greenwood Press 1962)\n210.\n86 Ibid. 211.\n87 Ibid. 201.\n88 Avraham Grossman, הראשונים אשכנז חכמי (Jerusalem: Magnes Press, 2001) 110–111. For a general\ndiscussion about his enactments see pages 132–49.\n-- 75 of 101 --\n\nIlan Fuchs\t138\nAttribution of such enactments varies in later generations. For example, some\nAshkenazi texts quote the Mordechai (from a text that is no longer extant) as\nmentioning the enactment of Rabbenu Tam.89 The Rema, in his book Darchei\nMoshe, on Choshen Mishpat section 35, mentions a responsum of the Mordechai\nconcerning laws of excommunication that allows the testimony of a woman\nin an excommunication for disrespecting a Torah scholar. This responsum is\nno longer extant, but the Rema’s citation is partially found in Sefer Hamerot,\nalthough with no mention of the acceptance of inadmissible testimony.90 Others\nrefer to the enactments but without attributing them directly to Rabbenu Tam\nor Rabbenu Gershom Me’or Hagola.91 Rabbi Menachem of Rizbrok (mid-four-\nteenth century) mentions the first enactment, but states that it did not spread\nbeyond the boundaries of France, and also mentions the enactment in the name\nof Rabbeinu Tam concerning Jews who turn in other Jews. He stipulates that\nit is still in effect and that it has the status מיגדר מילתא (ad hoc enactments).92\nParallel Developments in Canon and Secular Law\nUnlike in Spain, women in Ashkenaz took a much more active role in commerce,\nleading to changes in the interpretation of commercial halakhic law. Women\nwere obligated to take oaths, for example, contravening the geonic position.93\nHistorical research into canon and secular law of the High Middle Ages shows a\nsimilar conflict between practical need and traditional interpretations of canon\nlaw minimizing the admissibility of women’s testimony. In the Decretum Gra-\ntiani (ca. 1140), women are generally considered unfit witnesses except in cases\nof infidelity, simony, inheritance, or sexual impotence as grounds for divorce.\nThere was a long list of those ineligible to testify: the excommunicated, heretics,\n89 The Mordechai (Mordechai ben Hillel) was active in Ashkenaz in the second half of the 13th c.\n(Avraham Halperin, השלם המרדכי הלכות לספר מבוא, [Jerusalem: Machon Yerushlaim, 1992], 1–3).\nThe Mordechai mentions that according to the responsa of the geonim, there are eight instances\nwhere women can give testimony, but he does not mention the enactment (Mordechai, Yevamot,\n117).\n90 Written by Meir Ben Shimon Hameeili, Sefer Hamerot contains excerpts of laws of excommu-\nnication from Rabbi Asher Ben Meshulem Ben Yaakov Hacohen Luneil. See: וספר המאורות ספר\nמו״ק וחולין ההשלמה, ed. Yosef Blau (New York: n.p. 1964) 64.\n91 Kolbo, section 116.\n92 R. Menchem of Rizbrok was probably active in the first half of the fourteenth century. His\nrulings were printed at the end of the editions of the responsum of Rabbi Yaakov Ben Yehudah\nWeil (15th c.). On his personal history see: Yitzchak Zimmer, “ונימוקיו מריזברוק מנחם רבי,” Sinai\n78 (1977) 75–88.\n93 Avraham Grossman, ומורדות חסידות (Jerusalem: Zalman Shazar, 2001) 198–206. About other\nchanges in monetary law see 205–6.\n-- 76 of 101 --\n\nWomen’s Testimony in Jewish Law \t139\nJews, pagans, the mentally ill, and minors.94 Twelfth-century canonists often\nminimized the ability of women to give testimony, but practical needs forced\necclesiastical courts to widen the list of exceptions. 95 In matters of lineage and\nfamily relations, for instance, an issue could often only be adjudicated with\nwomen’s testimony. In 1254 Pope Gregory IX added other instances where\nwomen’s testimony was admissible, such as testimony against Jews, testimony\nagainst priests in certain situations, and the marriage of offspring.96\nJames Brundage and Charles Donahue identify a radical gap between the\nwritten law and the legal analysis of scholars, and the reality in the legal tribu-\nnals.97 The process of accepting inadmissible evidence was not specific to wom-\nen but encompassed a long line of evidentiary laws changed in order to better\nfit the England of the Middle Ages. Teachers of law preferred to put forward\nbasic norms and not deal with the exceptions that differed among countries.98\nSimilar conditions prevailed in Germany and Carolingian France. Elizabeth\nVan Houts describes how women in twelfth-century France testified as expert\nwitnesses about physical findings in rape cases, and there were perhaps other\nareas where women could testify as experts, e.g. childbirth, etc.99 She finds\nevidence for similar cases already in ninth-century France and in Saxon En-\ngland.100 The exceptions were the result of necessity: there were cases with no\nother option but to rely on women and minors. Even in church proceedings\nwomen’s testimony was heard in the canonization process.\nVan Houts finds a rationale for such exceptions in the legal texts of the French\nlay jurist Philippe de Beaumanoir (ca. 1280). Along with bastards, lepers, etc.,\nwomen are regarded as poor witnesses. He does note, however, that women\ntestify in questions concerning the age of their children, virginity, cases where\nthere are a least six men present, and, according to custom, also in cases with\n94 James Brundage, “Juridical Space: Female Witnesses in Canon Law,” Dumbarton Oak Papers\n52 (1998) 147–56; Elizabeth Van Houts, “Gender and Authority of Oral Witnesses in Europe”\n(800–1300), Transactions of the Royal Historical Society 9 (1999) 203.\n95 Brundage, “Juridical Space,” 150.\n96 Ibid. 151.\n97 Charles Donahue, “Proof by Witnesses in the Church of Medieval England: An Imperfect\nReception of Learned Law,” in On the Laws and Customs of England: Essays in Honor of Samuel\nE. Thorne, ed. Moriss Arnold, Thomas A. Green, Sally A. Scully, Stephen D. White (Chapel Hill,\nNC: University of North Carolina Press, 1981) 143.\n98 Brundage, “Juridical Space,” 156.\n99 Van Houts, “Gender and Authority,” 204\n100 For the French material see Van Houts, “Gender and Authority,” 205–7. For the Saxon material\nsee: Van Houts, “Gender and Authority,” 208, note 25. Women appear in witness lists from Saxon\nEngland: G. Reeuwijk, “Witnessing to her position – Female Attestations in Mercian Charters\nand the Social Position of Anglo-Saxon Women c. 757–919,” (Master’s thesis, University of\nUtrecht, 2007).\n-- 77 of 101 --\n\nIlan Fuchs\t140\nno male witnesses. This last criterion is identical to the Ashkenazi sources of\nthe period.101 Beaumanoir explains the reluctance to accept women as wit-\nnesses as a consequence of their general unreliability. In like token, canonists\nsaw women as lacking the requisite physical and mental strength to take part\nin most areas of public life. Some Canon texts doubt the ability of women to\ntell the truth.102 Women’s importance grew when there were no men to fulfill\nlegal duties. Many exceptions began to temper the general rule of exclusion,\nand while canon law scholars were skeptical about this process, secular jurists\nsupported it.103\nThere are many parallels between the interpretation of the rishonim of Ash-\nkenaz and ecclesiastical and lay jurists of the period. With a common historical\ncontext and similar legal conclusions, changes in women’s roles in medieval\nsociety in Ashkenaz led to the emergence of legal solutions, however partial,\nto the admissibility of women’s testimony.\nWomen’s Testimony in Tort Cases: Ashkenazic and\nSephardic Interpretations in the 14th–16th Centuries\nLater generations of halakhic authorities were asked to determine the scope\nof the enactment regarding women’s testimony – for example, could they\ntestify in tort cases? The Agudah’s position does not reveal his opinion on the\nmatter, but the Terumat Hadeshen was willing to use women’s testimony only\nin extraordinary cases and not in any situation where there was no admissible\ntestimony. However, he uses this halakhic model in cases other than those that\ninvolved violence.\nThe fifteenth-century Rabbi Yosef Kolon (the Maharik) attributes the en-\nactment to Rabbeinu Tam and quotes it as allowing inadmissible testimony\nnot only in the case of violence, but also when Jews turn in their brethren\nto gentile authorities. He also adds that money or property may be awarded\naccording to a woman’s testimony.104 Ettinger sees this as broadening the\noriginal enactment that dealt with violence, although the Maharik apparently\nrefers to another enactment of unknown provenance dealing with Jews who\ninform on other Jews.\nIn Italy, a contemporary of the Maharik, Rabbi Yehuda Mintz, rabbi of the\nAshkenazi community of Padua, allows the testimony of women where a man\n101 Van Houts, “Gender and Authority,” 210.\n102 Ibid. 211.\n103 Ibid. 220.\n104 Shut Maharik (Responsa of Joseph Colon ben Solomon Trabotto) section 179. Some editions\nnumber this responsum as 180.\n-- 78 of 101 --\n\nWomen’s Testimony in Jewish Law \t141\nclaims that his new wife is not a virgin – a claim that had considerable financial\nimplications in the case of divorce.105 He gives several reasons for his decision:\ncustom may overturn halakhah, a litigant may agree that inadmissible evidence\nwill be introduced in legal proceedings of which he is part, and, finally, he cites\nthe Agudah’s position. Although these exceptions are already made in the\nMishnah, the monetary implications represent a major change. Rabbi Mintz\ngoes even further and says that the enactment also applies to monetary issues,\nsince it is derived from the talmudic principle of הפקר דין בית הפקר, meaning\nthat a rabbinical court has the power to expropriate property. He sees the inter-\npretation of the Agudah as less convincing, and relies heavily on the concept of\nenactment, which is a well-established and well-fortified Ashkenazi tradition.106\nOne of the greatest proponents of Ashkenazi halakhic traditions was Rabbi\nSolomon Luria (The Maharshal, 1510–1573). In Yam shel Shlomo, he dedicates\na long discussion to testimony and inadmissible evidence. It begins with the\nstatements of the Mishnah and Maimonides that, in tort cases, there needs\nto be admissible evidence from which slaves, women, and other inadmissible\nwitnesses are excluded. Prima facie, he explains, in tort cases any person should\nbe believed so the damaged party may be compensated; but the Torah only\nallows admissible evidence. Even in a case where an ox of a non-Jew injures the\nox of a Jew, the non-Jew only pays damages when there is admissible evidence.\nThis raises the question of why non-Jewish witnesses may not be called or why\nwomen may not testify against other women, especially since in non-Jewish\nlegal systems such testimony is acceptable.\nLuria begins his explanation with the statement that the Torah prohibits\nstealing from Jews and non-Jews alike. He does not think that this statement\nis a rabbinical decree broadening the prohibition to non-Jews, but rather that\nthe Torah commands refraining from anything resembling theft. Rabbi Luria’s\nanswer is surprising: “So it will be unthinkable to be lenient in tort testimony\nsince these cases are frequent and it rarely happens that there is admissible\ntestimony.”107 In other words, in a case where a Jew sues a non-Jew and the\nwitnesses whom the Jew brings are non-Jews, the Jew cannot be awarded\ndamages, even though, had the case been heard in non-Jewish courts, the\nnon-Jew would have lost.\nThe Maharshal holds that legal reasoning taken from non-Jewish legal sys-\ntems justifying acceptance of inadmissible evidence is not relevant, and since\n105 Shut Mahari Mintz (Responsa of Rabbi Judah ben Eliezer), section 6.\n106 Shut Maharam Mintz (Responsa of Rabbi Moses Halevi Mintz; Machon Yerushalaim Edition),\n93, paragraphs 4 and 5. For a biography of Rabbi Moshe Mintz see Shlomo Tal (מהר״מ) משה ״רבי\nמינץ״, Sinai 40 (1957) 228–47, 278–95.\n107 Yam Shel Shlomo, B. Qam., Ch. 1, section 41\n-- 79 of 101 --\n\nIlan Fuchs\t142\nstealing from a non-Jew is prohibited, there is no option to turn to non-Jewish\nlegal systems, because adjudicating tort cases according to non-Jewish legal\nnorms, even though they have internal logic, is tantamount to stealing. Foreign\nlegal systems were believed to lack a spiritual essence only found in the Torah.108\nRabbi Luria maintains that the enactment attributed to Rabbeinu Tam may\nno longer be valid:\nIt is also possible that the words of Rabbeinu Tam are an enactment. For his\ntime and his generation he made it as a fence. And this enactment did not\nspread, since among our forefathers, the Tosefists, and after them Rabbeinu\nAsher and the Tur, no one has mentioned it. . . . And I have seen in the re-\nsponsum of Rabbi Pinchas Meil-tzedek, who wrote in the name of ancient\nones, that they decreed that one woman or one relative and also a minor\ncan say that he saw that someone beat another. And also when there is no\ntime to invite admissible witnesses. . . . And I do not accept his words at all, in\nmy opinion, even if you want to say that this is an enactment of the geonim.\nAfter all, in the days of the Talmud we do not find a hint of this. Specifically,\nsince it is said clearly in the Mishnah according to admissible witnesses, etc.,\nand this comes to exclude [referring to Maimonides’ interpretation that the\nMishnah excludes the idea of accepting inadmissible evidence when there\nis no other evidence]. And if there were an enactment in the days of the\nTalmud it is impossible that they did not write it down.109\nFrom his statement about Rabbi Pinchas (actually referring to Rabbi Menachem\nof Rizbrok), that even if this is an enactment of the geonim, he does not have\na coherent tradition about the origins of the enactment or its scope and use as\na basis for accepting inadmissible evidence.\nRabbi Luria accepts the interpretation of the talmudic midwife debate and\ndeduces that there is an option to accept women’s testimony even in tort cases:\nShe is trusted to say immediately about two males who is the firstborn, or if\none is male and one is female, who was born first, since it is readily apparent\nthat one of them came after the other. It is just a question [concerning who\nis the firstborn] before us. On this and similar issues they are to be trusted.\nAlso concerning an ox that rammed the cow, if her fetus was found next to it\nand it is not known, etc. Here also it seems that the inadmissible [witnesses]\nare trusted in a place where it is uncommon to find admissible witnesses.\nWhen it is known that a tort event took place, it is permissible to hear women’s\n108 Such arguments can be found in halakhic literature from a very early time, cf. Midrash Tannaim\nLesefer Devarim (Hoffmann Edition), 16, 17.\n109 Yam Shel Shlomo, B. Qam, Ch. 1, section 41\n-- 80 of 101 --\n\nWomen’s Testimony in Jewish Law \t143\ntestimony to find out the details of the event, but not whether or not it actually\noccurred.\nHe rejects the validity of the enactment of Rabbeinu Tam since its prove-\nnance and tradition are unclear, but he interprets the midwife debate to rule\nthat one may accept the testimony of inadmissible witnesses when there is no\ndisagreement about the occurrence of an event, but only about its details. He\nthus includes tort law in the exceptions to the laws of evidence.\nThe position of Rabbi Moshe Isserles (Rema) of Krakow also reflects the\nAshkenazi tradition:\nAnd all those who are ineligible witnesses, are ineligible even in a place where\nit is uncommon for admissible witnesses to be found and all this is according\nto law, but there are those who say that the enactment of the ancients is that\nin a place that men do not frequent like the women’s section of a synagogue\nor regarding a random thing that a woman is used to doing, not men, for\nexample, to say that these clothes are worn by a specific woman and that\nthey are hers and men are not used to noticing this, women are admissible.\nTherefore, there is one who wrote that even one woman, or a relative, or a\nminor, is trusted in a matter of beating or dishonoring a Torah scholar or\nother disputes and in cases of informing since there is no way to summon\nadmissible evidence to this.110\nThe Rema seems to adopt the position of Terumat Hadeshen and does not allow\nwomen’s testimony in tort cases. The Rema lists physical assault, the dishonoring\nof a Torah scholar and unspecified “other disputes,” but tort cases are absent.\nThis is also the understanding of Rabbi Yehoshua Falk in his interpretation of\nShulchan Arukh Sefer Meirat Einayim. He comments that the Rema only men-\ntions women’s testimony in section 35, but in section 408, where the Shulchan\nArukh cites Maimonides that in tort cases inadmissible testimony is never used,\nthe Rema stays silent. He explains that the Rema adopted the ruling of Terumat\nHadeshen, and therefore in a tort case women cannot give testimony.111\nAnother contemporary Ashkenazi decisor was Rabbi Mordechai Jaffe, author\nof the halakhic code Levush Malchut. In his rulings on Choshen Mishpat, he\nwrites in a similar manner to the Rema, but mentions that the source of the\nrule is an ancient enactment and not the interpretation of the talmudic mid-\nwife discussion.112 Ettinger believes that the Rema adopts the opinion that the\nenactment was the source of the custom to accept women’s testimony where\n110 Rema, Choshen Mishpat, 35, 14.\n111 עיניים מאירת ספר, 30, 35.\n112 Levush, Chosen Mishpat, 35, 14.\n-- 81 of 101 --\n\nIlan Fuchs\t144\nthere are no men and that later on, the other instances, such as physical assault,\nwere added as examples.\nPrimarily referring to a responsum of Rabbi Solomon ben Adret (Rashba)\nconcerning a woman’s ownership of a seat in a synagogue, Ettinger points out\nthat Sephardic rabbis take a quite different approach to the texts.113 Though\nsimilar to Terumat Hadeshen, the responsum starts from quite a different\npoint of view:\nYou should know that the testimony of women, even if there are a thousand,\nthey are all worth one testimony and their testimony is not in the category\nof testimony, only in the matter of איסור (a prohibition). And I see from the\npamphlet you wrote where you stand on the issue of women’s testimony,\nand you perhaps found one of the rishonim about places where women sit\nin synagogues because it is a special place for women and men do not enter\nwhen women sit there and we do not know these things and never heard\nthem and they should not be relied upon.114\nThe Rashba adamantly rejects the idea later found in Terumat Hadeshen. He\nmentions that in some communities women’s testimony is accepted in such\nan instance, but he is firmly opposed. The Rashba explains that the talmudic\ndebate about the midwife is different: “There it is different since it is impossible\nany other way since men do not assist women in childbirth.” He explains that\nthe exception in cases of chained women is because of the severity of the case.\nIn other instances, such as b. Niddah allowing women’s findings after physical\nexamination of other women, this is not an issue of testimony, but mere cor-\nroboration of a fact. In monetary questions, however, women’s accounts may\nnot constitute testimony.\nThe Sephardic Position in Responsa Literature\nin the Sixteenth Century and Onward\nIn the eleventh- and twelfth-century Islamic world, women’s involvement in\ncommerce was minimal and did not appreciably increase in thirteenth- and\nfourteenth-century Muslim Spain.115 Research on the Geniza shows a similar\nabsence of women in the commercial life of Egypt.116 Unlike in Ashkenaz,\n113 Ettinger, “כעד אישה”\n114 Shut Harashba (Responsa of Rabbi Solomon ben Adret), vol. 5, section 139.\n115 Grossman, ומורדות חסידות, 181. For extraordinary cases of women’s involvement, 188–95.\n116 Shelomo Dov Goitein, A Mediterranean Society: The Jewish Communities of the Arab World\nas Portrayed in the Documents of The Cairo Geniza, vol. 3, The Family (Berkeley: University of\nCalifornia Press, 1967–1973) 324–41.\n-- 82 of 101 --\n\nWomen’s Testimony in Jewish Law \t145\nwomen were not in positions that allowed them to take part in commercial life\nand therefore to become potential witnesses. This social reality is reflected in\nthe halakhic literature from these communities. Probably written in thirteenth-\ncentury Spain, the Sefer Ha-Chinuch explains: “women are not in the category of\nadmissible witnesses because of their lightheadedness.”117 The Shulchan Arukh\nfollows the Rashba, and did not adopt the Ashkenazi tradition.118\nRabbi Jacob Castro from sixteenth-century Egypt writes that in Sephardic\ncommunities the position of the Shulchan Arukh is followed, and no one is\nlenient like Terumat Hadeshen or the Maharik.119 His contemporary Rabbi\nDavid Ben Zimra, however, ruled that in a case where a woman’s testimony\nconcerns clothing worn by another woman, since men do not look at women’s\nclothing with expert eyes, women’s testimony is admissible. He explains this\nruling by using the responsum of Terumat Hadeshen and differentiates it from\nthe case of tort law, adding that since men never look at women’s clothing this\ncase is similar to the case of the midwife.120\nIn a similar matter Rabbi Jonah Navon, a decisor from Jerusalem in the\nfirst half of the eighteenth century and part of the Ladino-speaking commu-\nnity, discussed a petition to divorce a woman against her will. The husband\nsaid that even though he took an oath not to divorce his wife against her will,\nsince his wife is immodest, smokes, spits, and curses, he should be allowed to\ndivorce her. Rabbi Navon declared that without testimony from two credible\nwitnesses a woman cannot be divorced against her will. Even though men are\nrarely present in such situations, it is impossible to rely on Ashkenazi decisors\nlike Terumat Hadeshen, Rema, and others, since the Shulchan Arukh did not\naccept their position. In the case of סוטה (suspected wife), women’s testimony\nis only admissible when establishing that a woman was fornicating, but a wom-\nan cannot testify to fulfill the procedural demands, that is, the circumstantial\nevidence that the woman was alone with a man sufficiently long for sexual\nintercourse to have taken place. A woman may thus not testify about another\nwoman’s behavior; only about actually seeing her in flagrante.121\nOwnership of the seat in the women’s section of the synagogue is again ad-\ndressed in a responsum of the seventeenth-century Rabbi Shlomo Halevi, who\n117 החינוך ספר 122. In a commentary on this book called חינוך מנחת Rabbi Yosef Babad mentions\nad loc that where women’s testimony is accepted, damages can be awarded, e.g., testimony on\ndeath or impurity.\n118 Shulchan Arukh Choshen Mishpat 14, 35.\n119 Jacob Castro, Erech Lechem (Istanbul: 1718) section 35, 14.\n120 Responsa of David Ben Zimra (Jerusalem: 1987) vol. 1, section 366.\n121 Yona Navon, Nechpa Bekesef, vol. 2 (Istanbul: 1843), EH section 12.\n-- 83 of 101 --\n\nIlan Fuchs\t146\nconcludes that if the author of Terumat Hadeshen had seen the responsum of\nthe Rashba, he would have retracted his ruling.122\nThe Sephardic negation of the Ashkenazic model of women’s testimony\nwas also put to the test in difficult cases. Rabbi Uziel Al-Chayek from eigh-\nteenth-century Tunisia, for example, wrote that in a case where a woman alleges\nphysical abuse by her husband and brings testimony of women to support\nher claim, that testimony cannot be used. After surveying the opinions of the\nrishonim, he concludes that because all major Sephardic rabbis object, it is\nimpossible to accept a woman’s testimony. The only recourse is to require her\nhusband to take an oath.123\nRabbi Yosef David from Salonika discusses a similar situation in his book\nBeit David. Although the question was not printed, the answer was printed in\nfull. The first half of the discussion concerns the difference of opinion about\nwomen’s testimony, whether from an enactment or as corollary to the talmudic\nmidwife debate. According to the Maharik, Rabbi David notes, admissibility of\nwomen’s testimony stems from an enactment; but since neither Maimonides,\nRashba, or the Shulchan Arukh were aware of it, its application must remain\nminimal, that is, permitted in an assault case, but not permitted to resolve a\nmonetary issue.124\nThe second part of the responsum broadens the issue to include the power of\nrabbis to enact. Enactments should only be used in rare cases, and the power\nto issue them is limited. Evidentiary laws cannot be subject to change when\ndiscussing issues governed by Torah law; those subject to change are only those\nwhich result from other rabbinical enactments. Rabbi David conveys a concern\nabout giving the power of enactment to communal bodies and thus minimizing\nthe relevancy of Torah law. His objection to accepting women’s testimony is the\nfact that the origin of this acceptance was in an enactment, which he sees as\na dangerous blow to the most basic elements of the halakhic system. Though\naware of the problem of not using the Ashkenazi model, he is forced to make\na hard decision because of the danger he sees to the system as a whole.\nOne case best exemplifies the inherent tension between halakhic evidentiary\nlaws and the day-to-day activities of rabbinical courts. Treated at length in a\nresponsum from Rabbi Chaim Palagi, who lived in Izmir in the nineteenth\ncentury and was one of Turkey’s leading rabbis, the question deals with a\nteacher accused of repeatedly sexually assaulting children. 125 Testimony was\ngiven by a boy under 13 years of age whose father had had a previous quarrel\n122 Sholomo Halevi, Responsa of Rabbi Shlomo Halevi (Salonika: 1652), EH section 38.\n123 Uziel Al-Chayek, Mishkenot Haroim (Livorno: 1860) Maarechet Ayin, 65.\n124 Yosef David, Beit David, vol. 2 (Salonika: 1740), section 6.\n125 Chaim Palagi, Chikekey Lev, vol. 1 (Salonika: 1840) YD section 47.\n-- 84 of 101 --\n\nWomen’s Testimony in Jewish Law \t147\nwith the teacher. Rabbi Palagi asks whether inadmissible testimony maybe\ntaken into account in such a serious case. He mentions the different opinions\nof Terumat Hadeshen, the Agudah, and the Maharik, and says that it perhaps\nwould be appropriate to apply their opinions to this case, but, given the prior\nacrimonious relationship between father and teacher, the court should conduct\na meticulous investigation, since the minor could have been induced to give\nfalse testimony. His final ruling is that in light of the opinion of the Shulchan\nArukh and the discussion in the responsum Beit David, the Ashkenazi enact-\nment may not be applied. It is impossible to fire the teacher with no proper\nevidence, and all that can be done is to take serious precautions to make sure\nthe accusations are false.\nThe Sephardic position negates both the Ashkenazi interpretation of the\ntalmudic debate in Qiddushin and the validity of the Ashkenazi enactment,\nan attitude which remains extremely stable into the modern age. Even though\nthe difficulties arising from this rule of exclusion are obvious, especially in a\nchild molestation case, abolishing such a basic evidentiary rule comes at too\nhigh a cost for the Sephardic halakhic tradition.\nResponsa from the Modern Period\nIn the Modern period, discussions about women’s testimony become scarce,\nnot least because in modern states with advanced legal systems rabbinical\ncourts have lost any official status. Even within Jewish communities the courts\nhave ceased being a legal authority for all Jews. This has created a gap between\nhalakhic laws of evidence and the modern world. Traditional laws of evidence\nwere challenged by forensic evidence achieved by technological means as well\nas by testimony valid in secular courts but inadmissible under the halakhic\nsystem. Even in Ashkenazi communities, however, some of the halakhic discus-\nsions have taken a more restrictive, rather than a permissive approach. Among\nthose with more restrictive opinions were Rabbi Yonatan Eibeshutz, and also\nRabbi Jacob of Lisa, the author of Netivot Mishpat, wherein he states: “This\nenactment was not made for routine events because every unrighteous man\nwill hire gentiles and ineligible witnesses to testify that someone else damaged\nhim.”126 This change from the classic Ashkenazic tradition raises the question\nof why the shift towards a minimizing interpretation occurred. Perhaps it was\nbecause the sources advocating accepting women’s testimony in monetary\nissues are not clear, in the sense that they are not talmudic and originate from\neither an enactment with debatable scope or based on the midwife debate – an\n126 Urim 35:23; Netivot Mishpat Chidushim section 35.\n-- 85 of 101 --\n\nIlan Fuchs\t148\ninterpretation not widely accepted. One can also speculate that in an era where\nsecularization and reform are getting stronger, such interpretations are less\nfeasible – a similar position to the responsum in Beit David.\nIn 1782, Rabbi Ezekiel Landau of Prague, the author of responsum Noda\nBeyehuda, was asked to rule on a complaint of theft based on the testimony of\nwomen who claimed to see a man with the stolen property. The court could not\ndetermine whether this was a case where women’s testimony could be accepted.\nIn the responsum, Landau writes that this is not such a case, since it is not a\nsituation where it is uncommon to find admissible witnesses. He limits the\nenactment to physical assault and informing. About the relationship between\nthe enactment and the discussion on the midwife he writes:\nAs much as men are not regularly present there, so women are not regularly\nthere. Even so women are believed. But the root of the matter is that in a\nplace where women are regularly found and men are not regularly found,\nthen women are believed, and not because of the enactment separately. There\nis a source for this from the words of the Talmud that a midwife is believed\nwhen she says this is the firstborn. But in matters of fights and beatings\nand informing where in the same manner that men are not regularly there,\nso women are not regularly there [the ruling is accepted] only because of\nthe enactment of the Sages since the matter is uncommon and happened\nsuddenly and there is no time to invite eligible witnesses. Thus the ancients\nenacted to believe the women.127\nSo is theft a common occurrence? Apparently not, since it is a rare event and far\nfrom the public eye. However, this is not the opinion of Rabbi Landau. Since the\nfemale witnesses only saw the stolen property in the hands of the accused and\nnot the actual act of theft, he concludes that their testimony is inadmissible.\nIn his responsum Knesset Yechezkel, Yechezkel Katzenellenbogen does not\nsee the enactment as a broad enough basis for accepting inadmissible testimony.\nPuzzled by the phrasing of the Rema, he explains that the enactment may only\napply when there is no actual disagreement of fact. The only need for testimony\nis to fill in the details. This is a similar line of thinking to that of Rabbi Luria\nand the Maharam Mintz.128 The broadest approach to the issue is found in the\nruling of Rabbi Yechiel Michel Epstein, who allowed the acceptance of women’s\ntestimony in tort cases:\nAnd therefore it seems the rule is that if the court does not see any merit in\nthe plaintiff ’s claim and the person accused completely denies the charges,\n127 Yechezkel Landau, Noda BeYehudah, Tinyana (Jerusalem: 2008) Choshen Mishpat section 58.\n128 Yechezkel Katzenellenbogen, Knesset Yechezkel (Brooklyn: 1967) Choshen Mishpat, section 83.\n-- 86 of 101 --\n\nWomen’s Testimony in Jewish Law \t149\nwe do not rule according to them [the inadmissible witnesses]. But if ac-\ncording to the impression of the court, the damage [claim] is true, we do\nrule according to them [the inadmissible witnesses] to obligate the person\ncausing damage. And if you do not agree, they will destroy fields and gardens\nand orchards and no one could say return [the damages you caused]; and\nthis seems to be the law.129\nThe issue of accepting women’s testimony has ramifications beyond mere\nprocedure, evoking such issues as women’s rights, perceptions about women\nand their role in public life, and epistemology. One of the first texts to deal\nwith the issue in this broader context was written by Rabbi Chaim Hirschen-\nsohn. Hirschensohn’s text is not a traditional responsum, but rather a theoretic\nhalakhic debate; it is also not written in traditional halakhic language. He ap-\nproaches the subject through his democratic worldview and his wish to align\nhis support of human rights with halakhic texts. He explains the exclusion\nof women’s testimony as being rooted in theology: it is not that women lack\nunderstanding and thus their testimony is admissible, but rather, their exclu-\nsion is simply a decree of the Torah without human reason. His conclusion is\nthat evidence in Jewish law is not grounded in a procedural law attempting to\ngovern society, but in a religious need.130 The Sages do not perceive women as\ncongenital liars, he explains, and expressions about women being “lightheaded”\nonly mean that women are more delicate than men. When a rabbinic judge\ndecides by אומדנא (estimation) it is allowed to accept women’s testimony even\naccording to Maimonides and the Rashba.131 On the other hand, Hirschensohn\ncriticizes western legal systems that accept the testimony of felons and other\nwitnesses of dubious credibility:\nWhat they do in the courts of the nations when they rule based on one of\nthe criminals that confessed and testifies against the rest is really one of the\nunjust laws in their legal system. And they also multiply murderers, thieves,\nand robbers in the land, and the judges spill innocent blood. And the civ-\nilization should hasten to abolish them [these evidentiary laws] and even\nmore so, this should not be done in Israel.132\n129 Arukh HaShulchan, Choshen Mishpat 408, 2.\n130 Chaim Hirschensohn, Malki Bakodesh, vol. 2 (St. Louis: n.p, 1921), 176. For a similar interpre-\ntation see Rabbi Moshe Botzko, “?ולדון להעיד פסולה האישה האם” Qol MeHekhal 9 (1999) 125–30.\nFor more about Rabbi Hirschensohn and his halakhic and theological views see: David Zohar,\nהמודרנה אל ויחסו הירשנזון חיים הרב – מודרני בעולם יהודית מחויבות (Jerusalem: Machon Shalom Hartman,\n2003); Eliezer Schweid, הירשנזון חיים הרב של במשנתו עיון פרקי והלכה דמוקרטיה (Jerusalem: Magnes\nPress, 1997).\n131 Chaim Hirschensohn, Malkei Bakodesh, 177.\n132 Ibid. 178.\n-- 87 of 101 --\n\nIlan Fuchs\t150\nWe see from these sources that a discussion on procedure and laws of ev-\nidence became a part of the larger conflict between halakhic literature and\nmodernity. This question was tied into debates on women’s roles and nature,\nand later discussions continue to address these questions.\nContemporary Discussion on Women’s Testimony\nThe issue of women’s testimony was also debated in the state rabbinical courts in\nIsrael. The geopolitical situation in modern Israel, a state with a non-religious\nmajority and a secular political elite that gave Jewish law a role in personal status\nissues, led some rabbinic figures to support a minimal approach to women’s\ntestimony. The first chief rabbi of the independent state of Israel, Isaac Her-\nzog, wrote extensively about halakhah and its place in modern life, especially\nin modern Israel.133 His original opinion, from 1948, is no longer extant and\nis only cited in a legal ruling edited by the future chief rabbi Rabbi Avraham\nShapira and Zerach Varhaftig, who later became a prominent Israeli politician.\nThe case dealt with an accusation of domestic violence against a woman which\nwas supported by other women’s testimony.134 Herzog references both the\nRema’s ruling about the decree concerning fights and quarrels and the Noda\nBeyehudah’s opinion that women may only testify about events occurring where\nmen are not regularly present. However, he also adds a third reason: when the\nrabbinic judge “knows that the claims are true and it is set in the heart of the\nrabbinic judge that this is indeed so, we rely also on inadmissible testimony.”135\nEach of these reasons goes beyond the scope presented in earlier sources; for\nexample, no one interpreted the enactment as relating to a domestic dispute.\nThe responsum of the Noda Beyehudah and others defines very narrowly a\nsituation where only women are present, and a family quarrel does not neces-\nsarily fall under such a definition. Finally, the third and broadest reason uses\nMaimonides’ opinion that evidence laws are needed only if the rabbinic judge\nlacks internal conviction regarding the facts.136 Even though this opinion could\nhave had major ramifications, it seems to have been set aside. In a 1959 opinion\n133 Chaim Brogansky, “ישראל למדינת ישראלי שאול והרב הרצוג י׳ הרב של ההלכתי יחסם וממלכה קהילה,” in\nShenaton Dat u-Medinah beHagut haYehudit beMeah ha 20, ed. Aviezer Ravitzky (Jerusalem:\nHamachon Hayisraeli Ledemokratya, 2005). For another discussion about his legal perceptions\nsee: Moshe Hershkovitz, “העברי המשפט במחקר הרצוג ״הלוי אייזיק יצחק הרב של ושיטתו דרכו” (Master’s\nthesis, Bar Ilan University, 2008).\n134 The opinion was given in the case B. D. R. 143708 and published in הראשית הרבנות של הדין פסקי אוסף\nלערעורים הגדול הדין בית :ישראל לארץ, ed. Zerach Warhaftig (Jerusalem: Misrad HaMishpatim, 1985)\n11–15. Names of the litigants were not mentioned.\n135 Osef Piskei Din 12–13.\n136 Baris, “עדות להלכות מבוא”, 3.\n-- 88 of 101 --\n\nWomen’s Testimony in Jewish Law \t151\nof the rabbinical court ruling on a dispute over the ownership of a burial plot, a\nquestion arose about inadmissible testimony. The court found that it could not\nsay that the enactment allowed all inadmissible evidence in monetary issues.\nRabbi Herzog returns to this issue in a letter criticizing a 1950 law passed\nby the Israeli Parliament mandating gender equality. The first section of the\nlaw decrees that a woman is capable of all legal actions as are men – a con-\ntradiction of the Torah, Rabbi Herzog finds, since women are ineligible to\ngive testimony. There are exceptions to this rule such as אישה עדות (testimony\nconcerning a chained women), he notes, also referring to Choshen Mishpat\nsection 35. Legitimizing women’s testimony completely, however, he believes\nsends a dangerous message:\nThe laws of the Holy Torah to which we submit, whether we understand in\nour limited human mind or whether we do not understand, clearly are not\naimed to denigrate woman’s human value. The peak of human perfection is\nwithout a doubt prophecy. And in that the woman is equal to man! . . . It is\nclear that on the presumption that the prophet is the peak, there is no ques-\ntion. . . . It is possible that the explanation [regarding women’s ineligibility\nto testify] is based on the unique psyche of the fairer sex, referring to their\nsuperior power of imagery that can affect memory.137\nElsewhere he holds that the Sanhedrin itself could not have legitimized tes-\ntimony of women in all cases, and in a letter of March 18, 1951, speculates\nthat one of the reasons women are not good witnesses is an irritation of the\nnerves during menstruation, citing medical literature from the beginning of\nthe century as proof.138 Concerning אומדנא (estimation) to legitimize women’s\ntestimony, he notes:\n. . . we must leave much to the אומדנא (estimation) of the rabbinic judges and\nI have written extensively on this in my book about law in the state of Israel.\nBut in monetary issues that do not fall under the structure of criminal law,\nthe difficulty is indeed great. And even though in specific cases, the rabbinic\njudge in monetary issues can rule according to what his heart tells him is\ntrue, these cases are extraordinary. . . . 139\nThis statement conflicts with his legal opinion from 1948 that supported the\nadmissibility of women’s testimony, a contrast in even greater relief in his\npublished views on law, where he does not take a liberal stance toward issues\n137 Isaac Herzog, התורה פי על לישראל תחוקה vol. 3 (Jerusalem: Mosad Harav Kook, 1989) 56–57\n(henceforth לישראל תחוקה).\n138 Ibid., 64, note 34.\n139 Ibid., vol. 1, 216.\n-- 89 of 101 --\n\nIlan Fuchs\t152\nof constitutionality and human rights. His willingness to adopt liberal legal\nmodels was apparently the result of political necessity. His desire to bridge the\ngap between halakhah and the Israeli legal system, coupled with what he saw\nas the negligible political power of the religious community, led him to accept\nthese models while trying to legitimize them retroactively from a halakhic\nperspective.140 The inadmissibility of women’s testimony troubles him less\nfrom a gender perspective than from a legal one. While he understands that\nthis exclusionary rule impedes the daily activity of religious courts, he is afraid\nof any action that would undermine Torah law.\nRabbi Herzog points out several cases where the accepted interpretation of\ncertain halakhic concepts impedes the routine activity of the rabbinical courts.\nHe is especially critical of the procedural claim of לי קים, a procedural rule\nwhich allows a litigant to claim that his position is supported by a halakhic\nopinion, even if a minority one, thus avoiding awarding the claim against him.\nRabbi Herzog sees this legal strategy as a serious danger to halakhah as a legal\nsystem for day-to-day life. He supported limiting this rule either by enactment\nor other tools; for example, דינא דמלכותא דינא (the law of the land is the law).141\nThis tension between his desire to integrate halakhah with secular law in\nmodern Israel versus his difficulties suggesting radical interpretations to ca-\nnonical texts also permeates his writings concerning the testimony of secular\nJews. Rabbi Herzog was aware that fulfilling his goal to follow Torah law in\nIsrael forced a change in his approach to such testimony. Since he was also\nconvinced that secularism was not synonymous with unreliable behavior, he\nwas able to turn in another direction.142\nOn the other hand, he feared creating legal mechanisms that would sur-\nreptitiously introduce secular law into halakhah. For example, he rejected\nthe model presented by the Ran that suggests that halakhah does not have a\nrole in socio-political reality but has only a legal function.143 He rejects this\nnotion completely because its acceptance would result in the nullification of\nthe realistic validity of Torah law. A defendant being acquitted according to\n140 For a similar discussion about his ideas concerning the enactment of rules equating the inher-\nitance rights of daughters and sons, see Binyamin Brown, המהפכה ומנהיג המאמין ,הפוסק איש חזון\nהחרדית (Jerusalem: Magnes Press: 2011) 668–76.\n141 Herzog, לישראל תחוקה, vol. 2, 72. See also Menachem Elon,העברי המשפט, vol. 3, 3rd ed. (Jerusalem:\nMagnes Press, 1992) 1062–63; Chanina Ben Menachem, “יוריספונדנטי ניתוח לקראת – לי קים טענת,”\nShenaton HaMishpat HaIvri 6–7 (1979–1980) 45–60.\n142 Anat Navot, “בפרהסיה שבתות מחללי של ועדותן הרצוג הרב,” in הבאר פי על, ed. Uri Ehrlick, Daniel\nLasker, Hayyim Krisel (Beer Sheva: Ben Gurion University Press, 2008) 251–387.\n143 Drashot Haran (Mosad Harav Kook) section 11.\n-- 90 of 101 --\n\nWomen’s Testimony in Jewish Law \t153\nthe halakhic evidentiary laws, yet convicted under המלך משפט (literally “the\nlaws of the king”), makes a farce of the rabbinical court.144\nA contemporary of Rabbi Herzog, and his partner in many ways in develop-\ning the religious and political vision of religious Zionism, was Rabbi Ben-Tzion\nUziel, the Sephardic Chief Rabbi of pre-state Israel and the first Sephardic\nrabbi of the state of Israel. Uziel came from Salonika, where he was a rabbi,\nand later became the rabbi of Tel Aviv, the Chief Rabbi, and the head of the\nHigh Rabbinical Court.145 He ruled that an enactment may legitimize women’s\ntestimony because there is no problem with women’s credibility. The reason for\ntheir exclusion from testimony was that they did not deal in commerce and\ntherefore had a skewed view of monetary issues. That is why in issues such as\nchained women, etc. women are accepted as witnesses.\nIn an article published in the religious newspaper Hatzofe about the 1950\ngender equality law, Rabbi Uziel claimed that there was no purpose in looking\nfor a reason for women’s inability to serve as witnesses. This reality, he asserted,\nneeds to be accepted as a decree and in some cases it can be legitimized.146 In\nhis book of responsa, he dedicated several debates to dealing with legitimizing\ninadmissible evidence: evidence gained from minors, women, secular Jews,\nnon-Jews, and evidence that was obtained by recording. In a responsum dealing\nwith women’s inadmissibility, he noted that there are sources that suggest that\nwomen are suspected of lying, for example, the fact that women are named in\nMishnah Rosh Hashanah together with gamblers, etc. He also mentioned the\nopinion of the Tosefta Ketubbot which says women are suspected of giving\nunreliable testimony.147 But he noted that most sources do not use this justifi-\ncation, a stance which is supported by the lack of a biblical verse which states\nthat women are excluded from giving testimony. If women were suspected of\nhabitually lying, there is no need for a verse and this perception is good enough\nto explain the exclusion. He also notes that there seems to be a direct approach\nby the Toseftists that women are not excluded from testimony because they are\nsuspected of lying.148 But even more than this, the fact that women’s testimony\nis accepted in many cases – chained women, for example, and many other\npersonal status issues – negates the idea that they are suspected of lying. This\nis also the opinion of Terumat Hadeshen, which regards texts suggesting that\n144 Herzog, לישראל תחוקה, vol. 1, 166–67.\n145 Amichai Radzyner, “מערכות בארבע סיפור :לערעורים הגדול הדין ובית ,יפו-תל־אביב רבנות ,עוזיאל הרב,”\nMecharei Mishpat 21 (2004) 129–243. For a discussion about his halakhic perceptions see Bin-\nyamin Lau, “גיור בנושא עוזיאל הרב של פסיקתו בשיקולי הנביאים מוסר “ביקשתם לא האובדת ואת,” Akadamot\n21 (2008) 96–109.\n146 Herzog, לישראל תחוקה vol. 1, 166–67.\n147 See page 126, above.\n148 Tosefot Zevach. 103a.\n-- 91 of 101 --\n\nIlan Fuchs\t154\nwomen are suspected of lying as a minority opinion. Therefore, Rabbi Uziel\nconcludes, there is no reason to reject the opinion of the Ashkenazi sources or\neven to enact a new rule to legitimize women’s testimony. Although a Sephardic\ndecisor, Rabbi Uziel goes against Sephardic tradition and accepts Ashkenazi\ninterpretation.149 He concludes:\nAnd so now that we have explained that women are not suspected of lying,\ntherefore the reason for their exclusion is that they are not accurate, meaning\nthey are not accustomed to dealing with commerce and other monetary\nissues. So they cannot get a clear image in understanding the matter they\nsaw with their own eyes and they might be mistaken with similar things and\ninadvertently give an unreliable and inaccurate testimony. But in everything\nwhich is merely מילתא גילוי [A statement not considered testimony which can\nbe validated from other sources, thus believed even from someone ineligible\nto give testimony] or when they are accustomed to [the situation] and are\naccurate about [it], their testimony is accepted. Everything they are used to\ndoing and understand thoroughly, on that the Talmud says “and God gave\nwomen extra wisdom” [b. Niddah 45]. On this element is founded the enact-\nment of the ancients that where men are not regularly present, for example\nthe women’s section of a synagogue or regarding other random things that\na woman regularly does and not men, for example, to say that these clothes\nwere worn by this women and since men are not regularly attentive to that,\nwomen are trusted [Chosen Mishpat section 35, 14]. And according to this,\nthe community is allowed to enact, with everyone’s agreement that women’s\ntestimony will be accepted. In the same manner [their agreement] is sufficient\nto enact that relatives’ testimony would be accepted. 150\nRabbi Uziel acted with a deep sense of commitment to the Zionist enterprise.\nHis attempts to integrate halakhah into a predominantly secular Israeli society\nwith liberal values forced him to offer many innovative interpretations. Because\nof his deep commitment to the Jewish community and its unity, he took posi-\ntions contrary to Sephardic halakhic tradition.151 This is another example of\n149 This is not the first time he chose to diverge from Sephardic tradition. He was criticized by\nRabbi Ovadya Yosef many times for this tendency. See: Benyamin Lau, להח־ אעמודה משמרתי ׳על ״\nבארץ־ישראל״ הספרדית ההלכה לשמירת יוסף עובדיה הרב של מאבקו ליושנה׳ עטרה זיר, in יצירה הריבונות אתגר\nלמדינה הראשון בעשור והגות, ed. Mordechai Bar-on (Jerusalem: Yad Ben-Tzvi, 1999) 214–27; ״הרב\nההלכה״ בשדה האומה אחדות :עוזיאל ב״צ, in ישראל של בראשיתה ומדינה דת :הגשר עברי שני, ed. Mordechai\nBar-on (Jerusalem: Yad Ben-Tzvi, 2002) 297–319.\n150 Ben-Tzion Uziel, Mishpatei Uziel, vol. 4 (Jerusalem, 2000). Choshen Mishpat section 20.\n151 Tzvi Zohar, “עדות פסולי בהגדרת’ עוזיאל הרב של במאמרו עיון – ההלכה לעיצוה הכנסת אחריות’,” in תרבותיות רב\nז״ל רוזן־צבי לאריאל הזיכרון ספר ויהודית דמוקרטית במדינה, ed. Menachem Mautiner, Avi Sagi, Ronen\nShamir ed. (Tel Aviv: Tel Aviv University Press, 1998) 301–39.\n-- 92 of 101 --\n\nWomen’s Testimony in Jewish Law \t155\nhis commitment to the Zionist enterprise at the expense of his own halakhic\ntraditions.\nIn contrast, Rabbi Yeshoua Ahrenberg, head of the Tel Aviv rabbinical\ncourt, sees the reason for women’s exclusion from testimony as a concern for\nmodesty:\nThere is a reason to exempt women from testimony because of בת כבודה כל\nפנימה מלך [a rabbinical exegesis that women’s honor is served by modesty]. . . .\nit is possible that for this reason, the Torah did not mandate that a woman\ntestify because, if she would be obligated to testify, she would need to come\nto the court and as the Tosefot wrote she will violate the attribute of כבודה כל\nפנימה מלך בת and, since the Torah desires that women should not violate this\nattribute, as we see in the court being obligated to send scribes to her when\nshe is sued, so the Torah exempts the woman from the commandment to\ntestify. 152\nMay a woman relinquish this exemption and testify despite immodesty? If\nshe decides to come to the court and give testimony, since her exemption is\nbecause of a peripheral issue, not because of any fault with her actual testimony,\nit should be accepted. Since the commandment to give testimony in monetary\nissues is derived from the commandment to return lost objects, and women\nare not exempt from this commandment, her testimony should be accepted.\nBut it is not a mere exemption, since without it women would be obligated to\nappear before the court; it is a disqualification of women from giving testimony.\nIt has nothing to do with the character of women – the goal here is that they\nwill not take part in legal procedures for reasons of modesty.153 The rest of the\narticle criticizes another written by Rabbi Katriel Tchorsh, one of the leading\nrabbis of Hapoel Hamizrachi and a member of the Chief Rabbinate’s Council.\nThe Council dealt extensively with the role of halakhah in modern Israel and\ncollectively published an article based on Rabbi Ahrenberg’s article – without\nstating its source and also changing some of his conclusions.154 Rabbi Tchorsh\nadded that, beyond Rabbi Ahrenberg’s reasoning, women are excluded because\nof their different psychological profile. He explains that the talmudic saying\n“women are lightheaded” does not mean to censor women, but to explain that\nwomen are influenced more by emotion than cold logical analysis. That enables\nthem to have a better ability to draw conclusions, but their perception of pri-\nmary concepts is inaccurate.155 In essence, Rabbi Tchorsh returns to women’s\n152 Yeshoua Ahrenberg, “?אפליה או צדק – לעדות נשים פסול,” Pa’amei Yaacov 45 (2000) 16.\n153 Ibid., 17–18.\n154 Katriel Tchorsh, Keter Ephraim (Tel Aviv: 1967) 179–202 [Heb.].\n155 Ibid., 162, 194.\n-- 93 of 101 --\n\nIlan Fuchs\t156\ncharacter and to epistemology, wishing to explain the gap between halakhic\ntexts and modern perceptions without offering changes.\nConclusion\nThe routine activity of a legal system demands a clear mechanism of evidentiary\nlaws, and rules of exclusion are part of any such mechanism. The widening\nof rules of exclusion to protect values other than the finding of facts cannot\nbe avoided, and will not necessarily hinder an investigation into factual truth.\nThis balance of values is part of any legal system and accompanies halakhic\nliterature from its early stages. Tannaitic and amoriac sources – Sifre, Sifre Zuta\nDevarim, Mishnah, Babylonian Talmud, and the Yerushalmi – do not suggest\nany reasoning behind the exclusion of women’s testimony. Josephus and two\nlater aggadic exegeses (and perhaps also a baraita in the Tosefta) see a cause for\nexclusion in women’s unreliable character. The absence of such justification in\nvirtually all sources highlights the complexity of this rule of exclusion, but also\nhas a chilling effect on later discourse, because the inadmissibility is derived\nfrom a biblical decree rather than a socio-historical criterion subject to change.\nAs part of this complex relationship, there were cases where women could\ngive testimony when other interests besides inadmissibility overshadowed any\ndiscussion of the reason for the inadmissibility or its grounding in Scripture.\nThis tension is also evident in texts from the rishonim, when, in Ashkenaz, two\nsolutions were provided. The first is the enactment; its provenance is unclear,\nbut it was employed in many Ashkenazic communities and later gave way to\nan alternative explanation by the Agudah based on purposive interpretation,\nmeaning an interpretation which is based on the perceived goals of the legal\nrule rather than formalistic interpretation. This tool was used by the Agudah\nin interpreting the talmudic discussion in Qiddushin, and became the solution\npreferred by most rabbinic authorities in Ashkenaz. Comparing this solution to\nother legal systems in Europe, especially to canon law, shows that women’s tes-\ntimony was also on the agenda of non-Jewish jurists. The same socioeconomic\nfactors that led the rishonim in Ashkenaz to look for a solution to the limitations\nset by this rule also affected non-Jewish jurists, though not as acutely in Spain.\nThe rishonim in non-Ashkenazic communities rejected these solutions almost\ncompletely. From the Rashba to Rabbi Chaim Palagi, it is not only a matter of\nSephardic halakhic tradition, but also due to the understanding that changing\nthis exclusionary rule would be far too radical a solution. The novelty of this\nsolution, and its dangers, sound an alarm in many modern sources where\nthe debate on the inadmissibility of women’s testimony not only concerns\nlegal procedure but larger questions of equality and the relationship between\nhalakhah and modern Western society.\n-- 94 of 101 --\n\nWomen’s Testimony in Jewish Law \t157\nThe Israeli experience is different from what came before it in two main\npoints: first, modern science has completely changed evidentiary laws; both\nforensic and computer-obtained evidence are part of contemporary legal\ndiscussions. Second, it is difficult to explain in a modern secular world why\nhalf of humanity should be ineligible to give legal testimony, especially in a\nrabbinical court system competing with a parallel secular one with generally\nhigher authority. There are hardly any significant halakhic discussions in the\nstate rabbinical courts about women’s testimony, even though women appear\nbefore them on a regular basis. Moreover, the responsa of rabbis Uziel and\nHerzog were mentioned neither in later opinions of the rabbinical court nor\nin other responsa. How can this oversight be explained?\nThe answer is imbedded in the relationship of evidentiary halakhic laws and\nmodern technology. Slowly but surely rabbinic discourse is emerging on issues\nsuch as DNA, polygraphs, and information obtained by wiretapping. Writing\nextensively on evidence obtained using technology such as tape recording,\nRabbi Uziel theorizes that there must be a model allowing testimony from\nsecular Jews or non-Jews, otherwise the laws of the country would never be\ncompatible with halakhah. He develops several models based on the idea that\nIsraeli evidentiary laws are a form of community legislation. 156\nThe proper context for the deliberations surveyed here is wider than merely\nthe issue of testimony. Other than Rabbi Hirschensohn, at the far margins\nof halakhic discourse and with little influence, there are virtually no direct\nstatements in current rabbinic discourse dealing with the change in women’s\nlives in modern society. In the early stages of the meeting of Orthodoxy and\nmodernity, discussions about the testimony of secular Jews become relevant.\nBeginning with Rabbi Akiva Eiger in Germany, this issue has remained part of\nthe Orthodox agenda. The discussion on women’s testimony and later disputes\nover forensic evidence are thus components of an entire structured debate.157\nThe rise of secularism as a social phenomenon is not new. The change in the\nstatus of women in Orthodox society, however, constitutes a change no less\nsignificant than the encounter with secularism. While a secular Jew is exter-\nnal to the religious community, a religious, Torah-observant woman is at its\ncenter, a situation which demands a coming to terms with the changes in the\nrole of women that continue to occur in religious society. The changing status\nof women is one of the most difficult challenges facing a traditional society\nwishing to accept some aspects of modernity. Yet in some circles, the perception\n156 Uziel, Mishpatei Uziel, 157, sections 14–20\n157 Nachum Nerya, “ומצוות תורה מקיים שאינו מי של עדות,” Techumin 13 (1993) 417–21; Yuval Sinai, ״באור\nלעדות״ רשעים של כשרותם בעניין הרמב״ם שיטת, Magal 12 (1998) 289–310; Amir Rot, מחמת עדות ״פסולי\nעבירה״ (Master’s thesis, Bar Ilan University, 2001).\n-- 95 of 101 --\n\nIlan Fuchs\t158\nof women as confined to the private sphere leads to seeing even incremental\nchange as undermining the most basic and essential social foundations. Other\nchanges in the private sphere are much less threatening.\nThe question still remains: why so little debate on the issue? The rabbinical\ncourt system deals with evidentiary laws, but in light of its limited authority,\nwhich focuses mainly on personal status issues, there is little need for such a\ndiscussion. As time goes by, the secular court system removes more and more\nauthority from the rabbinical court. Even monetary claims brought before\nprivate rabbinical courts represent a mere fraction of legal suits. And since the\nmajority of legal activity is conducted in the secular courts, there is no catalyst\nfor the creation of innovative halakhic models in the field of evidentiary law.\nThe best examples of this process can be found in the writings of Rabbi Avra-\nham Sherman, a rabbinic judge who dealt with hearing inadmissible testimony\nin a family law case. Citing the Rif that the custom of the courts was to accept\nthe testimony of women in disputes between spouses, he writes in two different\nopinions that such testimony should only be heard when there is already no\ndoubt that domestic violence has taken place. When the actual dispute is in\ndoubt, he will not use women’s testimony. Even though he does not think the\nsource for Rif ’s position has anything to do with the Ashkenazi enactment, he\nputs them side by side and rules that inadmissible evidence will only be heard\nwhen there is no one to deny the existence of the dispute.\nThis case does not require a major response from the halakhic establishment;\nthe fact that it is not a widespread issue allows it to be set aside. The few discus-\nsions that have occurred were the initiative of rabbis committed to the Zionist\nproject and wishing to fortify, as much as possible, the connection between the\nstate and halakhah in an attempt to create a halakhic model that could accept\nwomen’s testimony. The more this view weakens among the rabbinic judges in\nthe state rabbinical courts, so too does the motivation to create these models.\nA complete rejection of such attempts by the state rabbinical courts, however,\nmay be suppressed due to fear of a negative reaction from the secular court\nsystem. This fear is not unwarranted, since there are precedents for involvement\nof the secular court in evidentiary matters in the rabbinical court. In a case\nbrought before the Israeli Supreme Court, Justice Strasberg-Cohen ruled that\nthe rabbinical court cannot hear evidence that was obtained contrary to the\nlaw protecting privacy.158\nIt is also difficult to say what weight is given to a woman’s testimony because\na rabbinical court can hear the testimony and simply disregard it. Since very\nfew of the opinions of the rabbinical court are published, it is hard to identify\na coherent judicial philosophy. The de jure/de facto split in the material from\n158 BGT 1135/02 Vagziel v. Beit Hadin Harabani Hagadol, Piskei Medinat Yisrael 56 (6) page 14.\n-- 96 of 101 --\n\nWomen’s Testimony in Jewish Law \t159\nthe rabbinical courts shows that this discussion went beyond a formalistic, local\ndiscussion on the finer points of procedure and evidentiary law. Solving this\nissue is a challenge fraught with the tension between Orthodoxy and modern\nvalues concerning women and their role in society.\nThe article is based on a chapter from a dissertation written at Bar-Ilan University under the\nguidance of professors Amichai Radzyner and Kimmy Kaplan. It was revised and translated in my\ntime as a research fellow at Sha’arey Mishpat law school and in the Hadassah-Brandeis institute.\nI would like to thank Dr. Karl Gerlach for his wonderful comments and Dr. Aviad Hachohen.\nSpecial thanks to Professor Shulah Reinhartz for her invaluable support.\n-- 97 of 101 --\n\nApplication Forms\nFoster Child Form\nFoster Child\nI was not a foster child\n-- 98 of 101 --\n\nVeteran Status/Identification Form\nVoluntary Self-Identification of Veteran Status\nI do not identify as a veteran\nSurviving Spouse of a Veteran\nI am not a surviving spouse of a veteran\nOrphan of a Veteran\nI am not an orphan of a veteran\n-- 99 of 101 --\n\nClery 