52	78	gibson_jedidiah_5550498.pdf	\N	Page 1 of 1\nJEDIDIAH GIBSON\ngibsonj5@byulaw.net • 918 323-1567\nNovember 25, 2024\nHiring Committee\nTexas A&M University\nSchool of Law\nDear Hiring Committee,\nI am writing to express my interest in the Adjunct Professor of Law position recently posted. My background\nincludes significant expertise in human resources and employment law, policy and management, alternative\ndispute resolution (ADR), risk management, and compliance. In addition, I bring substantial experience in\nemployment litigation, as well as teaching and mentoring legal students in foundational skills such as legal\nwriting and communication.\nIn my current role as a Senior Attorney Advisor at the Federal Communications Commission, I provide counsel\non complex employment law matters and serve as a mediator for workplace disputes. My prior roles at the U.S.\nDepartment of the Interior and Utah State University focused on civil rights issues, compliance, and resolving\nallegations of discrimination, harassment, and misconduct. These roles required extensive litigation experience,\npolicy development, and the ability to guide stakeholders through legal and procedural challenges.\nAt Cornell Law School, I serve as an assistant course facilitator for graduate-level courses, including\nRegulatory Policy and Process, Business Organizations and Corporate Governance, Working with Business\nContracts, and U.S. Antitrust Law and Policy. In this role, I work closely with students to connect theoretical\nframeworks with practical applications, enhancing their understanding of complex legal concepts, regulatory\nprocesses, and corporate governance strategies.\nThis position reflects my passion for legal education and my commitment to equipping graduate students and\nprofessionals with the skills needed for career success. I look forward to contributing to your institution by\ncreating an engaging and inclusive environment where students can develop their full potential.\nThank you for considering my application. I look forward to discussing how my experience and expertise align\nwith the needs of your program.\nSincerely,\nJedidiah Gibson\n-- 1 of 10 --\n\nPage 1 of 3\nJEDIDIAH GIBSON\ngibsonj5@byulaw.net • 918 323-1567\nEDUCATION\nJ. Reuben Clark Law School, Brigham Young University, Provo, UT\nJuris Doctor, April 2018\n▪ Associate Editor, BYU Education and Law Journal\n▪ Traveling Team Member, BYU Moot Court Team\n▪ Mediator, BYU Law Center for Peace & Conflict Resolution\nOklahoma State University, Stillwater, OK\nBachelor of Science, magna cum laude, Political Science, May 2015\nBAR ADMISSIONS\nOklahoma, 2022 (Active) & Utah, 2019 (Inactive)\nLEGAL AREA OF EXPERTISE\nExpert in employment law, with significant experience in civil rights and equal employment opportunity\ncompliance. Skilled in regulatory processes, federal administrative law, legal writing, and communication.\nProficient in designing and delivering legal training and courses, in the workplace and in academia. Robust\nexperience in mediation and alternative dispute resolution, facilitating effective conflict management across\nvarious settings.\nEXPERIENCE\nCornell Law School, Master of Science in Legal Studies Program, Ithaca, NY (Remote)\nAssistant Course Facilitator, April 2024 – Present (Part-Time)\n• Facilitates graduate-level courses in legal studies, including Regulatory Policy and Process, Business\nOrganizations and Corporate Governance, Working with Business Contracts, and U.S. Antitrust Law and\nPolicy. Ensures assignments and projects are graded on time, providing constructive and detailed feedback\nto enhance student understanding. Manages course materials and monitors student progress through the\nCanvas Learning Management System. Maintains consistent communication by responding to student\ninquiries within 24 hours and supports students in navigating complex legal concepts in an asynchronous\nonline learning environment.\nFederal Communications Commission, Office of Workplace Diversity (OWD), Washington, DC\nSenior Attorney Advisor, May 2022 – Present\n• Advises and adjudicates employment matters related to claims of discrimination and harassment under\nTitle VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, the ADA, the ADEA, and other civil rights laws and regulations.\nLeads the development and execution of a comprehensive training curriculum for FCC employees,\naddressing topics such as workplace discrimination prevention, harassment prevention, and providing\nreasonable accommodations for people with disabilities. Facilitates interactive training sessions through\nthe agency’s learning management systems, delivering engaging and effective learning experiences for\ngroups of up to 200 participants. Conducts legal research to support policy development and training\ncontent, ensuring materials are accurate, relevant, and accessible to non-legal audiences. Serves as a\n-- 2 of 10 --\n\nPage 2 of 3\nmediator in the U.S. Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service (FMCS) Shared Neutrals Program,\nmanaging workplace conflicts across federal agencies with diplomacy and conflict resolution expertise.\nU.S. Department of the Interior, Office of Diversity, Inclusion and Civil Rights (ODICR), Washington, DC\nPresidential Management Fellow, Equal Employment Opportunity Specialist, August 2018 – May 2022\n• Appointed as a Presidential Management Fellow (Class of 2018) through the prestigious program,\nreflecting a commitment to public service and leadership. Leads the organization and facilitation of EEO\ntraining sessions, utilizing learning management systems to deliver essential content on anti-\ndiscrimination laws and harassment prevention to a diverse audience across the department. Contributes\nto the development and revision of EEO policies, ensuring their effective implementation through\neducational programs and materials tailored to diverse audiences. Actively engages with training\nparticipants, providing personalized advice and feedback to enhance the learning experience and support\ndepartmental goals.\nU.S. Department of Commerce, Office of General Counsel, Washington, DC\nAttorney (Presidential Management Fellowship Detail Assignment), September 2019 – February 2020\n• Represented the Department in all phases of litigation before the U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity\nCommission (EEOC) and the Merit Systems Protection Board (MSPB). Prepared and drafted motions and\nother hearing documents, initiated and responded to discovery requests, and negotiated settlement\nagreements. Provided advice and counsel to managers, supervisors, and human resources/employee\nrelations staff on various employment-related issues. Common issues included claims of discrimination\nand harassment, employee misconduct and performance issues, reasonable accommodation requests from\nemployees with disabilities, laws governing veteran employment, and regulations involving hiring and\npromotions.\nU.S. Department of the Interior, Office of Collaborative Action and Dispute Resolution, Arlington, VA\nConflict Resolution Specialist (Presidential Management Fellowship Detail Assignment), July 2019\n• Led a comprehensive review of the Department's EEO ADR program. Analyzed critical performance\nmetrics and crafted strategic recommendations for senior leadership focused on improving ADR outcomes\nand fostering a culture of conflict resolution literacy among employees. These recommendations were\naimed at refining the Department's approach to conflict management, enhancing the effectiveness and\nefficiency of resolving workplace disputes.\nU.S. EEOC, Office of Legal Counsel, Washington, DC\nLegal Intern, June 2017 – August 2017\n• Assisted EEOC headquarters attorneys in the drafting of regulations and guidance documents interpreting\nfederal employment laws such as Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, the Americans with Disabilities\nAct Amendments Act of 2008 (ADAA), and the Age Discrimination in Employment Act of 1967ADEA.\nUtah Valley University, Office of Equal Opportunity and Affirmative Action, Orem, UT\nEqual Opportunity/Title IX Investigator, March 2016 – May 2017\n• Led investigations into cases concerning allegations of discrimination, sexual harassment/misconduct,\nretaliation, and gender-based violence.\n• Authored investigative reports summarizing findings; coordinated with human resources and the general\ncounsel to implement appropriate corrective action.\n-- 3 of 10 --\n\nPage 3 of 3\nCOMMUNITY SERVICE\n▪ Annual Volunteer, 2011 – 2024, Eastern Shawnee Tribe of Oklahoma, Shawna Stovall Back-to-School\nChildren's Powwow, Wyandotte, Oklahoma\n-- 4 of 10 --\n\nPage 1 of 1\nJEDIDIAH GIBSON\ngibsonj5@byulaw.net • 918 323-1567\nPersonal Statement\nMy teaching philosophy centers on empowering students to engage with the law in a practical, analytical, and\ninclusive manner. I believe legal education should not only develop the ability to interpret statutes and case law\nbut also equip students to apply these principles effectively to real-world challenges.\nAs an assistant course facilitator for Cornell Law School's Master of Science in Legal Studies program, I\nsupport graduate students in mastering complex legal concepts through courses such as Regulatory Policy and\nProcess, Business Organizations and Corporate Governance, Working with Business Contracts, and U.S.\nAntitrust Law and Policy. My responsibilities include fostering analytical and practical engagement with course\nmaterials, providing timely and detailed feedback, and facilitating discussions that bridge legal theory with real-\nworld applications. By creating a supportive and intellectually stimulating learning environment, I help students\ndevelop the skills necessary to navigate intricate legal frameworks and professional challenges.\nMy professional experience in civil rights, employment law, and alternative dispute resolution further shapes\nmy approach to teaching. I emphasize inclusivit