to provide students with a rigorous, practice-\noriented legal education aligns seamlessly with my career-long dedication to the intersection of\nlaw, national security, cyber operations, and human rights. As an experienced legal practitioner,\neducator, and strategic advisor, I have spent my career translating complex legal frameworks into\nreal-world applications. My philosophy of teaching is rooted in a deep commitment to mentorship,\nexperiential learning, and the development of critical thinking skills—equipping students not only\nwith legal knowledge but also with the ability to apply that knowledge in high-stakes, dynamic\nenvironments.\nTeaching Philosophy\nI believe that legal education should be immersive, adaptive, and directly applicable to real-world\nchallenges. My teaching philosophy is shaped by my experiences as Senior Legal Advisor at U.S.\nSpecial Operations Command (USSOCOM) and Director of the Security Justice Advisory\nDirectorate at the U.S. Embassy in Jerusalem, where I provided legal counsel in combat and non-\ncombat environments, advised on national security law, and trained military and civilian leaders in\nthe principles of law and governance. I have seen firsthand how law functions as both a guiding\nforce and a decisive operational tool, and I aim to ensure that my students graduate with a strong\ncommand of legal principles and their practical implications.\nIn my courses, I emphasize:\n1. Experiential Learning and Application:\n- Law students must be prepared to navigate the practical realities of the legal profession. I design\nproblem-based learning scenarios, case studies, and simulations that require students to engage\nwith real-world legal issues in national security, cyber operations, and the law of armed conflict.\n- I incorporate war-gaming and crisis response exercises where students must make legal\ndecisions under time constraints, reinforcing their ability to analyze risk, interpret legal authorities,\nand provide sound counsel in complex situations.\n2. Critical Thinking and Ethical Leadership:\n- Legal education should challenge students to think beyond black-letter law and examine the\nbroader impact of legal decisions on society, governance, and security. I engage students in\nSocratic dialogue, structured debates, and scenario-based policy analysis to sharpen their\nanalytical abilities.\n- I instill in students a deep appreciation for ethical decision-making by exposing them to the\npractical challenges faced by legal professionals advising government leaders, military officials,\nand policymakers.\n3. Bridging Law and Policy:\n-- 9 of 22 --\n\n- Given the evolving nature of national security threats, emerging technologies, and human rights\nchallenges, I ensure that students develop fluency in the intersection of law, technology, and policy.\n- My teaching incorporates current legal debates, legislative and regulatory developments, and\ncomparative legal analysis to provide students with a global perspective on security and\ngovernance issues.\n4. Mentorship and Professional Development:\n- As a career military paratrooper and 100% PNT service-disabled veteran, I have mentored\ncountless legal professionals across government, military, and private sectors.\n- I am committed to building a mentorship culture within my classroom, ensuring that students\nreceive individualized guidance on career paths, legal specialization, and professional growth.\nPlans for Teaching\nAt Texas A&M School of Law, I seek to develop and teach courses that immerse students in the\ncomplexities of modern legal practice while challenging them to think critically, problem-solve\neffectively, and apply legal knowledge in high-pressure situations. Some courses I would propose\ninclude:\n- National Security Law & Policy: A deep dive into legal authorities governing national security\noperations, the role of executive power, and legal challenges in counterterrorism and intelligence\noperations.\n- Cyber and Emerging Technologies Law: Examining cyber warfare, digital privacy, AI, and data\nprotection laws, with an emphasis on how evolving technologies shape modern legal frameworks.\n- Law of Armed Conflict & Human Rights: A practical, case-based approach to the Geneva\nConventions, human rights law, military justice systems, and legal challenges in modern warfare.\n- Legal Ethics and Decision-Making in Government & Security: Exploring the ethical challenges\nfaced by legal advisors, with real-world case studies on legal dilemmas in national security\ndecision-making.\nI also look forward to incorporating Texas A&M’s robust interdisciplinary programs into my courses,\nencouraging collaboration between law students and engineering, cybersecurity, and public policy\nprograms to reflect the cross-functional nature of today’s legal challenges.\nConclusion\nTexas A&M School of Law offers an extraordinary opportunity to shape future legal professionals by\ncombining doctrinal instruction with real-world experience and strategic insight. My career-long\ncommitment to the law, national security, and legal education makes me eager to contribute to\nTexas A&M’s legacy of excellence in teaching, scholarship, and service. I look forward to engaging\nstudents, fostering leadership, and contributing my expertise to one of the nation’s most dynamic\nlaw schools.\nThank you for your time and consideration.\n-- 10 of 22 --\n\nSincerely,\nDavid J. Green, Esq.\nLicensed in North Carolina and Texas\n-- 11 of 22 --\n\nDavid J. Green, Esq. (214) 846-4657\nReferences:\nJudge Charles Vanover (817) 271-3817\nJudge Brent Carr (817) 455-0973\nJudge Richard Sinnott (617) 694-7442\n-- 12 of 22 --\n\nUnited States Army\nColonel DAVID J. GREEN\nDirector, Senior Justice Advisor The Office of the United States Security\nCoordinator for Israel and the Palestinian Authority - U.S. Embassy Jerusalem\nSince: March 2024\nTop Secret – Sensitive Compartmented Information Clearance\nAdjunct Instructor, Defen