nand work product and preempting any issue before it is simply too late for the\nstudent to recover.\n2. Critical Thinking and Analytical Skills\na. The critical thinking and analytical skills that I acquired in law school have served\nme well, in law, business, higher education, and my personal life. Effectively\ncommunicating the tremendous value of critical thinking and analytical skills is\nthe first step in helping students achieve a higher level of knowledge and\napplication in these two most essential areas.\n3. Ethical Foundations and Professional Responsibility\na. With great power comes great responsibility. As an attorney licensed to practice\nlaw in the State of Michigan, I am an officer of the court. This status, combined\nwith the privilege to practice law, requires that I conduct myself as an ethical\nprofessional, and adhere to the rules of professional responsibility. As a member\nof the State Bar of Michigan Committee for Character & Fitness, I have come to\nrealize that one should not adhere to an ethical or personal responsibility standard\nsimply because a rule requires one to do so. Rather, we should, as learned\nprofessionals, operate in an ethical and responsible manner at all times because it\nis the right thing to do. The practice of law is a privilege.\n4. Teaching Methods\na. Interactive Lectures and Discussions: Encourage active participation to deepen\nunderstanding and engagement.\nb. Feedback and Mentorship: Provide detailed, constructive feedback and maintain\nan open-door policy to support students’ academic and career development.\nc. Technology Integration: Utilize digital tools for research, collaboration, and\nexploring emerging areas like law related technology and artificial intelligence.\n-- 10 of 14 --\n\nCONTACT REFERENCES\nJOHN GUSTINCIC\nProfessor DeLois Leapheart\no Email: leapheart@gmail.com\no Phone: 989.859.4075\nProfessor Clifford Harris\no Email: harrisc@northwood.edu\no Phone: 989.295.5995\nProfessor Christin Van W