58	84	henderson_xakema_5584198.pdf	\N	December 2, 2024\nRobert Ahdieh\nDean & Anthony G. Buzbee Endowed Dean’s Chair\nVice President for Professional Schools & Programs\nTexas A&M University School of Law\nRE: \tSpring \t2025 \t- \tAdjunct \tProfessor \tof \tLaw \tPosition \tfor \tProposed\nEnvironmental Insurance Coverage Course or Legal Writing Courses\nDean Ahdieh:\nI graduated from Texas A&M University in 2009, years before the law school opened as\na part of the TAMU system. Now, as a former student, practicing litigator, and Dallas\nnative, I am elated to apply for an adjunct professor position at Texas A&M University\nof School of Law. For the last six years, I have had the great fortune of practicing primarily\nin the environmental insurance coverage space, a niche area that I do not see is a course\noffering at the law school.\nAt first glance, environmental insurance coverage may not seem particularly interesting.\nBut it is. I deal with complex, high-stakes environmental claims involving multimillion-\ndollar exposures. These first-party and third-party claims span from one-off incidents like\nchemical spills, overturned tanker trucks, severe weather events, and pandemic-related\nclosures to long-tail claims like Superfund sites and mass tort pollution claims. My clients\nfor this work are major insurance carriers who I both advise pre-litigation and defend in\ncoverage lawsuits in state and federal courts across the country. I also advise them\nextensively on various claims-related issues arising from emerging contaminants such as\nPFAS (per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances, which are a category of man-made chemicals\nwhose ubiquity has led them to being deemed “forever chemicals”).\nMy \twork \tis \ta \tfusion \tof \tcontract \tlaw, \tinsurance \tlaw, \tenvironmental \tlaw, \trisk\nmanagement, and litigation. I love it, and my days are never the same.\nAs a partner at my law firm, I am regularly training associates as well as advising new\nclaims adjuster clients (who are typically recent law school graduates) on environmental\ninsurance coverage principles. The learning curve is steep because the area is not\nXakema Henderson\nPartner\nAkerman LLP\n2001 Ross Avenue\nSuite 3600\nDallas, TX 75201\nD: 214 720 4372\nT: 214 720 4300\nF: 214 981 9339\nxakema.henderson@akerman.com\n-- 1 of 12 --\n\ncomparable to anything they have ever done before. But once the principles begin\nclicking, these junior attorneys often respond positively, feeling privileged to practice in\nan ever-evolving and challenging area of the law. I enjoy being able to watch them grow\nan affinity for the area of the law I have come to enjoy so much.\nAs an adjunct professor, I would like to teach an environmental insurance coverage\ncourse, which would be a great addition to the school’s robust Energy Environmental &\nNatural Resource Systems Law course offerings. The class would be a two-hour,\nexperiential course that includes an overview of commercial general liability insurance\nwith an emphasis on recurring issues arising from environmental claims, including\nemerging contaminants like PFAS. The course is designed to introduce students to\nenvironmental insurance coverage as well as provide them with the basic knowledge and\nskills to issue spot environmental insurance coverage issues wherever their careers take\nthem. I have detailed my proposed teaching plan for the course in my personal statement.\nIf the school has a need for adjuncts to teach more traditional courses, as an alternative to\nan environmental insurance coverage course, I am also interested in teaching any legal\nwriting-based course, including advanced legal writing or judicial opinion writing, a\ncourse I took in law school that prepared me well for my clerkship at the Colorado\nSupreme Court and beyond. In addition to clerking, I have a professional writing minor,\nworked as a trained writing consultant at TAMU’s Writing Center for three years in\nundergrad, was a legal writing teaching assistant in law school, taught secondary writing,\nand have written dozens, if not hundreds, of motions, briefs, and other documents as a\nlitigator of nine years.\nI’d be grateful to join TAMU Law as an adjunct and look forward to discussing this\nopportunity.\nKindly,\nXakema Henderson\nakerman.com\n-- 2 of 12 --\n\nXakema Henderson\n5414 Oak Trail, Dallas, TX 75232 |Xakema.Henderson@akerman.com | 214-697-2823\nPROFESSIONAL EXPERIENCE\nAdmitted in Colorado (2014) & Texas (2018)\nAkerman LLP, Dallas, TX \tJan. 2019–present\nPartner, Litigation\n§ \tPractice in areas of complex commercial litigation, including contractual disputes,\naviation defense, and environmental insurance coverage\n§ \tRepresent major insurance companies in connection with claims of significant exposure\nthat pose extreme risk of loss to the company\n§ \tAdvise major insurance companies on coverage issues and disputes involving emerging\ncontaminants such as PFAS, PFOA, PFOS, and GenX\nBell Nunnally & Martin LLP, Dallas, TX \tJan. 2018–Jan. 2019\nLitigation Associate\nBaker Hostetler, LLP, Denver, CO \tOct. 2015–Dec. 2017\nLitigation Associate & Summer Associate (2012 & 2013)\nClerkship: Colorado Supreme Court, Denver, CO \tAug. 2014–Aug. 2015\nAppellate Law Clerk to the Honorable Justice William W. Hood, III\nEDUCATION\nUniversity of Colorado Law School, Boulder, CO\nJ.D. (May 2014), GPA 3.4\n§ \tNational Moot Court Team\n§ \tLegal Writing Teaching Assistant\nTexas A&M University, College Station, TX\nB.B.A. Finance; Professional Writing minor (May 2009)\nPUBLICATIONS\n§ \tTexas Lawyer, Author, “A Trigger Warning? The Untapped World of Trigger Theories\nin PFAS Coverage Litigation,” Nov. 2024\n§ \tTexas Lawyer, Co-author, “Is PFAS the New Asbestos?”, April 2019\n§ \tInternational E-Discovery, Co-author, U.S. Chapter on E-Discovery Practices, 2018\n§ \tSurvey of Federal Class Action Law: A Circuit-by-Circuit Analysis, Chapter Co-author,\n“Precedent in the United States Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit,”2018\nHONORS & AWARDS\n§ \tBenchmark Litigation, Listed in Texas as a “Future Star” for Dispute Resolution\n2025\n§ \tBloomberg Law, “They’ve Got Next: The 40 Under 40,” Honoree \t2024\n§ \tAmerican Lawyer Magazine, Young Lawyer of the Year – Beyond Practice, Finalist\n2024\n§ \tTexas Lawyer Texas Legal Awards, Pro Bono Attorney of the Year, Finalist \t2024\n§ \tBenchmark Litigation, Named to the “40 & Under” List \t2024\n-- 3 of 12 --\n\nXakema Henderson\nPage 2 of 2\n§ \tDallas Business Journal, 40 Under 40 Honoree \t2023\n§ \tBest Lawyers, Listed in Texas for Commercial Litigation, Insurance Law as\n“One to Watch” \t2021-2023\n§ \tTexas Lawyer’s Texas Legal Awards, “Rising Star” Honoree \t2023\n§ \tColoradoBiz, Top 25 Most Influential Young Professionals in Colorado \t2018\n§ \tLaw Week Colorado, Up and Coming Lawyers \t2017\n§ \tColorado Black Women for Political Action, Honoree for Community\nLeadership in Law and Service \t2017\nOTHER RELEVANT PROFESSIONAL EXPERIENCE\nTeach for America, Houston, TX \t2009–2011\n7th grade English Language Arts Teacher & English Department Co-Chair, Houston ISD\nCorps Member Adviser \t2011\n§ \tManaged and trained over 70 new teachers\nCOMMUNITY INVOLVEMENT\n§ \tUNT Dallas College of Law Louis A. Bedford Mentorship Program \t2019–present\no \tMentor 1L students each semester on the legal profession and\nlaw school-related issues\n§ \tUNT Dallas Foundation Board, Director \t2018–present\n§ \tBig Brothers, Big Sisters, Mentor \t2014–2022\n-- 4 of 12 --\n\nPersonal Statement on Teaching\nXakema Henderson\nTeaching Philosophy\nBecause I was formally trained in secondary education, learning to teach reading and\nwriting to middle schoolers, my teaching philosophy is that most classrooms should be\nstudent-driven. Student-driven means the students are learning and participating\nactively in the classroom, and the teacher is a facilitator and guide for their learning.\nThus, while traditional law school classrooms already places the onus for learning on\nstudents, student-driven learning, especially in upper-level law school courses, can help\nstudents develop critical thinking skills around how the concepts they are learning apply\npractically in the real world, a skill that, in my experience, is what marks creative,\nthoughtful advocates.\nWhen I began working with law students as a legal writing teaching assistant in law\nschool, I observed that student-driven learning was just as effective as it had been when\nI was teaching reading and writing to seventh graders. I was repeatedly having to help\nmy 1L legal writing students snap out of just seeing CREAC/CRAC as an unnecessary,\nrestrictive formula and understand that, in the real world, the clarity and predictiveness\nof this writing style made for powerful advocacy. In short, students learn best when they\ncan connect what they are learning to the world around them.\nTeaching Plans: Environmental Insurance Coverage\nThe proposed environmental insurance coverage course will be designed to comport\nwith but differ from the current Energy Environmental & Natural Resource Systems Law\ncourse \tofferings, \tincluding \tEnvironmental \tLaw \t(7277), \tInsurance \tLaw \tand \tRisk\nManagement (727), and Insurance Law and Risk Transfer (694).\nThe course would be a two-hour, experiential course that includes an overview of\ncommercial general liability and pollution liability insurance with an emphasis on\nrecurring issues arising from environmental claims, including emerging contaminants\nlike PFAS (per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances). Generally, the course will include a\nsurvey of the common legal and factual issues that arise in the environmental insurance\ncoverage space, such as those involving CERCLA (Comprehensive Environmental\nResponse, Compensation, and Liability Act) and Superfund cleanup sites, catastrophic\nenvironmental events, mold, asbestos, COVID-19, and emerging contaminants such as\nPFAS, including coverage lawsuits that have arisen in relation to PFAS-related multi-\ndistrict litigation. The course will include evaluating general insurance coverage issues\nlike \tconcurrent \tcausation \tand \tthe \tnumber \tof \t“occurrences” \tin \tthe \tcontext \tof\nenvironmental claims.\n-- 5 of 12 --\n\nXakema Henderson\nPage 2 of 3\nTo make the course experiential, students will be challenged to act as counsel for the\ninsurer or the insured in class discussions, and throughout the course, will have to write\na reservation of rights letter to an insured, a coverage opinion to an insurer, and for the\nfinal, a judicial opinion resolving a coverage-based motion for summary judgment.\nThe course is designed to be more nuanced than a general insurance law course to\nfamiliarize students with the issues that predominate environmental insurance claims\nand to be consistent with the law school’s philosophy of innovative teaching that\n“advanc[es] knowledge at the intersection of scholarly excellence and real-world\napplication.”\nThe text will be Insurance Law and Policy: Cases and Materials, Fifth Edition by Tom Baker,\nKyle D. Logue, and Chaim Saiman. We will also rely on other reading materials as\nsupplements.\nTeaching Plans: Legal Writing Courses\nIn any legal writing course I teach, students will experience a balance of exposure to good\nlegal writing and opportunities to practice good legal writing and receive feedback.\nBelow discusses the plans for each of the proposed courses.\n(1) 1L Legal Writing\nIn my experience, 1Ls struggle initially with adapting to the CREAC/CRAC method of\nlegal writing and tend to become overly rigid in trying to adhere to it. We will spend an\nappreciable amount of time learning the differences between rule statements, including\ngeneral rules, subrules, exceptions, and definitions, to help students understand how to\ncraft a rules and explanation section in a legal analysis. We will spend a comparable\namount of time learning that the application section is an intentional paralleling of their\nrules and explanation section.\nIn addition to learning how to write a strong legal analysis using the above, we will\nincorporate outlining, writing issue statements, modes of persuasion, grammar, and legal\ncitations.\nThe texts will include Bryan Garner’s Legal Writing in Plain English (for a first semester 1L\ncourse) or The Winning Brief: 100 Tips for Persuasive Briefing in Trial and Appellate Courts\n(for a second semester 1L course); The Redbook; and The Bluebook.\n(2) Advanced Legal Writing\nThe course is designed for students to tackle legally and factually complex issues. The\ncourse builds on what students learn in their first-year legal writing course and pushes\nthem to distill complex issues into a focused memorandum or argument section that\n-- 6 of 12 --\n\nXakema Henderson\nPage 3 of 3\nrequires answering a narrow question. Students will have the opportunity to practice\nwhat they learn in both objective and persuasive writings: one objective memorandum,\none objective email, and an argument section of a dispositive motion. All three\nassignments will involve complex legal and factual issues that students will have to sort\nthrough and organize in their writings. The complexity of the issues will increase with\neach assignment so that students have the opportunity to build on the skills they are\nlearning.\nThe course is designed to help students build their confidence when faced with writing\non complex issues.\nI have not decided on a textbook and would prefer to use a selection of appellate briefs\nand judicial opinions as texts during the course.\n(3) Judicial Opinion Writing\nThis course is designed to examine primarily: (i) the evolution of judicial opinions in\nAmerican jurisprudence, including the then-contemporary landscapes in which they\nwere written; (ii) judicial writing styles; and (iii) the limitations of and constraints on\njudicial opinions.\nThe purpose of the course is to help students think and write like federal and appellate\nlaw clerks in the short term and prudent, thoughtful advocates in the long term.\nStudents will write a bench memorandum based on competing briefs and two judicial\nopinions, one where they have no choice on the outcome and another where they get to\nchoose the case’s outcome.\nThe course will also include pertinent skill development around substantive and\ngrammatical editing, outlining, and modes of persuasion. The text will be Ross\nGuberman’s Point Taken: How to Write Like the World’s Best Judges and a variety of judicial\nopinions, namely from United States Supreme Court justices.\n-- 7 of 12 --\n\nProfessional References for Xakema Henderson\n1. \tMatt Schroeder\nDallas Office Managing Partner\nAkerman LLP\n214.720.4362\nmatt.schroeder@akerman.com\nRelationship: Current colleague and was my prior supervising attorney\n2. \tMichael Hess\nPartner\nAkerman LLP\n214.720.4335\nmichael.hess@akerman.com\nRelationship: Current colleague and is a more junior attorney than I am for\nwhom I have been a supervising attorney\n3. \tAgnes O. Doyle\nPartner\nHolland & Knight\n713.244.6886\nAgnes.Doyle@hklaw.com\nRelationship: Former colleague in Teach for America\n-- 8 of 12 --\n\nApplication Forms\nFoster Child Form\nFoster Child\nI was not a foster child\n-- 9 of 12 --\n\nVeteran Status/Identification Form\nVoluntary Self-Identification of Veteran Status\nI do not identify as a veteran\nSurviving Spouse of a Veteran\nI am not a surviving spouse of a veteran\nOrphan of a Veteran\nI am not an orphan of a veteran\n-- 10 of 12 --\n\nClery Act\nAcknowledgement:\nI acknowledge that I have received the above information regarding the Clery Act\n-- 11 of 12 --\n\nNotice of Non-Discrimination\nAcknowledgement:\nI acknowledge that I have received the information above regarding notice of non-discrimination and abuse\n-- 12 of 12 --\n\n	2025-10-12 01:08:40.197541+00	[-0.029325822,0.07855583,0.0611239,-0.04038507,0.03554558,