f Law, with a\nparticular interest in teaching intellectual property, entertainment law, or related courses. Over the past\nfive years, I have truly enjoyed teaching, viewing it as an extension of mentorship. I am eager to\ncontribute my knowledge and experience to your institution. My teaching philosophy is rooted in\nfostering a dynamic, engaging, and student-centered learning environment that equips students with the\npractical skills and critical thinking abilities necessary for success in their legal careers, particularly in\nintellectual property and the media/entertainment industry.\nTEACHING APPROACH\nMy teaching approach is based on four core principles: clarity, engagement, application, and relatability.\n1. Clarity\nI prioritize clarity by ensuring that students have a solid understanding of foundational legal concepts\nbefore advancing to more complex topics. I achieve this by:\no Providing a thorough reading of the statute or case law that defines a specific intellectual\nproperty rule.\no Offering a simplified interpretation of the rule.\no Demonstrating how the rule operates in case law.\no Applying the rule to real-world scenarios, using current events and practical examples to\nenhance understanding.\nA well-structured curriculum, supported by comprehensive case law and clear, concise explanations, is\nessential for effective learning.\n2. Engagement\nI strive to create an engaging classroom environment by encouraging active participation and discussion. I\ndo not subscribe to the Socratic method; in fact, I find it to be an outdated and ineffective tool for\nassessing students' grasp of intellectual property and entertainment law. Instead, I foster a classroom\natmosphere where students naturally engage through questions and discussion. Given the inherently\ninteresting and dynamic nature of these subjects, students are motivated to participate without coercion.\nMy goal is to create a non-punitive environment where students feel comfortable asking questions,\nchallenging assumptions, and thinking critically.\n3. Application\nBridging the gap between theoretical knowledge and practical experience is a key focus of my teaching. I\nincorporate experiential learning opportunities by:\no Analyzing current events and their legal implications in class.\no Utilizing real-world resources, such as license agreements, to provide students with\npractical exposure to industry documents.\nThis approach enhances students' comprehension and prepares them for the challenges they will\nencounter in their legal careers.\n-- 5 of 19 --\n\n4. Relatability\nRelatability is central to my teaching style. Research indicates that a professor’s age can influence\nstudents' perceptions. I take pride in the fact that I am young and the age gap between me and my students\nis not that large. Additionally, I take pride in my ability to connect with students through my\nunderstanding of social media and pop culture trends, fostering rapport and trust. Law school professors\nare often perceived as rigid and unapproachable; I strive to counter this perception by being accessible,\nsupportive, and creating an environment where students feel comfortable seeking guidance.\nTEACHING PLANS AND PROPOSAL\nIf given the opportunity to join Texas A&M University School of Law, I hope to teach courses such as:\n• Intellectual Property Law\n• Entertainment Law (Introductory Level)\n• Advanced Entertainment Law\n• Other relevant IP/entertainment law courses\nMy teaching plans include leveraging my professional experience in the IP/media space to provide\nstudents with valuable insights and practical perspectives. I plan to incorporate current legal issues, case\nlaw updates, and industry trends to ensure students receive up-to-date and relevant information.\nAdditionally, I am committed to supporting students outside the classroom by providing mentorship and\nindividualized feedback to enhance their learning and professional development.\nTo provide further insight into my teaching approach, I have included syllabi for my Entertainment Law\nand Intellectual Property courses, which outline the structure and methodology I have successfully\nimplemented at New York Law School over the past five years.\nCONCLUSION\nI am excited about the prospect of contributing to Texas A&M University School of Law and shaping the\nnext generation of legal professionals. My teaching philosophy and plans reflect my commitment to\nacademic excellence, student success, and the practical application of legal knowledge. I welcome the\nopportunity to discuss my qualifications further and answer any questions you may have.\n-- 6 of 19 --\n\nAnthony Iliakostas Personal References\n1. Elizabeth Dambriunas – Executive Director, Alumni Advising at New York Law School\n• Phone: 212-431-2857\n• Email: elizabeth.dambriunas@nyls.edu\n• Relationship: Colleague at New York Law School\n2. Howard Meyers – Dean of Adjunct Faculty Engagement at New York Law School\n• Phone: 212-431-2338\n• Email: howard.meyers@nyls.edu\n• Relationship: Colleague at New York Law School\n3. Oral Hope – Dean of the Registrar at New York Law School\n• Phone: 212-431-2302\n• Email: oral.hope@nyls.edu\n• Relationship: Colleague at New York Law School\n4. Dan Lust – Adjunct Professor, Sports Law at New York Law School\n• Phone: 914-589-4642\n• Email: daniel.e.lust@gmail.com\n• Relationship: Close friend and colleague at New York Law School\n5. Samantha Jorden – Associate Attorney at Toerek Law, Member of TAMU Law Alumni Board\n• Phone: 512-826-5976\n• Email: samantha@legalandcreative.com\n• Relationship: Close friend, collaborated with her on Dallas Bar Association events\n-- 7 of 19 --\n\n1\nENTERTAINMENT LAW – FALL 2024\nProfessor Tony Iliakostas\nanthony.iliakostas@nyls.edu\nTeacher’s Assistant: Ranielle Nulman (ranielle.nulman@law.nyls.edu)\nWelcome to Entertainment Law! The entertainment industry is a vast world that touches on\nvarious legal issues, from intellectual property issues surrounding the use of films or TV shows\nto contractual issues that actors deal with on a daily basis, and much more.\nThe premise of this Entertainment Law course is to provide an understanding of fundamental\nblack letter law principles that are common in the various sectors of entertainment while also\nproviding a very practical approach and understanding of this niche industry. This means we\nwill review various types of entertainment-oriented contracts, review case law that has\ndrastically shaped the entertainment industry, and most importantly, bring in a few guest\nspeakers to speak to share their experience working in the entertainment industry.\nMy goal as your professor for the next few months is to show how the entertainment industry\ntouches on so many areas of law and open your eyes to subject matter that is a bit more unique\nthan what you’re accustomed to with other law school classes. We will have what I hope will be\na very engaging and enjoyable semester that will inspire you to pursue a career in\nentertainment law or at least encourage you to learn more about the entertainment law world.\nOffice Hours: Available Monday-Friday to chat, please email me to arrange for a meeting by\nphone or via Zoom.\nClass Meet Times: Every Tuesday, 7:50 PM – 9:30 PM exclusively on Zoom (links are on\nBlackboard)\nTextbook: There is no textbook assigned for this class. We will be using whatever cases,\nsample contracts, and other documents are made available on Blackboard. However, if you are\ninterested in having a supplement to learn a little more about the nuances of entertainment\nlaw, I highly recommend Entertainment Law: Fundamentals and Practice by Corey Field. I’ve\nincluded optional readings in bold and red from that book if you’d like to learn a little more\nabout the subject. Remember that the Corey Field book is purely optional!\nBlackboard: Please make sure you check Blackboard for any additional readings required for\nclass. Each file is named to its corresponding class.\nGrade: 20% - small group presentations, 80% - final (open book final to be taken between\nDecember 9 and December 19)\n-- 8 of 19 --\n\n2\nAcademic Integrity Policy: As you all know, NYLS adheres to a fairly strict academic integrity\npolicy that certainly applies to this course. You can refer to the policy at your own leisure in\nyour student handbook. Additionally, for both your small group presentation and your final\nexam, any use of generative AI, including but not limited to the creation of material from a\nlearned language model AI platform, is strictly prohibited. Any student found using generative\nAI may be subject to disciplinary action.\nPLEASE NOTE: I always award a 1/3 grade bump-up for students who regularly participate in\nclass. It’s a guaranteed way to boost your grade, regardless of whether you do well or not on\nthe final exam. I never cold call so I enthusiastically encourage class participation!\nSYLLABUS\nAugust 27: Overview of Entertainment Law\n• \tWhat it means to work in Entertainment Law\n• \tComments on the class structure, discuss the various template agreements being used,\nand cases we will use as the basis of understanding core legal principles.\n• \tDiscussion of upcoming small group presentations.\nReading - NONE\nSeptember 3: Film Production and Finance – Part 1\n• \tWhat are the components of film production?\n• \tHow does the project come together?\n• \tHow does the financing work?\n• \tWhat are the various contracts needed to successfully produce a film?\n• \tHow does talent contract with a studio/producer on a film?\n• \tWhat does a boilerplate template look like and what are the likely points to be\nnegotiated?\n• \tHow does ‘back-end’ profit participation work and how is it drafted?\nReading - Buchwald v. Paramount (January 1990 decision), Review Sample Talent\nRepresentation Agreement, Corey Field – Chapter 1, Pages 1-66\nSeptember 10: Film Production and Finance – Part 2\n• \tContinued discussion of film production issues.\n• \tDiscussion of evolution of film release and how revenue streams attach to each\nstaggered release; how this affects talent and promotion of the film.\nReading - Buchwald v. Paramount (March 1992 decision), LA Times article about Buchwald\nsettlement, Review Submission and Release Form, Sample Screen Treatment, and Sample\nOption Contract, Corey Field – Chapter 1, Pages 66-116\n-- 9 of 19 --\n\n3\nSeptember 17: Television Production\n• \tDiscuss television production, and structure and evolution of TV dissemination\n• \tDiscuss shift in consumption of television content from broadcast to cable to streaming\nand how this affected production and talent deals\n• \tIn depth discussion of ABC v. Aereo case and how it set the stage for TV streaming\nplatforms\nReading - ABC v. Aereo and WarnerMedia Direct v. Paramount Global et al, Corey Field –\nChapter 2\nSeptember 24: IP Content in Entertainment – Part 1\n• \tIntroduction into the world of intellectual property – special focus primarily on\ncopyright and trademarks\n• \tWhat are the common IP issues in the entertainment world?\n• \tAn understanding of licensing third-party material for movies or TV programs\nReading – Review of Photo/Video License Agreement and Sample Merchandise License\nAgreement\nOctober 1: IP Content in Entertainment – Part 2\n• \tContinuing discussion of IP issues in the entertainment world\n• \tWhat happens in the event there is copyright infringement?\n• \tWhat defenses exist to avoid liability in the event of an infringement?\nReading – Disney v. VidAngel, AWF v. Goldsmith, and Warner Bros. Entertainment v. The Global\nAsylum, Inc.\nOctober 8: Music Rights and Licensing in Entertainment\n• \tWhat are the components and the IP rights that attach to a musical\nrecording/composition?\n• \tWhat rights are needed to use either the composition or the recording in a TV or film\nproduction and what do those agreements look like?\nReading – Campbell v. Acuff-Rose Music and Peters v. West, Review of Sample Sync License\nAgreement, Master Use License Agreement and Mechanical (Music Sampling) License\nAgreement, Corey Field – Chapter 4\nOctober 15: Personality Rights Enforcement\n• \tAn in-depth understanding of personality rights enforcement\n• \tWhen does licensing one’s right of personality apply\n• \tAn explanation of how personality/likeness rights compare and contrast to other\ntraditional IP rights\nReading – Midler v. Ford Motor Co., Comedy III Productions, Inc. v. Gary Saderup, Inc., and HUJ\nv. GM, Review of Personality Rights License Agreement, Corey Field – Chapter 7\n-- 10 of 19 --\n\n4\nOctober 22: Labor and Employment in Entertainment Industry\n• \tWhat is the role of entertainment labor unions and guilds?\n• \tWhat rights are afforded to members of this guilds?\n• \tHow do labor unions affect the talent negotiations?\n• \tWhat legal grounds can studios/production companies take to terminate employment\nwith an actor or other employee?\nReading – Hosokawa v. SAG-AFTRA, Nader v. ABC Television, Inc., and review of SAG-AFTRA and\nWGA Memoranda of Agreements, Corey Field – Chapter 5\nOctober 29: 1st Amendment Issues in Entertainment Law\n• \tWhat is the 1st Amendment? How does it apply to entertainment properties?\n• \tWhat analysis is undertaken in the consideration of potential defamation and libel\nconcerns?\n• \tWhat is protected/unprotected speech and how does it apply in the context of\nentertainment?\n• \tHow does the 1st Amendment apply in IP oriented litigation as a defense?\nReading –NY Times v. Sullivan, Miller v. California, and Rogers v. Grimaldi, Corey Field – Chapter\n8\nNovember 5: Entertainment Law Career Roundtable (guests TBD)\nNovember 12: Group Presentations – Part 1\nNovember 19: Group Presentations – Part 2\nDecember 3: Final Exam Review\n-- 11 of 19 --\n\nINTELLECTUAL PROPERTY LAW – SPRING 2024\nProfessor Tony Iliakostas\nEmail: anthony.iliakostas@nyls.edu\nTeachers Assistants: Darryl Bobb (darryl.bobb@law.nyls.edu) and Kelly Badak (elif.badak@law.nyls.edu)\nWelcome to Intellectual Property Law! IP law is truly one of the most fun areas of law because it\ntaps into the world of creativity and ingenuity. What happens if you create a logo for a start-up tech\ncompany? What legal protections are you afforded if you create a short film? What if you invent a\ncontraption that can make breakfast for you? We will touch on the legal principles and implications\nassociated with all of that and much more during the course of this semester.\nBecause this is an IP survey class, we will focus much of our attention on the big areas of IP law:\ncopyright, trademarks, and patents. But in addition to these areas of law, we will also touch on the\nother important but less prominent areas of IP law: trade secrets, trade dress, and right of\npublicity. My goal, as your professor, is to help you gain a better understanding of these areas of\nintellectual property with the hope that you will further pursue IP coursework during your time in\nlaw school. And who knows? Maybe this class will inspire you to pursue internship and career\nopportunities in intellectual property law.\nOffice Hours: Available Monday-Friday to chat, please email me to arrange for a meeting by\nphone or via Zoom.\nClass Meet Times: Every Monday, 5:45 PM – 7:45 PM in W300 (NOTE: I know some students are\ngetting out of class just prior to our class. Don’t worry about being 5-10 minutes late. I will do my\nbest to start class at 5:50 PM just to give students a chance to arrive at class on time.)\nTextbook: Intellectual Property Law: Cases and Materials, 8th Edition by Lydia Pallas Loren and\nJoseph Scott Miller (Amazon sells it for $67 but the publisher Semaphore Press sells the e-book\nversion of the textbook directly for $30, OR you can download the e-book for free if you already\npurchased the hard copy of the book)\nBlackboard: Please make sure you check Blackboard for any additional readings required 