uestion of law or application of one’s legal training to real\nworld fact patterns or circumstances is, by its nature, going to be complex and difficult. Effectively\npresenting those matters demands that the instructor be well prepared in advance and fully versed\nin the materials. Philosophically, this means thinking strategically about the material that needs to\nbe covered, the illustrations application of that material, and working backward from that into a\nclear and comprehensive presentation that engages the students to be present, prepared, and\ninvested for each class session and assignment. \tThere must never be confusion on the subject\nmatter, expectations of the course, or accessibility of instructor.\nSecond, teaching demands flexibility. To be sure, preparation is key. But, like any deposition or\ntrial, a classroom must be flexible to be dynamic and effective. Good teaching provokes questions,\nand a good instructor is flexible enough to address those questions on the spot with the\naforementioned clarity. In that sense, the first two points flow together as effective preparation\nresults in clarity of instruction but can never become so rigid as to deny the students the opportunity\nto engage on topics and questions that are relevant and of interest to them.\nThird, teaching demands empathy. A professor at Wake Forest School of Law taught me that a no\none calls a lawyer on their best day. \tAs attorneys, we must be empathetic to our clients. That\nempathy must also define how we relate to and teach our legal students, each of whom brings\nunique experiences, ambitions, and heuristics into the classroom. It is how we model effective,\nclient-centered communication while encouraging our students to grow professionally and\npersonally to meet the challenges of the legal market. Frankly, any attorney can offer advice, but\ntruly effective advocates are able to relate to and manage their clients while also building\n-- 4 of 11 --\n\nAUSTEN IRROBALI ~ 2