nts in the courts.\nMy practice fuels my passion for advocacy. I am a ten-year, personal injury trial lawyer. I\nhave tried numerous cases to verdict in Dallas and Fort Worth – presenting everything from pre-\ntrial motions to closing arguments. These cases have all been on behalf of people who have\nsuffered injuries at the hands of others – including at the hands of doctors. I have argued motions\nbefore State and Federal Courts, and I have handled an appeal to the 5th District Court of Appeals\nin Dallas which included oral argument. I am well-versed in advocacy at the trial and appellate\ncourt levels.\nMy devotion to the study of law guides my passion for advocacy. I am the graduate of\nnumerous trial academies including the Texas Trial Lawyers Association Trial Advocacy College\nof Texas, the Dallas Bar Association Trial Academy, the William “Mac” Taylor Inn of Court Trial\nAcademy, and the Collin County Bar Association Trial Academy. I have studied for certification\nbeyond that which is required of the average lawyer, and I am a Board-Certified Civil Practice\nAdvocate by the National Board of Trial Advocacy. I have also served as the Chairman of the State\nBar of Texas Court Rules Committee. That role required extensive study and knowledge of the\nTexas Rules of Civil Procedure, as the committee reviewed and proposed changes to the Texas\nRules of Civil Procedure for the Supreme Court of Texas.\nMy present teaching commitments motivate me to make others passionate about advocacy.\nI am a regular speaker at local bar associations and have presented at State Bar of Texas CLE\nprograms including the 15th Annual Damages Course and the 2023 Advanced Evidence and\nDiscovery Course. This year, I am the Course Director for the 16th Annual Damages Course. I also\nteach Client Counseling as well as Negotiation Courses at UNT Dallas College of Law as well as\nLitigation Writing at Baylor Law. I bring the energy and intellect I use to win a client’s case to\nevery teaching opportunity – trying to impart my love for the law to the listener and help them\ngrow as a future lawyer or current professional.\nThis is why I believe I would be an excellent adjunct faculty in the area of civil procedure,\ntorts, negotiations, client counseling, advocacy, or legal writing. I welcome the challenge to take\non any other course you feel appropriate.\n-- 8 of 13 --\n\nAndy Jones – Cover Letter – TAMU Law PAGE 2 OF 2\nPlease feel free to call or email me to discuss this opportunity. I can be reached at (832)\n492-1740 (my personal cell phone) or by email at ajones.jd@gmail.com\nRespectfully,\nAndrew A. Jones\n-- 9 of 13 --\n\nApplication Forms\nFoster Child Form\nFoster Child\nI was not a foster child\n-- 10 of 13 --\n\nVeteran Status/Identification Form\nVoluntary Self-Identification of Veteran Status\nI do not identify as a veteran\nSurviving Spouse of a Veteran\nI am not a surviving spouse of a veteran\nOrphan of a Veteran\nI am not an orphan of a veteran\n-- 11 of 13 --\n\nNotice of Non-Discrimination\nAcknowledgement:\nI acknowledge that I have received the information above regarding notice of non-discrimination and abuse\n-- 12 of 13 --\n\nClery Act\nAcknowledgement:\nI acknowledge that I have received the above information regarding the Clery Act\n-- 13 of 13 --\n\n	2025-10-12 01:08:41.246483+00	[-0.047988,0.015717134,0.04357068,-0.035580683,-0.022003824,0.019758634,-0.052042462,0.030990468,0.022626227,0.009132855,-0.01137917,0.03351946,0.07811361,-0.03529058,0.004731206,0.0100688925,0.08989838,0.032802545,-0.0024102135,0.012451754,0.00393585,0.0579805,-0.0060193613,-0.043798625,-0.06736459,-0.0069926674,-0.067765206,-0.047146596,-0.11604213,-0.057311747,-0.045704756,0.059484977,0.004697365,-0.019384671,0.018709019,0.0212837,0.00062806346,0.027602168,-0.0066903606,0.015105892,-0.05515227,-0.0031408358,0.020841744,0.018527195,-0.037362676,-0.10705983,0.0043365173,-0.019573508,0.01257983,-0.030925095,-0.096482754,0.0075930827,0.0484516,0.0