65	92	jumes_steven_5636113.pdf	\N	Steven Jumes\nJudge, 485th District Court\n(817) 212-7142\n(817) 600-3083\nDecember 23, 2024\nTexas A&M University School of Law\nOffice of Human Resources\nI am writing to express my interest in becoming an Adjunct Professor at the\nTexas A&M School of Law. I am the sitting judge of the 485th District Court in\nTarrant County, where my wife and I live. I heard about becoming an adjunct from\nmy colleague of many years, Professor Jack Strickland.\nI am at a stage in my career where I can devote significant time and energy\nto teaching, and I would relish the opportunity to do so. I thoroughly enjoy\nteaching, and I believe I could provide valuable guidance and coaching for students\ntaking the critical first steps in their legal careers. I have prior teaching experience\nboth in the classroom and the workplace: having taught Criminal Law at Tarrant\nCounty College; and providing training for the United States Attorney's Office,\nTexas State Bar, Texas Criminal Defense Lawyer's Association, and Tarrant\nCounty Criminal Defense Lawyer's Association.\nI graduated Summa Cum Laude from the University of Texas at Austin in\n1993 with a major in government and a minor in philosophy. Subsequently, I\ngraduated from U.T. Law before beginning a long career defending and\nprosecuting state, federal, and white-collar crime. I have attached my curriculum\nvitae and contact information if you have any questions, and I hope you'll consider\nme for an adjunct position.\nSincerely,\nSteven Jumes\n-- 1 of 11 --\n\nSTEVEN T. JUMES\n6913 Bent Spur Dr. (817) 212-7142 office\nFort Worth, Texas 76179\nsteve@jumeslaw.com (817) 600-3083 mobile\nBoard Certified Judge in a Felony Court with Experience as a Professor, Assistant District Attorney\nand Assistant United States Attorney, seeking to Serve as an Adjunct Professor\nEDUCATION BOARD CERTIFICATION, CRIMINAL LAW 2002\n&\nCREDENTIALS UNIVERSITY OF TEXAS – AUSTIN, Austin, Texas\nBA –Government, Summa Cum Laude, U.T. Speech Team 1993\nUNIVERSITY OF TEXAS, SCHOOL OF LAW, Austin, Texas\nJD, Criminal Defense Clinic, Harris County D.A. Internship, Review of Litigation 1996\nUBS FINANCIAL ADVISOR TRAINING\nWeehawken, New Jersey\nSales and Marketing training including sales presentations and video critique 2007\nWHITE COLLAR INVESTIGATION AND LEGAL TRAINING\nColumbia, South Carolina\nWhite Collar Survey, Advanced Evidence, AFMLS Financial Investigations Course 2010-2011\nLEADERSHIP INSTITUTE, 2021\nConservative Campaign Training\nJUDGE, 485TH DISTRICT COURT August 2022-present\n Manage felony caseload\n Preside over felony jury trials\n Make personnel decisions regarding staff and other judiciary officials\n Interact with public\nCAMPAIGN FOR JUDGE, 485TH DISTRICT COURT June 2021-November 2022\nCandidate\n Mona Bailey, Treasurer\n Raised Thousands of Dollars\n Secured Endorsement of more than 90 Precinct Chairs\nTHE LAW OFFICE OF STEVEN JUMES, PLLC\nManaging Member May 2019-August 2022\n Lead Counsel in State and Federal Cases\n Manage Associate Attorney\n Trial and negotiation experience in all levels of criminal cases\n White Collar, Asset Forfeiture, Defense Practice\nVARGHESE SUMMERSETT, PLLC\nPartner, Chief of Federal Criminal Division October 2014-May 2019\n Trial Counsel in State and Federal Criminal Cases\n Federal Restitution Resolution\n Coordinated Complex Financial Investigations\n White Collar Defense Practice\n State and Federal Asset Forfeiture Practice\n-- 2 of 11 --\n\nBROWN, PC January 2013-October 2014\nSenior Counsel\n Trial Counsel in State and Federal Criminal Cases\n Restitution Resolution Counsel\n Coordinated Complex Financial Investigations\n White Collar Defense Practice\n State and Federal Asset Forfeiture Practice\nUNITED STATES ATTORNEY’S OFFICE, NORTHERN DISTRICT OF TEXAS February 2010-January 2013\nProsecutor, Criminal Division, Asset Forfeiture Section\n Trial experience in civil forfeiture, bank robbery, and wire fraud matters\n Vertical prosecution of multiple civil and criminal forfeitures\n Spearheaded an ongoing IRS initiative that has recovered $5.0 million\n Recovered several million dollars in assets, multiple weapons,\nbank accounts, residences, and parcels of real property\nAWARD TAX SERVICE April 1998 – present\nElectronic Filing Manager\n Reviewed and edited over 10,000 tax returns for accuracy\n Prepared tax returns and educated clients\nDALLAS COUNTY DISTRICT ATTORNEY’S OFFICE April 2009 – February 2010\nFelony Trial Lawyer, Public Integrity Division\n Caseload included offenses such as fraud, theft, and official oppression\n Extensive vertical prosecution and\nconsultation with various law enforcement personnel\nUBS FINANCIAL SERVICES, INC. October 2006 – January 2009\nWealth Manager\n Evaluated investment plans and complex financial statements\n Created investment strategies for individuals and small businesses\nTARRANT COUNTY COLLEGE May 2000 –December 2006\nCollege Professor\n Taught management processes, criminal procedure, and criminal law\nTARRANT COUNTY CRIMINAL DISTRICT ATTORNEY’S OFFICE August 1998 – October 2006\nFelony Trial Attorney, Supervisor of Grand Jury Division, Crimes Against Children\n Most lead jury trials during tenure as felony prosecutor\n Lead prosecution of capital murder, murder, aggravated sexual assault,\naggravated robbery, theft, assault, and dwi cases\n Trained staff for public presentation, negotiation, and strategy building\n Supervisor of the Grand Jury Section\n Specialization in Crimes Against Children\n-- 3 of 11 --\n\nPROFILE / ACCOMPLISHMENTS\nOver 24 years of professional experience with recognized results in trial advocacy, financial planning, case investigation,\npublic relations, asset recovery, and compliance consultation to include:\nTrial Advocacy Experience including lead attorney presentation of State and Federal matters, case initiation,\npreparation of multiple civil and criminal briefs and motions, presentation of complex financial records and tax\ninformation, and negotiation of hundreds of case settlements;\nBoard Certified in Criminal Law; Bar membership in the State of Texas, 5th Circuit of Appeals, and the\nNorthern Western, Southern, and Eastern Districts of Texas;\nCampaign Experience: Raised thousands of dollars, secured endorsements of city council persons, precinct\nchairs and Mona Bailey.\nProven track record of success in investigation, defense, and prosecution of complex White Collar cases\nincluding money laundering, criminal and civil forfeiture, structuring, tax evasion, mail fraud, conspiracy to\ncommit wire fraud, bank fraud;\nFinancial Planning and Sales Experience including Series 7, 66, Life and Auto Insurance licensures,\nprospecting, sales meetings, portfolio management, and allocation responsibilities, extensive training in\nSarbanes Oxley considerations and White Collar Investigation techniques, as well as successful management of\nindividual and small business retirement plans;\nCompliance Experience including consultation with various Tier One and International bank counsel and\nregulatory agencies regarding the US Bank Secrecy Act and the Patriot Act, subpoenas, seizure warrants,\nadministrative and judicial forfeiture proceedings, suspicious activity reports, as well as money service business\nreporting requirements.\nAccomplishments include:\n• Spearheading the ‘Return to Sender’ Initiative resulting in the recovery of approximately $5.0\nmillion dollars in stolen tax refunds and the pursuit of multiple conspiracy targets. The Initiative is\nongoing and expected to result in more financial recoveries and convictions. The Initiative was\naccomplished with personal coordination of Internal Revenue Service-Criminal Investigations, the\nBureau of Public Debt, the Treasury Office of the Inspector General, the U.S. Attorney’s Office in\nthe Northern District of Texas, the Department of Justice Asset Forfeiture and Money Laundering\nSection and consultation with multiple Tier One financial institutions including Citibank, Bank of\nAmerica, Treasury Direct, and various federal credit unions.\n• Established relationships with the Internal Revenue Service, the Drug Enforcement Administration,\nBureau of Alcohol Tobacco and Firearms, the Secret Service, the Food and Drug Administration,\nHomeland Security, the Texas State Attorney General’s Office, Medicaid and Medicare, and the\nFederal Bureau of Investigation.\n• Successful prosecution of Wire Fraud, Mail Fraud, Conspiracy to Launder Money, Possession and\nDistribution of Narcotics, as well as recovery and forfeiture of multiple millions of dollars in\ncriminal proceeds obtained by violations of CTR and MSB reporting requirements as well as wire\nfraud and money laundering. Also significant trial experience regarding Capital Murder, Murder,\nTheft, Aggravated Sexual Assault, and Burglary cases.\n• Expanded criminal and civil forfeiture recoveries in the Northern District of Texas.\nSPEAKING ENGAGEMENTS\nGuest Speaker-Advanced Criminal Law Course, 2015, Texas State Bar, Federal Asset Forfeiture\nWebcast Presenter-Texas Bar CLE, 2015, Texas State Bar, Asset Forfeiture in Light of One Lincoln Case\n-- 4 of 11 --\n\nGuest Speaker-Fort Worth Republican Women’s Club, 2015, Asset Forfeiture Reform\nGuest Speaker- Tim Curry Justice Center 2013, Tarrant County Criminal Defense Lawyers Association, Forfeiture\nGuest Speaker – Kerrville State Hospital 2011, Expert Testimony, Direct and Cross Examinations\nSpeaker – Northern District of Texas Asset Forfeiture Boot Camp 2011, “Civil Forfeiture”\nGuest Speaker – Health Care Strike Force 2011, “Identifying and Forfeiting Assets in Health Care Fraud Cases”\nGuest Speaker – DEA, Dallas, Texas 2010, “Asset Seizure and Forfeiture”\n-- 5 of 11 --\n\nSTEVEN T. JUMES\n6913 Bent Spur Dr. (817) 212-7142 office\nFort Worth, Texas 76179\nsteve@jumeslaw.com (817) 600-3083 mobile\nTeaching Philosophy\nI have had the fortune of t