71	98	landry_james_5704938.pdf	\N	James Landry\n1953 W Lakeside Drive\nDecatur, GA 30032\nJames@Landrypllc.com\n(678) 761-1056\nJanuary 29, 2025\nHiring Committee\nTexas A&M University School of Law\n1515 Commerce Street\nFort Worth, TX 76102\nDear Hiring Committee,\nI am writing to express my interest in an adjunct professor position at Texas A&M University School\nof Law. With a comprehensive background in entertainment and sports law, coupled with my passion\nfor teaching and mentoring future legal professionals, I am eager for the opportunity to contribute to\nyour academic community.\nAs the founder of Landry Legal, PLLC, my practice is centered on entertainment law, where I\nrepresent clients in the music and film industries. I routinely handle copyright, trademark, licensing,\nand contractual matters, ensuring artists, producers, labels, and production companies protect their\ncreative works. My firsthand experience navigating intellectual property disputes, rights clearances,\nand deal structures provides invaluable insights into the complexities of entertainment law—insights\nI am eager to share with students. Additionally, my expertise in intellectual property law has been\nrecognized in academia, with my work “Change or Be Changed: A Proposal for the NCAA to Combat\nCorruption and Unfairness by Proactively Reforming Its Regulation of Athlete Publicity Rights”\npublished in New York University's Journal of Intellectual Property and Entertainment Law. This publication\nunderscores my deep understanding of IP law and its evolving role in entertainment and creative\nindustries.\nAdditionally, I am an NFL Certified Contract Advisor and the founder of Impact Sports Agency,\nwhere I represent professional athletes in contract negotiations, endorsement deals, and career\nmanagement. My work extends beyond representation to advising on NIL (Name, Image, and\nLikeness) deals, compliance, and regulatory matters. My experience negotiating multi-million-dollar\ncontracts and protecting athletes' financial and legal interests offers a unique perspective on the\nintersection of law and sports, which I believe would benefit students interested in this evolving legal\nfield.\nBefore transitioning fully into legal practice, I was immersed in academia, attending the University of\nGeorgia and Florida State University as a Ph.D. student. During this time, I served as a Teaching\nAssistant and Instructor, honing my ability to translate complex legal concepts into engaging,\ndigestible lessons. My experience in the classroom was further enriched by learning from Dr. Thomas\nBaker and Dr. Ryan Rodenberg, both of whom shaped my approach to legal instruction. Observing\ntheir teaching methodologies provided invaluable insights into course structuring and student\nengagement. Prior to departing, I completed a comprehensive update of Dr. Rodenberg’s class\n-- 1 of 11 --\n\nmaterials, including but not limited to all new presentations, quizzes, and exams, further refining my\nskills in curriculum development. These experiences strengthened my ability to design and implement\nrigorous legal coursework that is both practical and accessible.\nThe combination of my real-world experience in entertainment and sports law, my background in\nacademia, and my commitment to mentoring students align well with the curricular needs of Texas\nA&M University School of Law. I am confident that my professional expertise and dedication to legal\neducation would make me a valuable addition to your faculty.\nI welcome the opportunity to discuss how my experience can contribute to Texas A&M University\nSchool of Law and look forward to the possibility of joining your esteemed faculty. Thank you for\nyour time and consideration.\nSincerely,\nJames Landry\n-- 2 of 11 --\n\nJAMES LANDRY\n1953 W Lakeside Drive\nDecatur, GA 30032\nJames@landrypllc.com\n(678) 761-1056\nEDUCATION\nFlorida State University, J.D., 2017\nUniversity of New Hampshire, B.S., Business Administration and Management, 2014\nB.A., Economics, 2014\nPUBLICATIONS\nChange or Be Changed: A Proposal for The NCAA To Combat Corruption and\nUnfairness by Proactively Changing Its Regulation of Athlete Publicity Rights\nNYU JOURNAL OF INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY & ENTERTAINMENT LAW 9,1 (2020) (with\nThomas Baker III)\nPRESENTATIONS\n32nd Cutting Edge Entertainment Law Seminar, Annual Conference\nInvited Panelist (August 22, 2024)\nGlobe Vision Grammy Awards Panel: The Business of Music, Annual Conference\nMusic Law Panelist (January 24, 2020)\nSport and Recreation Law Association, Annual Member Conference\n“Risk of Harm at the Farm: Mejia v. Big League Advance and a New Threat to Minor\nLeague Players” (March 2, 2019)\nPeter T. Paul College of Business and Economics Research Conference,\n“Local Economic Impact of the New University of New Hampshire Football Stadium”\n(April 25, 2014)\nACADEMIC POSITIONS HELD\nUniversity of Southern California\nResearch Assistant, Dr. Adam Feldman 2019-2020\nConducted research and data coding of U.S. Supreme Court cases.\nFlorida State University\nGraduate Assistant, Department of Kinesiology 2019-2020\nAdvisor: Dr. Ryan Rodenberg – Sports Law\nUniversity of Georgia\nGraduate Assistant, Department of Kinesiology 2018-2019\nAdvisor: Dr. Thomas Baker III – Sports Law\n-- 3 of 11 --\n\nOTHER PROFESSIONAL EMPLOYMENT\nLandry Legal, PLLC, Present\nFounder/Managing Partner\nA law firm specializing in intellectual property and transactional services for a diverse\nclient base, including businesses, entertainers, and athletes. Provide expert guidance in\nprotecting brands through strategic copyright and trademark registrations, and deliver\ncomprehensive transactional services tailored to client needs. The firm negotiates and\ndrafts critical legal documents such as licensing agreements, nondisclosure agreements,\nrecording agreements, and contracts for the licensing, acquisition, and sale of intellectual\nproperty rights, ensuring that our clients’ interests are protected.\nImpact Sports Agency, LLC, Present\nFounder/Chief Executive Officer\nEstablished a sports agency that specializes in providing college athletes Name, Image, and\nLikeness (“NIL”) services and National Football League (“NFL”) contract guidance,\ncatering to the unique needs of athletes aiming to enhance their careers both on and off the\nfield. Provide expert guidance in navigating the complexities of NIL agreements, ensuring\nathletes not only secure lucrative endorsements but also build and safeguard their personal\nbrands in a dynamic marketplace. Simultaneously, our dedicated focus on NFL contract\nnegotiations offers our clients strategic representation aimed at maximizing their career\nearnings and securing favorable contract terms. The agency negotiates and drafts essential\nlegal documents, including endorsement contracts, representation agreements, and privacy\nagreements, focused on the licensing, protection, and monetization of athlete's rights,\nensuring our clients' interests are always at the forefront.\nDe Novo Agency, Inc., 2017 – 2023\nFounder/Chief Executive Officer\nFounded and sold a music marketing company that specializes in crafting custom\nmarketing plans for artists who are looking to expand their music businesses.\nWells Fargo Securities, 2017 – 2018\nCompliance Consultant\nConducted research of emerging policies, procedures, and regulations, released by\ncorporate, to determine applicability to business groups within Wells Fargo Securities.\nDeveloped and maintained a database tracking the policies, standards, and procedures, that\naffected a business group, from development to implementation. Built the Financial\nIndustry Regulatory Authority (“FINRA”) supervisory structure chart and became the\nsubject \tmatter \texpert \tregarding \tcompliance \twith \tFINRA \tsupervisory \tstructure\nrequirements.\nPRESENT MEMBERSHIPS/AFFILIATIONS\nNew York State Bar, 2018\nMember in good standing\nNational Football League Players Association Certified Contract Advisor, 2023\nMember in good standing\n-- 4 of 11 --\n\nJames Landry’s Personal Statement\nLegal education should not only equip students with theoretical knowledge but also provide them with\npractical insights that prepare them for the realities of practicing law. My teaching philosophy is rooted\nin bridging the gap between theory and practice, ensuring that students gain an in-depth understanding\nof legal principles while also developing the skills necessary to navigate real-world legal challenges. As\nan attorney specializing in entertainment and sports law, my approach is shaped by firsthand\nexperience in high-stakes contract negotiations, intellectual property disputes, and the evolving\nregulatory landscape of the music, film, and sports industries. I believe that law students learn best\nwhen they can connect legal doctrine to tangible applications, and I aim to create a classroom\nenvironment where critical thinking, problem-solving, and professional preparedness are at the\nforefront.\nIn my teaching, I emphasize four core principles: engagement, adaptability, mentorship, and effective\ncommunication.\n1. \tEngagement Through Practical Application\nThe study of law should be interactive, engaging, and relevant to students’ career aspirations.\nI integrate case studies, contract drafting exercises, and mock negotiations into my courses,\nenabling students to apply what they learn in real-world scenarios. By analyzing entertainment\nand sports industry contracts, dissecting intellectual property disputes, and evaluating NIL\n(Name, Image, and Likeness) regulations, students gain hands-on experience that translates\nbeyond the classroom. Guest speakers from the legal and business sectors will also be\nincorporated to provide diverse perspectives on the application of law in various industries.\n2. \tAdaptability to an Evolving Legal Landscape\nThe legal field is constantly evolving, particularly in entertainment, intellectual property, and\nsports law. I plan to tailor my course materials to reflect the latest legal developments, ensuring\nthat students remain informed about current trends, legislative changes, and landmark cases.\nI also value the integration of technology in legal education, leveraging digital tools, case\nmanagement software, and online legal research databases to provide a modern learning\nexperience.\n3. \tMentorship and Professional Development\nMy goal as an educator is not only to teach legal concepts but to help students navigate their\nprofessional journeys. I encourage one-on-one discussions, career guidance, and opportunities\nfor networking. By sharing my own experiences as an attorney and NFL Certified Contract\nAdvisor, I hope to provide students with valuable insights into their potential career paths.\nFurthermore, I emphasize the importance of ethics, negotiation skills, and client advocacy,\nensuring that students develop both competence and integrity in their legal practice.\n4. \tEffective Communication of Complex Legal Concepts\nA critical component of legal education is the ability to explain complex legal topics to\nindividuals who do not have a law degree. I want my students to leave the classroom equipped\nwith the skills to effectively communicate legal concepts to clients, business professionals, and\nother non-lawyers. This ability is essential for practical legal practice, as lawyers frequently\nwork with clients who rely on their expertise to make informed decisions. By incorporating\nexercises that challenge students to simplify intricate legal matters into accessible language, I\n-- 5 of 11 --\n\naim to develop their ability to bridge the gap between legal knowledge and client\nunderstanding.\nIn sum, my teaching philosophy revolves around making legal education engaging, practical, and\nadaptable to industry needs while fostering mentorship and professional development. I look forward\nto bringing my expertise to the classroom, inspiring students, and equipping them with the knowledge\nand skills to thrive in their legal careers.\n-- 6 of 11 --\n\nReferences\nDr. Justin Sevier\njsevier@law.fsu.edu\n850-644-6596\nCharles W. Ehrhardt Professor of Litigation, Florida State University College of Law\nDr. Ryan Rodenberg\nrrodenberg@fsu.edu\n850-645-9535\nProfessor, Department of Sport Management, Florida State University\nDr. Thomas Baker\ntab3@uga.edu\n706-542-4379\nProfessor, Department of Kinesiology, University of Georgia\n-- 7 of 11 --\n\nApplication Forms\nFoster Child Form\nFoster Child\nI was not a foster child\n-- 8 of 11 --\n\nVeteran Status/Identification Form\nVoluntary Self-Identification of Veteran Status\nI do not identify as a veteran\nSurviving Spouse of a Veteran\nI am not a surviving spouse of a veteran\nOrphan of a Veteran\nI am not an orphan of a veteran\n-- 9 of 11 --\n\nClery Act\nAcknowledgement:\nI acknowledge that I have received the above information regarding the Clery Act\n-- 10 of 11 --\n\nNotice of Non-Discrimination\nAcknowledgement:\nI acknowledge that I have received the information above regarding notice of non-discrimination and abuse\n-- 11 of 11 --\n\n	2025-10-12 01:08:42.055808+00	[-0.019031746,0.02178982,-0.00784014,-0.11141122,0.0068936236,0.017169686,0.036908373,0.0033081493,0.052142974,0.066098295,-0.032668207,0.025854856,-0.009925232,-0.0013905113,0.02414185,0.027611466,0.027646372,0.07863914,-0.10828088,0.08473634,0.05713392,0.053481784,-0.025239222,-0.026375368,-0.0870499,-0.017453985,0.0026241315,0.010211919,-0.14410664,-0.10451928,-0.052473657,0.11363609,-0.006587557,0.07934037,0.094369,0.0040680594,-0.009624393,0.00467346,0.019031595,0.033363774,0.018919777,-0.044166587,-0.0025153563,0.0638466,-0.09043769,-0.05422695,0.040459953,0.0046194135,0.007656348,0.034846585,-0.084457725,-0.0033200951,0.011649984,0.0029137041,0.021335324,-0.02825455,0.024237886,0.06023745,-0.011593239,0.008130499,0.030415863,0.057209123,-0.04348845,0.019638639,-0.004528467,-0.02