75	102	loforese_john_4954725 (1).pdf	\N	JOHN LOFORESE\njohnloforese@gmail.com • linkedin.com/in/johnloforese • (845) 987-4952 • Austin, Texas\nPROFESSIONAL EXPERIENCE\nGoogle LLC, Austin, Texas \t2019 – present\nPrivacy Counsel\n● Lead counsel for FTC Consent Order compliance and engagement with external assessors, managing FTC\nand external assessor engagements related to Google’s comprehensive privacy program.\n● Lead counsel for Google and Alphabet EU-U.S. data transfer compliance processes.\n● Lead counsel on privacy issues relating to mergers and acquisitions diligence and negotiations, designing\nand executing diligence assessments.\n● Lead third party risk management program by negotiating data protection agreements, conducting third\nparty audits, and counseling product teams on third party privacy and security risks.\n● Counsel data protection impact assessments for new products and features, privacy and security\ncompliance requirements, third party data protection risk.\n● Analyze and respond to litigation and inquiries of U.S. and international privacy regulators.\n● Provide specialist consultation and legal teams, software engineering, compliance, and government affairs.\n● Train attorneys and engineers on global data protection laws and enforcement risks.\nUniversity of California, San Francisco College of the Law \t2022 – present\nAdjunct Professor of Law\n● Teach foundational class on American data protection and privacy laws including Constitutional right to\nprivacy, privacy torts, FTC enforcement actions, VCDPA, CCPA, HIPAA, BIPA, FCRA, GLBA, COPPA,\nFirst Amendment limitations, and privacy incident response.\nThe Dun & Bradstreet Corporation, Short Hills, New Jersey \t2018 – 2019\nPrivacy and Compliance Attorney\n● Designed and executed internal privacy and compliance audits.\n● Counseled privacy incident response in coordination with security operations teams.\n● Drafted global and regional privacy notices to maintain compliance with emerging data protection laws.\n● Negotiated data privacy and security contracts for data driven products and services.\nState of New Jersey Office of the Attorney General, Trenton, New Jersey \t2016 – 2018\nDeputy Attorney General\n● Outside Counsel to the Office of Information Technology: Drafted and reviewed data privacy, security, and\ncompliance notices and policies regarding statewide processing of information by government agencies.\n● Outside Counsel to the Office of the Comptroller: Represented agency in matters related to disclosure\ninformation under the Open Public Records Act and public contract audits.\n● Outside Counsel to Division of Pensions and Benefits: Represented agency before NJ Appellate and\nAdministrative Law Divisions.\nEDUCATION\nAmerican University Washington College of Law, Washington, D.C. \t2015\nJuris Doctor, cum laude.\n● Law Review, Journals: AU International Law Review (Senior Editor); Human Rights Brief (Lead Web\nEditor); Journal of International Service (Editor-in-Chief).\n● Internships: Financial Industry Regulatory Authority, Rockville, Maryland (2015); U.S. Securities and\nExchange Commission (2014); Office of the Public Defender, Rockville Maryland (2013).\nMcGill University, Montréal, Québec \t2012\nBachelor of Arts, Dual Major and Joint Honors in Political Science and Philosophy.\n● Editor, Canadian Undergraduate Journal of Philosophy.\nBAR ADMISSIONS AND CERTIFICATIONS\n● Licensed Attorney: Texas, New York, New Jersey\n● Professional Certifications: CIPP/US (IAPP); GASQ Certified Data Protection Officer\n-- 1 of 12 --\n\nJOHN LOFORESE\njohnloforese@gmail.com • linkedin.com/in/johnloforese • (845) 987-4952 • Austin, Texas\nTo the hiring committee at Texas A&M Law:\nI am writing to express my interest in the Adjunct Professor position at Texas A&M University Law School.\nWith my background in teaching law, combined with my extensive experience as a privacy counsel at Google, I\nam confident in my ability to effectively convey the importance of data protection and privacy laws to your\nstudents.\nAs an Adjunct Professor at the University of California, San Francisco College of the Law, I have developed and\ntaught a foundational course on American data protection and privacy laws for the past two years. The course\ncovers a comprehensive range of U.S. Privacy topics, including the Constitutional right to privacy, privacy torts,\nFTC enforcement actions, U.S. State privacy laws, and sectoral laws and regulations including HIPAA, BIPA,\nFCRA, GLBA, and COPPA. The subject matter of this course is dynamic and continues to be of great interest to\nstudents, where personal data is constantly collected, processed, and shared in an ever-expanding set of contexts.\nAs such, it is crucial for future legal professionals to have a strong understanding of these laws and regulations\nto protect the privacy rights of individuals and ensure compliance. The materials used in these courses are up to\ndate and are supplemented with emerging primary and secondary sources.\nMy unique experience as privacy counsel at Google has provided me with a deep understanding of the practical\napplication of data protection and privacy laws in the real world. I have advised on a wide range of legal issues,\nincluding FTC Consent Order compliance, EU-U.S. data transfer compliance, privacy issues relating to mergers\nand acquisitions, third-party risk management, and data protection impact assessments.\nThis experience has equipped me with the skills and knowledge necessary to teach students how to analyze\ncomplex legal issues, apply the law to real-world scenarios, and effectively advocate for their clients. I believe\nthat my practical experience will bring a valuable perspective to the classroom and help students to develop the\nskills they need to succeed in the legal profession.\nI am known for my emphasis on student engagement and strive to provide students with a dynamic and\ninteractive learning environment. I encourage students to actively participate in class discussions, ask questions,\nand challenge my viewpoints. I also provide multiple written assignments and hold regular office hours to offer\npersonalized feedback and support. This approach has proven effective, as evidenced by the positive feedback I\nhave received from my students.\nI am confident that my relevant teaching experience and expertise, along with my commitment to student\nengagement and practical application, make me an ideal candidate for the Adjunct Professor position at Texas\nA&M University Law School. I am eager to bring my passion for data protection and privacy law to your\ninstitution and contribute to the education of future legal professionals.\nThank you for considering my application. I look forward to the opportunity to discuss how my qualifications\nalign with your needs further.\nThank you for your time and consideration,\nJohn Lo Forese\n-- 2 of 12 --\n\nU.S. Privacy Law 257 Syllabus\nUC Law SF | Fall 2023\nKelly Cooke (cookekelly@uclawsf.edu)\nJohn LoForese (loforesejohn@uclawsf.edu)\nOverview\nThis two credit course introduces students to foundational U.S. privacy law and regulatory\nconcepts, with an emphasis on applying material that prepares students to counsel businesses\nthat process significant amounts of personal information.\nLearning Outcomes\n● Demonstrate a combination of legal knowledge, legal writing, strategic thinking, and a\nset of business-related communication skills to counsel entities on privacy and data\nprotection laws and regulations.\n● Analyze fact patterns for legal risk related to U.S. State Laws, FTC enforcement actions,\nand U.S. sectoral regulation including the Children's Online Privacy Protection Rule and\nFair Credit Reporting Act, as well as key requirements related to data breach\nregulations.\n● Understand and apply effective privacy and data breach litigation and enforcement\nstrategies, presenting and defending legal arguments from various viewpoints and\ninterests.\n● Purposefully read privacy notices without falling asleep.\nAbout the Lecturers\nThe lecturers for this course are in-house counsel, so the presentation of material will typically\nfocus on legal and regulatory issues impacting corporations. By the end of this course, students\nshould have gained foundational knowledge of U.S. privacy law needed to succeed in privacy\nand data protection counseling environments as in house or outside counsel. In the shorter\nterm, the course should also help prepare students to achieve certification in professionally\nrecognized certifications such as the CIPP/US.\nIn the hopes of fostering open discussion of policy and legal issues, the opinions of the lecturers\nwill be presented for educational purposes only, and won’t reflect the views of Google or the\ninstructors in their individual capacities.\nCasebook\nConsumer Privacy and Data Protection, Third Edition (2021)\nDaniel J. Solove, Paul M. Schwartz\nThis textbook will form about ~50% of content for the course, but because U.S. privacy law is\nchanging at a rate unseen since its origins, it will be heavily supplemented with emerging\nprimary sources (e.g. laws passed since 2020, regulatory enforcement actions) and secondary\nsources (e.g. comparative analysis and commentary on emerging privacy laws).\n-- 3 of 12 --\n\nClass Meetings\n● Fridays @ 10:20-12:30 PST (Aug. 25 - Nov. 17). No class on Nov 10 with makeup\nlecture @ Tuesday Nov. 21\n● Fully Remote (see class Canvas page for Zoom meeting instructions)\nAssessments (subject to confirmation by Registrar’s Office)\n● 60%: Final (2.5 hours remote open-universe take home exam)\n● 30%: 3 take home assignments\n● 10%: Participation\nOffice hours: Virtual, weekly on Friday afternoons at 1:00 PM PST or by appointment.\nAttendance and Participation\n● Will be monitored closely, but not overly socratic\n● Directly affects participation grade\n● Keeps things way more interesting for everyone\n● More information on schoo