pliance. This practical\nknowledge, combined with my academic background, allows me to bridge theory and\npractice in the classroom.\n-- 1 of 14 --\n\nMy commitment to diversity and inclusion is demonstrated through my founding role in\nNew Ground, a Muslim-Jewish dialogue group in Los Angeles, and my years of service as a\nvolunteer mediator in Los Angeles small claims court, where I worked with litigants from\ndiverse socioeconomic and cultural backgrounds. These experiences have shaped my\nteaching philosophy and approach to mentoring students from all backgrounds.\nI have included my CV, recent course evaluations and other required materials in my\napplication. I would welcome the opportunity to discuss how I could contribute to the\nuniversity's mission and community.\nSincerely,\nNicholas Merkin\n-- 2 of 14 --\n\nPage 1 of 5\nNicholas Merkin\nnmerkin@usc.edu\n310-623-0915\nEXPERIENCE\nUNIVERSITY OF SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA, SOL PRICE SCHOOL OF PUBLIC POLICY\nAdjunct Instructor in the Graduate Program in Healthcare Administration, August 2017-Present\nAs an adjunct instructor in the University of Southern California’s graduate program in healthcare administration,\nNick lectures in the areas of Leadership of Healthcare Organizations (HMGT 520), Population Health\nManagement (HMGT 575), Healthcare Compliance and Accountability (HMGT 601), the Strategic Management\nof Healthcare Organizations (HMGT 570), and Law and Public Policy (PPD 314). Nick has also served as faculty\nfor the University of Southern California’s Healthcare Management Workshop for Senior Healthcare Executives\nand at the 2018-2019 USC Freshman Welcome Week Micro-Seminars Program.\nUNIVERSITY OF SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA, GOULD SCHOOL OF LAW\nLecturer in Law, August 2019-Present\nAs a lecturer in law at the Gould School of Law at the University of Southern California, Nick teaches courses in\nRegulatory Compliance (LAW 598) and Healthcare Compliance (LAW 572). Nick also delivered a law school-\nwide lecture on the legal history of the U.S. healthcare system in March of 2021, at the invitation of the law\nschool dean and faculty committee.\nCOMPLIAGENT\nChief Executive Officer, October 2013-Present\nAs part of his consulting practice, Nick serves as a fractional or interim Chief Compliance Officer for healthcare\norganizations experiencing rapid growth, enforcement challenges, or in the process of merger and acquisition.\nNick has a thorough knowledge of complex and rapidly changing state and federal laws and policies regarding\norganizational governance issues, board oversight and liability, compliance auditing, the Stark Law, the Anti-\nKickback Statute, HIPAA privacy, data security, and the False Claims Act. Nick also has particular expertise in\nthe areas of alternate payment methodologies and innovative provider structures for networks within the\nhealthcare industry.\nGIBSON, DUNN & CRUTCHER, LLP and NELSON HARDIMAN, LLP\nAssociate Attorney and Of Counsel, September 2001-September 2013\nAs an associate and of counsel attorney with the above law firms, Nick practiced in the areas of healthcare law\nand regulation.\nSPEAKING ENGAGEMENTS\n• \tFeatured Speaker, A New Sheriff in Town: The FTC’s Emergence in Healthcare Privacy Enforcement and\nNewly Issued Guidance, Healthcare Compliance Association (HCCA, 2024 HCCA Annual Compliance\nInstitute Conference (April 15, 2024).\n• \tFeatured Speaker, Confidentiality Matters: HIPAA Training With a Focus on Behavioral Health,\nBehavioral Health Association of Providers (BHAP), BHAP Web Conference Series (August 9, 2023).\n• \tFeatured Speaker, Emergency and Disaster Preparedness Basics, Compliatric Web Conference Series\n(June 14, 2023).\n-- 3 of 14 --\n\nPage 2 of 5\n• \tHost, Compliance Conversations Podcast (Recorded November 22, 2022) episode, “Turning the Tables:\nOur Guest Interviews Our Host CJ Wolf” (November 2022).\n• \tFeatured Speaker, OMG! What Next? The Basics of Disaster Preparedness in Healthcare Settings,\nB