79	106	miller_ashley_5788571.pdf	\N	ASHLEY FLOREK MILLER\n( 203.260.4225 \tashley.florek@gmail.com \tJersey City, NJ 07302\nHiring Committee\nTexas A&M University School of Law\n1515 Commerce St.\nFort Worth, TX 76102\nDear Hiring Committee,\nI am excited to apply for an Adjunct Professor of Law position at Texas A&M University School of\nLaw. With over a decade of experience in litigation and management, I am eager to bring my practical\nexpertise and deep commitment to mentorship into the classroom.\nCurrently serving as the Managing Attorney at the Office of the Appellate Defender (OAD) in New\nYork City, I manage many day-to-day and long term operations and systems within the office. OAD is often\nnoted to be the city’s premier training office for criminal appellate defense, where we develop the next\ngeneration of public defenders through intensive supervision, skills training, and hands-on litigation\nexperience. In this role, I have trained and mentored junior attorneys, paralegals, and fellows, ensuring they\ngain the analytical, research, and advocacy skills necessary for effective representation.\nMy career has spanned trial and appellate litigation, criminal defense, and civil rights work. Before\nOAD, I was a Senior Associate at Slater Slater Schulman LLP, handling complex litigation representing sexual\nabuse survivors in New York who brought suit against the state under the Adult Survivors Act. Most of the\nclients I represented were sexually abused by corrections officers within the state and county prison facilities.\nMy work here not only involved a deep understanding of procedural and substantive law, but also important\n“soft skills” such as trauma-informed communication, media advocacy, and understanding of personal\nboundaries. I have also spent time working as a Supervising Attorney at the Urban Justice Center,\nadvocating for marginalized communities in housing matters both in tenant defense work and affirmative\nlitigation on behalf of tenants unions in New York City.\nBefore my time practicing in New York, I spent 8 years working in criminal defense work in\nMassachusetts advocating on behalf of largely indigent individuals charged with misdemeanor and felony\noffenses. During my time in Massachusetts, I helped to expand my firm’s private practice while\nsimultaneously supervising junior attorneys and staff on both private and public defense matters, as well as\nsome civil matters. Teaching and mentorship have been central to my practice and I am deeply committed to\nfostering student growth through experiential learning and critical thinking.\nI would welcome the opportunity to teach courses related to criminal law, appellate advocacy, trial\npractice, professional responsibility, or legal research and writing, but I am open to any subject where my\nexperience can benefit students. I am eager to contribute to Texas A&M Law’s mission and would appreciate\nthe opportunity to discuss how my background aligns with your curricular needs. Thank you for your time\nand consideration. I look forward to the possibility of joining your faculty.\nSincerely,\nAshley Florek Miller\n-- 1 of 9 --\n\nASHLEY FLOREK MILLER\n( 203.260.4225 \tashley.florek@gmail.com \tJersey City, NJ 07302\nEXPERIENCED LITIGATION ATTORNEY AND MANAGER\n10 Years of Litigation Experience | Oral Advocacy & Complex Litigation Matters | Extensive Public and Private Sector Management Experience\nSpent five (5) years as founder and partner of a small but mighty criminal defense litigation practice. Went on to contribute extensive\nlitigation experience as Sr. Associate at mass tort firm Slater Slater Schulman. Most recently a member of the leadership team while serving\nas the Managing Attorney at the Office of the Appellate Defender. Recognized for unique combination of decisive legal strategy, deeply\ngenuine client relations, and instinctive business acumen as driving force behind multi-year client relationships. Not only took charge of\nmarketing and business development while leading a small law firm, but simultaneously produced positive outcomes for clients in both\ncivil and criminal legal matters. Expert in nuanced navigation of legal procedure / courtroom procedure backed by thorough discovery and\ninvestigations. Extensive supervisory, managerial, and executive leadership experience in the public and private sector.\nCORE QUALIFICATIONS\n• \tAdmission to the New York State Bar and 10 years of progressively responsible experience performing highly complex and\nsignificant legal work subsequent to admission to any state bar.\n• \tSupervisory experience over other attorneys, legal, and non-legal staff in an administrative and managerial capacity.\n• \tExceptional academic credentials with experience evaluating, negotiating, and settling pre-litigation and pending litigation on\nbehalf of clients.\n• \tExtensive litigation experience, including defense work in areas of torts, municipal law, personal injury, and criminal law. Prepared\ncomplex legal memoranda and made recommendations based on independent judgment and risk analysis.\n• \tExperience making appearances in state courts across multiple jurisdictions.\n• \tLegal skills include strong legal writing skills, analytical skills, legal research, written advocacy, investigative strategy, litigation\nmanagement, critical thinking, documentation, risk assessments, taking depositions, preparing and conducting trials, and leading\nsettlement negotiations.\n• \tStrong technical skills: Westlaw, LexisNexis, Clio, Microsoft Office Suite (Word, Excel, PowerPoint), Pacer, QuickBooks, Legal\nServer, Smart Advocate.\nPROFESSIONAL HISTORY\nManaging Attorney | Office of the Appellate Defender | New York, NY \t2024 – Present\nServe as a key member of the leadership team that oversees the executive functions and operational management of the nonprofit\norganization.\n• \tSupervise a team of paralegals and the client services director, ensuring seamless client support during the intake process and\nthroughout extended pre-assignment periods, often lasting over eighteen months.\n• \tDirect and manage intake operations, including case evaluation, documentation, record compiling, case triaging, and preparation\nto ensure readiness for attorney assignment.\n• \tOversee client services director to address client needs unrelated to litigation of appeals, offering critical support and resources\nto clients awaiting attorney assignment.\n• \tCollaborate with Attorney-in-Charge and Deputy Attorney-in-Charge to develop policies, improve processes, and maintain\noperational standards throughout the organization.\nSenior Associate | Slater Slater Schulman LLP | New York, NY \t2023 – 2024\nPersonally recruited by a mass tort and catastrophic injury firm. One of only two associates supervising a team of junior attorneys and close\nto 2K cases under New York’s Adult Survivors Act. Serve under the managing attorney and oversee the drafting, review, and filing of\ncomplaints, demonstrating expertise in handling all aspects of tort litigation.\n• \tSupplied litigation and managerial experience to junior associates and a growing caseload, overseeing case development,\nproviding strategic guidance, and mentoring junior team members to ensure effective case management and professional\ndevelopment.\n• \tStepped up to streamline the complaints filing process and supervise work by third-party legal vendors. Improved visibility into\ndeadlines, supporting documentation, and case acceptance. Results included compressing filing turnaround and package\ncompletion.\n-- 2 of 9 --\n\nASHLEY FLOREK MILLER\n( 203.260.4225 \tashley.florek@gmail.com \tJersey City, NJ 07307\nSupervising Attorney | Urban Justice Center | New York, NY \t2022 – 2023\nSupervised team of five (5) junior attorneys, ultimately overseeing combined caseload of up to 350 and personal caseload of ~40. Assigned\nto the Safety Net Project for this storied not-for-profit and focused on landlord-tenant relationships in accordance with the New York City\nDepartment of Housing Preservation and Development.\n• \tEncouraged creative yet pragmatic legal thinking and mentored attorneys in courtroom procedures and litigation. Provided sound\nlegal counsel to clients and direct reports, reviewing complex and highly technical laws, rules, and regulations.\n• \tGained experience in working with a high-profile public sector service agency and deftly increased the amount of time clients\nremained in their apartments, meeting organizational objectives.\n• \tAdhered to litigation best practices and spent three (3) days weekly appearing in New York City Civil Court, handling up to five (5)\ncases daily, navigating landlord-tenant disputes and related settlement negotiations. Simultaneously coached team members in\nadvocating for client interests.\n• \tEffectively worked with all levels of management, government officials, attorneys, the Court, and the public, demonstrating ability\nto interact professionally with all parties.\n• \tDrafted clear, concise, and accurate memoranda, legal briefs, and motions, imbuing each document with meticulous legal analysis\nand adherence to relevant statutes, regulations, and precedent.\nPartner | Gens, Stanton, and Florek, PC | Boston, MA \t2017 – 2022\nRestructured firm and directed day-to-day business development and financial management while simultaneously managing litigation\ncaseload of 40-50. Zealously litigated for private and state-appointed clients charged with all manner of offenses. Led in-court evidentiary\nmotions and served as First Chair. Supervised one (1) associate and multiple legal interns who handled civil litigation and transactional\nmatters (critical to firm growth). Adopted writing style with emphasis on brevity and persuasion.\n• \tGrew practice caseload by 3X between 2017 and 2022. Won new business through referrals and strategic marketing. Maintained\ndiligence in publicizing positive outcomes and directed backend demographic / segmentation analyses.\n• \tBrought a new level of organization to the practice and fundamentals in legal research, in-court advocacy, and courtroom\ndemeanor. Ensured 100% adherence to meeting deadlines and follow-through with structured calendaring.\n• \tNegotiated plea agreements with District Attorney and Attorney General’s offices, including pre-arraignment diversionary\nprograms, pre-trial probationary programs, and admissions to preserve clients’ records and mitigate sentencing concerns.\nWorked with clients to seal and expunge criminal record entries and assisted clients with criminal appeals.\n• \tDemonstrated strong legal acumen and produced a 90%-win rate on behalf of criminally charged clients. Coordinated work with\nfirm’s investigators and experts in medicine, ballistics, technology, psychology, DNA, and financial analysis. Successfully litigated\nmultiple motions to suppress based on researched case law and produced positive outcomes after court review of motions for\nrelease of custody.\n• \tEngaged in detailed discovery as part of legal strategy and opened the door to future motions to compel or exclude.\n• \tAdditional work included civil litigation encompassing business law, contracts, and landlord/tenant matters.\n• \tRepresented multiple individuals called to testify in front of grand juries. Negotiated with prosecutors to invoke Fifth Amendment.\nAssociate Counsel | William E. Gens Law Offices, PC | Boston, MA \t2014 – 2017\nOffered role as Associate after passing the bar and after working for the firm as a law clerk for 2.5 years during law school studies.\nSuccessfully secured Bar Advocate contract and effectively managed client expectations. Represented criminal defendants at trial and\nappellate levels and assisted senior attorneys in defending serious criminal cases from arraignment to trial.\n• \tDemonstrated nuance in courtroom procedure and exposed to projects in civil defense, business litigation, and transactional\nwork, as well as negotiation and settlement tactics.\nEDUCATION\nJuris Doctor | Suffolk University Law School \t2011 – 2014\n• \tStaff Member, Health & Biomedical Journal\nBachelor of Arts in Political Science and History | University of Connecticut \t2010\n-- 3 of 9 --\n\nASHLEY FLOREK MILLER\n( 203.260.4225 \tashley.florek@gmail.com \tJersey City, NJ 07302\nPersonal Statement\nTeaching law is both a privilege and a responsibility—one that extends beyond conveying legal\ndoctrine to preparing students for the realities of practice. My approach to legal education is rooted in three\ncore principles: experiential learning, critical thinking, and ethical lawyering. These principles shape how I\nmentor, train, and teach, ensuring that students develop not only the technical skills to succeed but also the\njudgment and integrity to navigate the profession with confidence.\nAs the Managing Attorney at the Office of the Appellate Defender (OAD)—New York City’s premier\ntraining office for criminal appellate defense—I have had the honor of involvement with training programs\nfor junior attorneys, fellows, and law clerks. OAD’s training model combines rigorous doctrinal instruction\nwith hands-on litigation experience, reinforcing my belief that students learn best when they apply legal\nprinciples to real-world problems. I bring this philosophy into the classroom by incorporating practical\nexercises such as mock oral arguments, case analysis workshops, and drafting assignments that mirror actual\nlegal practice.\nBeyond technical proficiency, I emphasize critical thinking and strategic decision-making. Law is not\njust about knowing rules—it is about understanding how to use them effectively. In my appellate work, I train\nattorneys and paralegals to dissect complex legal issues, anticipate counterarguments, and craft persuasive\nadvocacy. In the classroom, I challenge students to analyze legal problems from multiple perspectives,\nfostering intellectual curiosity and resilience. In my role, I also supervise a team of social workers and advise\nlegal professionals regarding the intersection of social assistance and the law. This area is an important,\nalbeit often understated, aspect of law practice that I intend to incorporate into my teaching.\nFinally, I view legal education as a training ground for ethical lawyering. Whether teaching criminal\nlaw, appellate advocacy, or trial practice, I would integrate discussions on professional responsibility, client-\ncentered representation, and systemic justice. I would encourage students to grapple with the ethical\ndilemmas they will face in practice, equipping them with the tools to navigate difficult decisions with\nintegrity.\nIf given the opportunity to teach at Texas A&M University School of Law, I would bring my passion\nfor mentorship, my commitment to experiential learning, and my dedication to preparing students for the\ncomplexities of legal practice. I look forward to the possibility of contributing to the law school’s academic\ncommunity and shaping the next generation of lawyers.\n-- 4 of 9 --\n\nASHLEY FLOREK MILLER\n( 203.260.4225 \tashley.florek@gmail.com \tJersey City, NJ 07302\nReferences\n1. \tBradford R. Stanton \t(617) 945-3660\n2. \tLeslie Hansen-Weiden \t(214) 535-1476\n3. \tGow Mosby Jr. \t(631) 880-8595\n-- 5 of 9 --\n\nApplication Forms\nFoster Child Form\nFoster Child\nI was not a foster child\n-- 6 of 9 --\n\nVeteran Status/Identification Form\nVoluntary Self-Identification of Veteran Status\nI do not identify as a veteran\nSurviving Spouse of a Veteran\nI am not a surviving spouse of a veteran\nOrphan of a Veteran\nI am not an orphan of a veteran\n-- 7 of 9 --\n\nClery Act\nAcknowledgement:\nI acknowledge that I have received the above information regarding the Clery Act\n-- 8 of 9 --\n\nNotice of Non-Discrimination\nAcknowledgement:\nI acknowledge that I have received the information above regarding notice of non-discrimination and abuse\n-- 9 of 9 --