e Southern District of Texas\nForeign Attorney’s License in Vietnam - 2005\n-- 4 of 10 --\n\nTeaching Philosophy\nAs an applicant for your law professor position, my teaching philosophy revolves\naround two core principles: the Socratic method and the use of practical exercises\nto prepare students for the demands of the bar exam and the practice of law. I\nbelieve that the combination of these pedagogical tools cultivates critical thinking,\nanalytical rigor, and real-world application, providing students with the skills they\nneed to become competent, ethical lawyers.\nThe Socratic method, central to my teaching approach, fosters an environment\nwhere students actively engage with the material and with each other. I believe\nthat law students learn best when they are challenged to think on their feet,\ndefend their reasoning, and engage in constructive debate. By asking probing\nquestions, I encourage students to examine legal principles from multiple angles,\ndevelop their arguments, and refine their critical thinking skills. This method\npromotes a deeper understanding of legal concepts beyond rote memorization\nand prepares students to handle complex legal issues they will encounter in\npractice.\nIn addition to the Socratic method, I place a strong emphasis on integrating\npractical exercises into the classroom. The legal profession requires not only\nintellectual capacity but also the ability to apply knowledge in real-world settings.\nTo bridge this gap, I regularly incorporate simulations, problem-solving exercises,\nand multiple choice questions into my teaching. These exercises are designed to\nmimic the types of tasks students will face on the bar exam and in their legal\ncareers, from drafting motions to advising clients in hypothetical scenarios. By\nengaging in these practical activities, students learn how to translate theory into\npractice, develop their advocacy skills, and gain confidence in their ability to\nnavigate the legal landscape.\nTogethe