 would be happy to provide copies of my writing samples. I look forward\nto meeting with you and discussing this opportunity in more detail.\nSincerely,\n/s/ R. Casey O’Neill\nR. Casey O’Neill\n-- 1 of 9 --\n\n5460 Huntly Drive\nFort Worth, Texas 76109 \nR. CASEY O’NEILL\nr.casey.oneill@gmail.com\nMobile: (817) 565-8806\nEDUCATION\nUniversity of Houston Law Center Houston, Texas \tJ.D. – May 2011\nAssociate Editor, Houston Law Review\nUnited States Military Academy West Point, New York \tB.S. – June 2001\nMajor: Economics with a Civil Engineering Track\nLEGAL EXPERIENCE AND EXPERTISE\n§ Litigation: Experience and expertise in the pre-trial, trial, and appellate stages of litigation, in both state and federal\ncourt, across a wide array of practice areas, including breach of contract, non-competition, non-solicitation, trade\nsecrets, unfair competition, rights of first refusal, shareholder disputes, mineral royalties, real property ownership, patent\ninfringement, and trademark infringement.\n§ Contract Law: Experience and expertise in contract litigation, interpretation, and negotiation. Experience drafting\ncontracts concerning independent contractor classification, non-competition covenants, software licensing, mandatory\nalternative dispute resolution procedures (mediation and arbitration), and acquisitions.\n§ Labor and Employment: Experience and expertise in issues surrounding 1099 versus W-2 employment classifications,\nnon-competition covenants, non-solicitation covenants and non-disclosure agreements, as well as employee and\nindependent contractor termination and resignation issues.\n§ Intellectual Property: Experience and expertise in patent litigation, trade secrets litigation, trademark infringement\nlitigation, and software licensing litigation, trademark prosecution, and copyright issues.\nLEGAL EMPLOYMENT\nO’NEILL LAW, PLLC – Fort Worth, Texas \tJanuary 2023 – Present\nFounding Attorney\n§ Advise and assist clients on a wide variety of issues, including complex civil litigation, labor and employment,\nintellectual property, contract drafting and negotiation, licensing, shareholder rights, and real property disputes.\nUNITEDHEALTH GROUP, INC. – Fort Worth, Texas \tMay 2018 – January 2023\nVice President, Assistant General Counsel – USHEALTH Group, Inc.\n§ Oversaw and managed outside counsel in all aspects of ongoing litigation, including disputes related to policyholders’\nclaim denials, former agents’ breaches of contract, intellectual property infringement, labor and employment.\n§ Researched applicable law and advised in matters associated merger and acquisition of USHEALTH Group, Inc. by\nUnitedHealth Group, Inc.\n§ Researched and advised company management on a wide variety of legal matters including contract drafting and\nnegotiation, insurance disputes, labor and employment issues, intellectual property strategy and impact of current and\nfuture branding and marketing efforts.\nWICK, PHILLIPS, GOULD & MARTIN, LLP – Fort Worth, Texas \tJuly 2014 – May 2018\nAssociate Attorney\n§ As first chair, successfully defended a multimillion-dollar fraudulent transfer claim and obtained a significant judgment\nfor attorney’s fees.\n§ As second chair, obtained a temporary injunction unwinding a $34 Million transaction concerning a right of first refusal\nin a shareholder dispute in favor of a cardiac monitoring company.\n§ Successfully defended a plaintiff’s appeal of the denial of a temporary injunction in a non-compete dispute.\n§ Drafted and filed pleadings, motions, and oppositions, and conducted pre-trial discovery in cases across a wide variety\nof practice areas, including contracts, non-competes, real estate, and shareholder disputes.\n-- 2 of 9 --\n\nR. CASEY O’NEILL - Page 2\nNELSON BUMGARDNER CASTO, PC – Fort Worth, Texas \tFebruary 2013 – July 2014\nAssociate Attorney\n§ Drafted and filed pleadings, motions, and oppositions, and conducted pre-trial discovery in over 40 cases asserting\ninfringement of patents covering various aspects of computer software and hardware.\n§ Advised clients on compliance with contractual obligations, common law, and state and federal regulations.\nBRACEWELL AND GIULIANI, LLP – Dallas, Texas \tOctober 2011 – February 2013\nAssociate Attorney\n§ Researched and drafted pleadings, motions, and requests for discovery for cases filed in both federal and Texas courts\nacross a wide variety of practice areas.\nMILITARY SERVICE\nUnited States Army - Aviation Captain \tJune 2001 – October 2008\nCompany Commander \tU.S. Army Aviation Logistics School\n§ Commanded and led over 275 Officers, Warrant Officers, and Noncommissioned Officers comprising the instructors\nand staff of the Department of Attack Helicopters Training, Department of Trades Training, and the Latin American\nTraining Division.\nAirborne Aviation Platoon Leader \tB/1-159th Airborne Aviation Regiment\n§ Commanded and led over 35 Warrant Officers, NCOs, and soldiers conducting combat air operations in Iraq, while\nplanning and executing a full range of combat aviation missions in all areas of Iraq, including air assaults and air\nmovements, as well as other helocast operations.\n§ Achieved Pilot-in-Command proficiency rating for the UH-60L Blackhawk helicopter and led over 40 combat flight\nmissions as Air Mission Commander.\n§ Conducted “high profile” combat air movements, including the U.S. Secretaries of State and Defense, U.S. Ambassador\nto Iraq, and various members of the Iraqi Parliament.\nTheater Level Aviation Operations Officer \tCoalition Forces Land Component Command\n§ Responsible for managing, coordinating and directing U.S. and Coalition aviation operations in the U.S. Central\nCommand Area of responsibility, including assembling and managing detailed information on combat and support\naircraft force flow into and out of the Iraqi theater for 8 Army divisions and several international units.\n§ Individually provided daily briefings to the Commanding General and other general staff officers around the world.\nMILITARY CAREER HIGHLIGHTS\n§ Deployed twice in support of Operation Iraqi Freedom, accumulating over 495 flight hours with over 215 combat\nflight hours.\n§ Honored with numerous commendations including:\n§ Army Aviator Badge \t§ Air Medal \t§ Joint Service Commendation Medal\n§ Parachutist Badge \t§ Army Commendation Medal\nwith Oak Leaf Cluster\n§ Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary Medal\nPERSONAL INTERESTS\n§ Married with three children\n§ Member:\n§ West Point Society\nof Dallas Fort Worth\n§ Army Aviation Association\nof America\n§ West Point Association of Graduates\n§ Texas Bar Association\n§ Interests: family, cooking, aviation, college and professional sports, hunting, and golf\n-- 3 of 9 --\n\nMy teaching philosophy is deeply rooted in the principles of the Thayer Method, which I\nexperienced as a cadet during my time at the United States Military Academy at West Point. Rather\nthan relying solely absorbing class material through lectures, the Thayer Method emphasizes active\nstudent engagement and preparation. Students should come to class having already studied the\nmaterial, ready to engage in meaningful discussions, problem-solving, and the application of\nconcepts. In practice, this fosters an interactive classroom environment where students take\nownership of their learning, while the instructor acts as a guide to deepen understanding and refine\ncritical thinking skills.\nThe Thayer Method is particularly well-suited for law students, where the ability to analyze\ncomplex issues, synthesize diverse perspectives, and communicate effectively are paramount. By\nintegrating this philosophy, I would aim to create a classroom dynamic mirroring real-world\nchallenges faced by legal practitioners, and requiring students to think on their feet, articulate their\nreasoning, and adapt to evolving scenarios.\nMy professional background further molds my teaching approach. Having served two combat tours\nin Operation Iraqi Freedom in both leadership and support roles, I have a profound appreciation\nfor the necessity of clear and effective communication across diverse audiences. In my military\nroles, I worked closely with individuals of varying ranks, from Privates to Major Generals, honing\nmy ability to convey complex information in accessible and actionable ways. This skill translates\ndirectly into the classroom, where I strive to make legal concepts understandable and relevant to\nstudents from all backgrounds.\nAdditionally, my experience in the private legal sector—both as in-house and outside counsel—\nprovides a broad foundation of practical knowledge to draw upon. This breadth allows me to enrich\nclassroom discussions with real-world examples and ensure that students grasp not only theoretical\nprinciples but also their practical applications.\nMy primary interest lies in teaching a course on military law and ethics. This subject combines my\nprofessional experiences and academic interests, offering students a unique perspective on the\nintersection of law, leadership, and ethical decision-making. However, I would also welcome\ncontributing to other areas of the Texas A&M curriculum as needed.\n-- 4 of 9 --\n\nProfessional References:\nTroy McQuagge\nPresident, USHEALTH Group, Inc.\n300 Burnett St # 200, Fort Worth, TX 76102\n(817) 878-3300\nDavid Drez\nWick Phillips Gould and Martin, PLLC\n100 Throckmorton Street, Suite 1500\nFort Worth, Texas 76102\n(817) 332-7788\nBrant Martin\nWick Phillips Gould and Martin, PLLC\n100 Throckmorton Street, Suite 1500\nFort Worth, Texas 76102\n(817) 332-7788\n-- 5 of 9 --\n\nApplication Forms\nFoster Child Form\nFoster Child\nI was not a foster child\n-- 6 of 9 --\n\nVeteran Status/Identification Form\nVoluntary Self-Identification of Veteran Status\nI identify as an active duty wartime or campaign badge veteran\nSurviving Spouse of a Veteran\nI am not a surviving spouse of a veteran\nOrphan of a Veteran\nI am not an orphan of a vet