ons and legislative enactments, for newsletter circulated to legislatures, administrative agencies\nand law firms. Researched and revised drafts of legislation and regulations relating to disability law.\n-- 2 of 9 --\n\nK IMBERLY F. RICH\n_____________________________________________________________________________________\nLEGAL EXPERIENCE, cont'd\nSuperior Court of California, The Honorable James McIntyre \tSan Diego, California\nJudicial Clerk (1994)\nResearched and evaluated briefs submitted to Superior Court Judge McIntyre for criminal and civil\nproceedings. \tPrepared bench memoranda and recommendations for pending cases and motions.\nAttended all court proceedings and meetings in chambers.\nTask Force on Human Subject Experimentation \tBoston, Massachusetts\nLegal Research Assistant (1994)\nInvestigated and researched alleged radiation experiments on child victims in Massachusetts.\nComposed historical analysis of legal relationship created by state ward. Analysis presented verbatim\nto U.S. Congress in report submitted by Task Force.\nMaryland Circuit Court, Baltimore County Clerk Division \tBaltimore, Maryland\nIntern (1992)\nObserved and documented civil and criminal court proceedings. Assisted court clerks and judicial\nresearch clerks by preparing and processing court files.\nDepartment of Justice, Immigration & Naturalization Service \tBaltimore, Maryland\nIntern (1991)\nAssisted attorneys in preparation of asylum cases through research of claims made by applicants.\nInvestigated political and social situations in countries of origin to determine applicants’ eligibility for\nrefuge and asylum.\nPROFESSIONAL MEMBERSHIPS & FIRM COMMITTEES\n \tBaker McKenzie Inclusion, Diversity and Equity Committee: Committee Member (2015 to\npresent)\n \tBaker McKenzie Recruiting Committee: Former Hiring Partner (2005 to 2012) & Recruiting\nCommittee Member (2001 to present)\n \tBaker McKenzie Pro Bono Program: Pro Bono counsel (1999 to present)\n \tAmerican Bar Association: Vice-Chair of Trade Secrets Committee (2015 to 2020); Member of\nLitigation & Intellectual Property Sections (2001 to 2020)\n \tLaw360 Hospitality: Editorial Advisory Committee Member (2012 to 2020)\nCOMMUNITY ACTIVITIES\n \tFor the Love of the Lake: Regular Volunteer (2012 to present)\n \tSalvation Army: Regular Volunteer & Donor (1999 to present)\n \tFeed My Starving Children: Regular Volunteer & Donor (2012 to present)\n \tVNA Meals on Wheels: Regular Volunteer (2010 to present)\n \tBoy Scouts of America: Cub Scout Den Leader (2011 to 2018); Troop Community Service\nCoordinator (2018 to 2022); Merit Badge Counselor (2015 to 2022)\n \tGirl Scouts: Troop Volunteer & Former Treasurer (2010 to 2022)\n \tSPCA: Regular Volunteer (2017 to 2020)\n \tNational Charity League: Member & Regular Volunteer (2016 to 2022)\n-- 3 of 9 --\n\n1\nKIMBERLY F. RICH\n14037 Brookcrest Drive, Dallas, Texas 75240\nEmail: kimberlyfrich@icloud.com Mobile: 214 632 2595\nAugust 29, 2023\nRe: \tApplication for Adjunct Law School Professor\nI am writing to apply for the open position of Adjunct Law School Professor. As a Partner at Baker McKenzie with\n27 years of business advising and litigation experience, I developed extensive knowledge, diverse and global\nexperience and unique skills that pair ideally with the job functions as an Adjunct Professor. \tI possess the\nknowledge and skill set you are looking for based on my experience with Baker McKenzie, as well as serving on\nthe Board of Trustees and Executive Committee of a non-profit educational institution and chairing its Risk\nManagement Committee. My curriculum vitae is submitted separately.\nI offer a strong track record of success to demonstrate that I possess the requisite expertise that would enable me to\nbecome an impactful strategic instructor and advisor. I am particularly interested in courses based on first year core\ncurriculum (especially Civil Procedure, Torts, Contracts and Legal Writing) and courses 