TIGATION\n• \tRepresent companies in litigation and at trial, in both state and federal\ncourts, and before arbitration tribunals, including class-action and multidis-\ntrict litigation, related to antitrust, commodities, consumer-protection, con-\ntract, partnership, products-liability, and securities disputes.\n• \tRepresent companies in litigated proceedings in and related to chapter 11\nbankruptcy cases in the automotive, aerospace, chemical, commercial\nreal-estate, environmental, financial-services, and power-generation in-\ndustries.\n• \tSubject-matter expertise in litigation involving securities and derivative fi-\nnancial instruments, the Bankruptcy Code, the Commodity Exchange Act,\nthe Delaware General Corporation Law, the Delaware Limited Liability\nCompany Act, the Federal Arbitration Act, the General Data Protection Reg-\nulation (and several member-state data-protection laws), the Hague evidence\nconvention, the Securities Act of 1933 and the Securities Exchange Act of\n1934, the Texas Citizens Participation Act, and several states’ versions of\nthe Uniform Commercial Code, Uniform Fraudulent Transfer Act, and Uni-\nform Interstate Depositions and Discovery Act.\n• \tGOVERNMENT-ENFORCEMENT DEFENSE & INTERNAL INVESTIGATIONS\n• \tRepresent audit committees, boards of directors, companies, and individuals\nin government-enforcement and parallel proceedings involving alleged vio-\nlations of anticorruption, antitrust, commodities, consumer-protection, con-\ntracting, financial-fraud, and securities laws in the aerospace, automotive,\ndefense, engineering, environmental, financial-services, healthcare, petro-\nleum, and telecommunications industries.\n-- 3 of 14 --\n\n2\n• \tConduct internal investigations on behalf of corporate stakeholders, includ-\ning investigations with overseas components.\n• \tRespond to inquiries from primary regulators.\n• \tNegotiate civil and criminal dispositions of enforcement proceedings and\nadvise clients on settlement strategies and ramifications.\n• \tSubject-matter expertise in the federal bank-fraud and wire-fraud statutes,\nthe Bank Secrecy Act, the Commodity Exchange Act, the Foreign Corrupt\nPractices Act, the General Data Protection Regulation (and several mem-\nber-state data-protection laws), federal marijuana-related enforcement reg-\nulations, sanctions, the Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002, the Securities Act of\n1933 and the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, the United States Sentenc-\ning Guidelines, and the Travel Act.\n• \tELECTRONIC DISCOVERY, RECORDS MANAGEMENT, AND EVIDENCE GATHER-\nING\n• \tAs the counsel managing Skadden’s Electronic Discovery Committee, edit\nSkadden’s Electronic Discovery Manual; draft model discovery and protec-\ntive orders and review protocols; assess compliance with data-protection and\nstate-secrecy laws; and assess technology-assisted-review solutions.\n• \tAssess preservation and harvesting obligations in civil litigation and govern-\nment-enforcement proceedings considering the nature of the potential liabil-\nity, available resources, and file types and locations.\n• \tFormulate strategy and manage efforts to preserve, harvest, review, and pro-\nduce documents, including calculating and managing projections for time\nand cost.\n• \tAddress cross-border evidence gathering and resolve conflicts of law involv-\ning data-protection and state-secrecy laws.\n• \tFormulate time and budget estimates for evidence gathering and review; as-\nsess review tools for particular cases; train and manage review teams.\n• \tREGULATORY COMPLIANCE\n• \tDevise and assess corporate compliance programs in the aerospace, apparel,\nasset-management, automotive, beverage, energy, environmental,\nhealthcare, mining, publishing, technology, and tobacco industries. Draft\n-- 4 of 14 --\n\n3\ncodes, policies, procedures, and contract compliance provisions. Advise\ncompanies on structuring and staffing compliance programs.\n• \tAssess regulatory compliance in operations and provide advice regarding\nconduct.\n• \tAddress regulatory-compliance issues in connection with mergers, acquisi-\ntions, and corporate-financing transactions in the consumer-products, elec-\ntronics, financial-services, healthcare, mining, and technology industries.\nREPRESENTATIVE MATTERS\n• \tCOMPLEX CIVIL LITIGATION\n• \tRepresented financial-services company in class-action litigation related\nto benchmarks for derivative financial instruments following government-\nenforcement proceedings. Obtained dismissal of Commodity Exchange\nAct claims.\n• \tRepresented Canada-based financial institution in contract litigation against\na U.S.-based hedge fund regarding a loan securitized in part by the pro-\nceeds of single-name credit-default swaps. Case is ongoing.\n• \tObtained summary judgment for a real-estate investment trust in a $22 mil-\nlion fraud and fiduciary-duty suit against its broker.\n• \tRepresented contract market and clearing organization in administrative-re-\nview litigation against the Commodity Futures Exchange Commission re-\nlated to Dodd–Frank rulemaking. Obtained favorable settlement with the\nCFTC whereby the CFTC agreed not to enforce its guidance.\n• \tRepresented Swiss financial institution in a litigated bankruptcy-court ad-\nversary proceeding against debtors and the official committee of unsecured\ncreditors in jointly administered cases. Managed a team of 10+ attorneys.\nDeveloped litigation strategy; prepared key witnesses, drafted pretrial, post-\ntrial, and appellate briefs; and argued motions at trial. Obtained favorable\npost-judgment settlement and favorable plan treatment.\n• \tRepresented registered investment adviser in litigation against former mem-\nbers of investment adviser in related proceedings in multiple courts. Ad-\ndressed issues related to derivative claims under Delaware law and arbitra-\nbility. Cases settled on favorable terms.\n-- 5 of 14 --\n\n4\n• \tGOVERNMENT-ENFORCEMENT DEFENSE & INTERNAL INVESTIGATIONS\n• \tRepresented United Kingdom-based swap dealer in parallel price-manipula-\ntion investigations by the CFTC and the Department of Justice, and a follow-\non investigation by the Financial Industry Regulatory Authority, related to\nthe benchmark for valuing cash-settled interest-rate swap options. Managed\na team of 25+ attorneys. Developed a novel argument that section 2(d) of\nthe CEA so completely excluded the type of swap options the CFTC was in-\nvestigating that the CFTC was not entitled to Chevron deference to deter-\nmine the CEA’s applicability and that a challenge to the CFTC’s jurisdiction\nto bring an enforcement proceeding need not be brought through the CEA’s\nusual administrative-review provisions. Obtained declinations of enforce-\nment from the DOJ and from FINRA. Obtained a favorable settlement with\nthe CFTC whose civil monetary penalty was the lowest penalty paid to date\nby any institution involved in the CFTC’s investigations into the benchmark.\n• \tRepresented Russian telecommunications company in parallel Foreign Cor-\nrupt Practices Act investigations by the DOJ and the Securities and Ex-\nchange Commission related to conduct in Asia. Developed novel argument\nagainst enforcement on the ground that the FCPA could not be applied to\nthe conduct under the Charming Betsy canon and the objective territorial\nprinciple of jurisdiction of customary international law. Developed a prin-\ncipled framework proposal for resolving the case based on the alternative-\nfines statute, the U.S. Sentencing Guidelines, and the Supreme Court’s de-\ncision in Kokesh v. SEC. Obtained favorable settlement with the DOJ and\nthe SEC that met the client’s strategic objectives.\n• \tRepresented German automaker in parallel FCPA investigations by the DOJ\nand the SEC related to conduct in Africa, Asia, Europe, and North and\nSouth America. Managed a team of 75+ attorneys from numerous locations\nin the United States, Europe, and Asia. Trained non-U.S. attorneys in con-\nducting a U.S.-style investigation. Addressed conflicts of laws, including\ndata-protection, blocking, and labor laws. Obtained favorable settlement\nwith the DOJ and the SEC that met the client’s strategic objectives and per-\nmitted it to move forward with significant transactions.\n• \tRepresented U.S.-based medical-devices manufacturer in parallel FCPA in-\nvestigations by the DOJ and the SEC related to conduct in Asia, Europe,\nand Central America. Managed a team of 15+ attorneys. Addressed con-\nflicts of laws, including data-protection and blocking laws. Obtained favor-\nable settlement with the DOJ and the SEC.\n-- 6 of 14 --\n\n5\n• \tConducted internal investigation of medical-devices company related to\nallegations of earnings management. Reported findings to the Board of\nDirectors, which resolved to prohibit certain sales practices.\n• \tConducted internal investigation of tactical-communications company re-\nlated to allegations of misuse of corporate assets by a senior executive. Re-\nported findings to the Board of Directors, which resolved to discipline the\nsenior executive.\n• \tConducted internal investigation on behalf of mining company related to\nconduct in China. Reported findings to the Board of Directors, which re-\nsolved to terminate these activities in China.\n• \tREGULATORY COMPLIANCE\n• \tAdvised a publishing company on restructuring and staffing its compli-\nance function in advance of a strategic transaction, including designing a\nnew code of conduct and ethics, and relevant policies and procedures.\n• \tAssessed global compliance program and multiple business-unit compli-\nance functions at a financial-technology company and money services\nbusiness, particularly related to anticorruption, antitrust, gifts and enter-\ntainment, political and charitable contributions, and sanctions.\n• \tConducted legal-compliance due diligence in multiple acquisitions for a\ndiversified technology company, including reviewing target compliance\nprograms; interviewing personnel; and drafting and negotiating represen-\ntations, covenants, and related provisions.\nSELECTED WRITINGS/PUBLICATIONS\n• \tThe Challenges for CEA Price Manipulation Plaintiffs, Law360, April 2017\n• \tU.S.A. chapter of The International Comparative Legal Guide to Busi-\nness Crime 2017, Global Legal Group, October 2016\n• \tCFTC Aims To Lower the Bar on Proving Manipulation in Pending Cases,\nWestlaw Journal, July 2016\n• \tU.S.A.—Washington, DC, chapter of The International Comparative Legal\nGuide to Litigation and Dispute Resolution 2014, Global Legal Group, Febru-\nary 2014\n-- 7 of 14 --\n\n6\n• \tChapter X of Crisis Management in Litigation and Investigations: Parallel\nProceedings, Competing Stakeholders, and Multiple Venues, Association of\nCorporate Counsel, August 2008\n• \tParallel Proceedings Complicate Crisis Management: Tradeoffs Inevitable, Ex-\necutive Counsel, March/April 2007\nPUBLIC SPEAKING AND ATTORNEY EDUCATION\n• \tRegularly present to litigation practice groups on best practices for gathering\nevidence overseas, including complying with data-protection laws.\n• \tRegularly present to firm lawyers and in-house counsel on best practices for\nmanaging all stages of electronic discovery.\n• \tRegularly present to firm lawyers and in-house counsel on practical applica-\ntions of the attorney-client privilege and the work-product doctrine.\n• \tFrequent CLE presenter on Foreign Corrupt Practices Act and on conducting\ninternal investigations.\n• \tRegularly present to firm lawyers and in-house counsel on alternative litigation\nfinance.\n• \tRegularly present to firm lawyers on swaps and swap options, and related mar-\nkets.\n• \tRegularly present to firm lawyers on conducting regulatory-compliance due dili-\ngence in mergers, acquisitions, and corporate-financing transactions.\n-- 8 of 14 --\n\nGary A. Rubin\n4133 Southwestern Blvd.\nDallas, TX 75225\nJanuary 2, 2024\nRe: \tAcademic Professional Track (Non-Tenure): Adjunct Pro-\nfessor of Law position\nBy electronic submission\nTexas A&M University School of Law\n1515 Commerce Street\nFort Worth, TX 76102-6509\nLadies and Gentlemen:\nI write to respond to your hiring announcement, Academic Professional Track\n(Non-Tenure): Adjunct Professor of Law. I currently am a member and general\ncounsel of WTAII PLLC, a DC-based boutique law firm that focuses on regulatory-\ncompliance matters, internal investigations, and related litigation and transactions.\nFor more than 20 years, my law practice has focused on regulatory compli-\nance and ethics in the business setting. I have significant experience counseling cli-\nents on compliance with laws, regulations, guidance, and business-ethics standards\nacross numerous jurisdictions. This includes providing training to client accounting,\nlegal, and sales teams, providing advice to in-house attorneys and compliance offic-\ners on prospective conduct, and drafting codes of ethics, policies, and procedures. I\nalso have assisted clients in establishing their compliance organizations out of whole\ncloth, including providing advice on structuring and staffing the compliance func-\ntion, assessing risk, and assessing gaps between clients’ day-to-day operations and\nbest practices from guidance from numerous regulatory authorities.\nDespite my hiatus in legal practice (including nearly two decades at one of\nthe largest law firms in the world and nearly a half decade owning my own boutique\nfirm), teaching has been my first love since my high school allowed to me to return\nafter graduation to teach a mini semester to seniors on the emancipation of the Jews\nin Europe and the rise of Zionism from 1648. Years later, my decision to leave grad-\nuate school for law school was a close one. Even throughout my career at law firms,\nthe time I loved best was spent developing and mentoring young lawyers and train-\ning clients. I have taught courses to lawyers and finance professionals on regulatory\n-- 9 of 14 --\n\nTexas A&M University School of Law\nJanuary 2, 2024\nPage 2\ncompliance, compliance due diligence in mergers and acquisitions, protecting privi-\nlege in the corporate setting, electronic discovery, cross-border evidence gathering,\ntaking and defending depositions, understanding SEC filings, alternative litigation\nfinance, and interest-rate swaps and options markets. I now seek an opportunity to\ncome full circle and return to academia.\nMy research interests center on regulatory overreach in the context of general\ncorporate compliance. In particular, my professional practice has led me to question\nhow prosecutorial and regulatory agencies increasingly seek to circumscribe conduct\nusing methods that are less than final agency actions, or civil or criminal enforce-\nment proceedings, and the negative effects this conduct has on the predictive quality\nof statutes, regulations, and case law. This lack of predictability especially affects\ncompliance professionals. To illustrate by just one example: a compliance profes-\nsional seeking to understand enforcement risk respecting only the Justice Depart-\nment, as of March 2023, should be familiar with (at least): the memorandum from\nDeputy Attorney General Lisa Monaco entitled, Corporate Crime Advisory Group\nand Initial Revisions to Corporate Criminal Enforcement Policies (Oct. 28, 2021);\nthe memorandum from Deputy Attorney General Monaco entitled, Further Revisions\nto Corporate Criminal Enforcement Policies following Discussions with Corporate\nCrime Advisory Group (Sept. 15, 2022); the Criminal Division’s Corporate Enforce-\nment and Voluntary Self-Disclosure Policy (updated Jan. 2023); Assistant Attorney\nGeneral Kenneth Polite, Jr.’s, Remarks on Revisions to the Criminal Division’s Cor-\nporate Enforcement Policy (Jan. 17, 2023); the Criminal Division’s guidance enti-\ntled, Evaluation of Corporate Compliance Programs (updated Mar. 2023); the Crim-\ninal Division’s Pilot Program Regarding Com