96	124	smith_eric_5791984.pdf	\N	\n-- 1 of 11 --\n\nEric P. Smith JD\n2483 Raven Hollow Road Page 1of1\nState College, PA 16801\nCell: (814) 876-0318\nEmail:ericpsmith14@gmail.com\nEDUCATION\nThe Pennsylvania State University, University Park, PA\nBA, Political Science, 1971\nWidener University School of Law, Wilmington, Delaware\nJuris Doctor Degree, 1976\nLICENSURE/CERTIFICATION\no Admitted to the Bar of the Supreme Court of Pennsylvania and the Bar of the\nUnited States District Court for the Middle District of Pennsylvania,1976.\n.Licenses retired administratively at my request.\no Certificates in teaching online, classroom management, and use of\ncomputerized learning and research-- issued by the South Hills School of\nBusiness and Technology, State College, PA and Penn State University.\nPROFESSIONAL EXPERIENCE\n- Law Clerk in prominent Delaware Corporate Law firm while attending Law\nSchool Evening Division.\n- Private Law Practice with a focus on Business, Commercial, Bankruptcy, and\nReal Estate Law. Commercial Creditor representation in Federal Bankruptcy\nCourt proceedings. Gained working knowledge of the Uniform Commercial\nCode, Bankruptcy, and Creditors Rights law.\nACADEMIC POSITIONS HELD\nAdjunct Faculty Member\n• The Pennsylvania State University, Smeal College of Business\n2016-2023 Teach Advanced Uniform Commercial\nCode (UCC) to fifth year students in the Master’s In Accounting Program.\nIn-depth coverage of Sales, Leases, Negotiable Instruments, Secured\nTransactions, Banking, Creditors Rights and Bankruptcy.\n• The Pennsylvania State University, Continuing Education 1996-2014.\nProvide instruction in various Business and Commercial Law courses for\nReturning Adult Learners and four-year track Undergraduate Students. Topics\nincluded Torts, Contracts, Agency, Bankruptcy, Creditors Rights, Real Property,\nand Commercial Law.\n-- 2 of 11 --\n\nPage 2 of 2\n-- 3 of 11 --\n\nTeaching Statement\nIt has been the central theme in all of my courses: the Law, and\nthe Judicial System that interprets and enforces the Law is not\nsome inanimate object. The Law is living and breathing, and\nadaptable to change as new issues and disputes arise between\nparties that may not have been previously addressed by Courts\nand Legislative bodies. For example, in my Uniform Commercial\nCode class, I want each student to see that the UCC and the\nrules it sets forth have been devised over the years to adapt to\nchanges in how we do business with each other, and to resolve\nnew legal issues not previously addressed that have arisen from\nnew ways of doing business. My main goal in any law course I\nhave taught has been to convey to my students not just bare legal\nrules, but to teach them to learn law by also learning the rationale\nbehind each rule.\nWhen I began teaching I simply conveyed information. As a result,\nmy students became bored. I learned to make my students’\nengagement more interactive. I decreased actual lecture time and\nincreased my students’ hands-on participation, for example,\nthrough written case analysis relating to the material being\npresented at any given time. I decreased the frequency of exams.\nAs long as I achieved my major course objectives I felt less\npressure to adhere strictly to the “pace” I set for myself through\nmy syllabus outline.\nBy increasing my students’ interactivity I found that students feel\nmore invested in the process. Grading written assignments\nincreases time I spend outside of class on a given course.\n-- 4 of 11 --\n\nHowever, I have found that my own level of personal satisfaction\nas a teacher has greatly increased.\nEric P. Smith\n-- 5 of 11 --\n\nEric Smith References\nSteven J. Huddart\nSmeal Chair Professor of Accounting\nSenior Associate Dean for Research & Faculty\nPenn State Smeal College of Business\n210E Business Building\nUniversity Park, PA 16802\nPh. 814-865-3271\nsjh11@psu.edu\nScott Collins\nAccounting Dept.\nPenn State Smeal College of Business\nDirector, On