97	125	soileau_alida_5661287.pdf	\N	Alida B. Soileau\nCurrently based in Montrose, Colorado\n(318) 423-6052 \t• \talida.soileau@gmail.com\nJanuary 6, 2024\nTexas A&M University School of Law\n1515 Commerce Street\nFort Worth, TX 76102\nRe: Non-Tenure: Adjunct Professor of Law\nTo whom it may concern:\nI am writing to apply for a Non-Tenure: Adjunct Professor of Law position at the School of\nLaw. Presently, I am a Deputy Public Defender serving indigent criminal defendants in rural\nColorado. In addition to my time as a practicing attorney, I have teaching experience and one\npublished law review article under my belt. I look forward to making meaningful contributions to\nstudents’ learning, Texas A&M University School of Law, and the legal community more broadly.\nWriting and teaching have long been my strong suits. As a Deputy Public Defender, I write\neverything from pre-trial motions to appeal briefs. My legal writing is stronger than that of many\ntrial attorneys because I honed my skills in law school. I have long been a writer, but legal writing is\npithy and structured in ways that are very different from the liberal arts writing of undergrad. I\nfound legal writing challenging and frustrating at first. However, my legal writing professor paid\nscrupulous attention to each assignment I submitted and pushed me to keep going. Over time, I got\nthe hang of things. In a teaching role, I look forward to pushing my students to keep improving\nupon their work. That positive push—that encouragement—is, in my opinion, critical to student\nsuccess. It was critical to my own.\nDuring my second year of school, I also had the privilege of working with my 1L\nConstitutional Law professor as a teaching assistant. I reviewed key concepts and cases from the\nprevious week’s lectures, fielded questions, and walked through practice questions with my\nstudents—now my attorney peers—who were just one year behind me. My proximity to the\nstudents’ (often difficult) experiences navigating doctrinal materials and 1L year made me a\nparticularly effective student teacher. During my final year of school, that same Constitutional Law\nprofessor mentored me through the process of submitting a law review article for publication. I was\nthrilled that the South Carolina Law Review accepted my article, and I enjoyed working with the\neditors there to improve upon it before publication.\nI would welcome the opportunity to speak with you further about my interest in joining\nTexas A&M University School of Law as an Adjunct Professor of Law. Thank you for your\nconsideration.\nSincerely,\nAlida B. Soileau\n-- 1 of 12 --\n\nAlida B. Soileau\nCurrently based in Montrose, Colorado\n(318) 423-6052 \t• \talida.soileau@gmail.com\nExperience\nColorado State Public Defender \tMay 2023-Present\nDeputy State Public Defender\n• \tDevelop litigation and trial strategies. Represent clients at hearings and trials.\n• \tLitigate issues including suppression of evidence, compelling information, violations of\nmandatory discovery rules, failure to preserve evidence, limitations on restitution, and\ncompetency to proceed.\n• \tNegotiate proposed disposition of cases (plea agreements); compile and present\nmitigation information.\n• \tMeet and communicate regularly with clients about their cases. Advocate tirelessly for\nclients, bearing witness to their lived experiences.\n• \tIdentify avenues of investigation. Review records, conduct interviews, document new\nevidence, and more.\n• \tGuide clients through the criminal justice system, from initial contact with law\nenforcement to trial.\n•\nOtten Johnson Robinson Neff + Ragonetti PC \tSep. 2022 – Apr. 2023\nAttorney – Real Estate & Land Use\n• \tLand use matters including entitlements, zonings, and annexations.\n• \tTransactional matters including development agreements and purchase & sale\nagreements.\n• \tCollaborative matters including negotiating a community benefits agreement.\nUniversity of Denver, Sturm College of