 property law and human remains as historical\nartifacts. I paid particular attention to disparate, state-level rules and argued in favor of a more\nunified approach to the disposition of human remains. Further, my work set forth concerns related\nto whose history our property law schemes favor protecting.\nI am not presently engaged in research beyond the day-to-day research requisite to my role\nas a Deputy Public Defender.\nFuture Research Directions\nI favor an interdisciplinary approach to my work. More perspectives almost always lead to\nstronger conclusions. My interests lie in the at the intersection of history, environmental\nconsiderations, and the meaning of “justice,” with special attention to the institutions shaping the\nterrain. I look forward to developing my research objectives with the help of colleagues and\nstudents.\nTeaching\nCourses I am interested in and qualified to teach include (but are not limited to)\nConstitutional Law, Criminal Law, Criminal Procedure, Criminal Procedure Trial Rights, Evidence,\nProfessional Responsibility, Property, Property Law and Transactions, and Legal Research for\nClients.\nMy teaching philosophy holds: “Encouragement is everything.” Gone are the days when law\nschool enrollment numbers plummeted after the first semester. With that in mind, I do not know\none lawyer, regardless of law school rank, who found the endeavor to be easy. The fact that a\nstudent is sitting in my class in the first place tells me all I need to know about their ability to\nsucceed academically. It is my job to effectively instill doctrinal law, but it is also my job to instill a\nsense of resiliency in each student.\n-- 7 of 12 --\n\nAlida B. Soileau\nCurrently based in Montrose, Colorado\n(318) 423-6052 \t• \talida.soileau@gmail.com\nReferences\nProfessor Nancy Leong\n303-871-6092 (office)\n650-814-9418 (cell)\nnleong@law.du.edu\nAlex Haggarty, Esq.\n720-673-9192 (office)\n802-558-2414 (cell)\naahaggarty@gmail.com\nBrooke Donnelly, Esq