99	127	steele_jesse_5769378.pdf	\N	JESSE D. STEELE\n8623 Ellenwood Estates Dr. • Montague, MI 49437 • 231.563.1728 • jesse.d.steele@gmail.com\nMarch 6, 2025\nDear Jennifer Merrywell,\nI am writing to express interest in teaching an online class in an adjunct capacity at Texas A&M\nUniversity Law School. \tI am a practicing corporate attorney who has been impacted greatly by\npractitioner-professors during my own education, and I desire to make the same investment in today's\nstudents.\nIn my legal practice, I draft and negotiate all sales and marketing contracts for an electric vehicle\ncompany (Lucid Motors) headquartered in Silicon Valley, California. Additionally, I have studied many\ndifferent fields at the graduate level, including law, business, alternative dispute resolution, and public\npolicy, and I greatly enjoyed the opportunity to co-teach a business law class at Rutgers School of Law\nmany years ago.\nWhile I am open to discussing any particular class needs you may have, based on my current\npractice and academic background, I believe I would be well-suited to teach a class in any of the following\nareas:\n• \tBusiness Law\n• \tContract Law\n• \tNegotiation (Strategy & Practice)\nI would greatly appreciate an opportunity to speak with you. Thank you for your consideration,\nand I look forward to hearing from you soon.\nSincerely,\nJesse D. Steele\n-- 1 of 9 --\n\nJESSE D. STEELE\n8623 Ellenwood Estates Dr. • Montague, MI 49437 • 231.563.1728 • jesse.d.steele@gmail.com\nOBJECTIVE\n• Practicing corporate attorney, having been impacted greatly by practitioner-professors during my own\neducation, seeking to teach an undergraduate evening course in law, business, negotiation, public policy, or\nlogic in a college or university that encourages critical thinking.\nTEACHING EXPERIENCE\nRutgers University – School of Law \tNewark, NJ\nClass: Corporate Reorganization (Co-Lecturer) \tSpring 2010\nWORK EXPERIENCE\nLucid Motors \tNewark, CA\nManaging Counsel - Sales, Marketing, and Advertising \tFebruary 2024 – Present\n• Strategically advise C-suite regarding emerging electric vehicle market, often in undeveloped areas of law.\n• Lead contracting and negotiations for all North America sales, marketing, and advertising transactions.\n• Draft and negotiate numerous other complex commercial contracts, including multinational purchasing,\nsponsorship, licensing, and professional services agreements.\nMercedes-Benz USA \tAtlanta, GA\nCorporate Counsel - Commercial Affairs \tApril 2019 – February 2024\n• Draft and negotiate a wide variety of complex corporate, purchasing, marketing, and sponsorship transaction\ndocuments, including master purchase agreements, sales and licensing agreements, supply agreements,\nprofessional services agreements, confidentiality agreements, etc.\n• Advise executive management on contract interpretation and dispute mitigation; manage pre-litigation\ncontractual disputes; provide policy recommendations.\nKemira \tAtlanta, GA\nCorporate Counsel - North America \tJanuary 2015 – March 2019\n• Lead contracting and negotiations and for all North America sourcing, procurement, and capital expenditure\n(CapEx) projects (with annual expenditures over $200 million).\n• Draft and negotiate a wide variety of complex corporate, sales, construction, real estate, R&D, and finance\ntransaction documents.\n• Serve as principal Ethics & Compliance representative for North America, advising management board on\npolicies, presenting to local site management across region, and investigating violations.\nGreenberg Traurig, LLP \tAtlanta, GA\nAssociate Attorney \tMay 2014 – January 2015\n• Draft and negotiate corporate and finance transaction documents, including credit agreements, asset purchase\nagreements, security agreements, service agreements, guarantees, subordination agreements and leases.\n• Manage junior associates and deal timelines; prioritize numerous projects to achieve business objectives.\nKing & Spalding LLP \tAtlanta, GA\nAssociate Attorney \tMay 2011 – May 2014\n• Draft and negotiate transaction documents for syndicated credit facilities, including credit agreements, security\nagreements, guarantees, pledges, certificates, engagement and fee letters, legal opinions, leases and mortgages.\n• Review corporate organizational documents and transaction documents, including asset purchase agreements,\nsupply agreements, licensing agreements, service agreements and employment agreements.\nBracewell & Giuliani LLP \tNew York, NY & Hartford, CT\nAssociate Attorney \tSeptember 2009 – May 2011\n• Draft and review finance transaction documents and corporate organizational documents.\n• Draft first day motions in Chapter 11 cases and bankruptcy related memoranda addressing legal issues raised\nby clients regarding executory contracts, reasonably equivalent value, critical vendors, etc.\n-- 2 of 9 --\n\nEDUCATION\nColumbia University – School of International and Public Affairs \tNew York, NY\nMaster of Public Administration (MPA) \tMay 2013\nConcentration: \tInternational Finance & Economic Policy\nJournal: \tSIPA Journal of International Affairs – Assistant Editor\nUniversity of London – University College London & Queen Mary \tLondon, England\nMaster of Laws (LLM) \tMay 2012\nConcentration: \tInternational Business Law\nHonors: \tDiploma “with merit” distinction\nPepperdine University – School of Law \tMalibu, CA\nPepperdine University – Graduate School of Business & Management \tMay 2009\nPepperdine University – Straus Institute for Dispute Resolution\nJuris Doctor (JD) / Master of Business Administration (MBA) / Master of Dispute Resolution (MDR)\n• JD: \tHonors: \tJD/MBA Scholarship; Research Assistant to Dean Kenneth W. Starr\nJournal: \tManaging Editor – Pepperdine Dispute Resolution Law Journal\nCALI Award: \tInternational Trade (98% – Top Grade in Class)\n• MBA: \tHonors: \tLos Angeles Chamber of Commerce – World Trade Week Award\n• MDR: \tHonors: \tChina Dispute Resolut