ws me to\ndistill difficult legal principles into clear and digestible lessons that are understandable by students that\nhave varying levels of familiarity with the topics. When designing an asynchronous course, I will develop\nstructured content—via recorded lectures and cases studies—that is systematic and thorough, yet allows\nroom for students to wrestle with complex real-world scenarios.\nI believe that effective online education requires more than simply ingesting content. It also\nrequires intentional connection and adaptability. To this end, I will use a philosophy of teaching that\nemphasizes active learning, despite being in a separate environment. For example, I will integrate tools\nsuch as discussion boards and personalized feedback to engage students personally and directly. I will\nalso host regular virtual office hours to engage with the students who desire real-time interaction. These\napproaches also foster accessibility and inclusion, as students with varying work schedules or those who\nlive in different time zones are all able to participate. My goal is to ensure that students feel supported and\nmotivated as they engage with the material on their own schedules.\nI am eager to contribute to Texas A&M University Law School and to provide exceptional legal\neducation by teaching an asynchronous online course that is intellectually engaging, widely accessible,\nand deeply supportive. I look forward to inspiring the next generation of legal professionals to think\ncritically and adhere to the principles of justice—all via a format that fits within their already busy lives.\n-- 4 of 9 --\n\nJESSE D. STEELE\n8623 Ellenwood Estates Dr. • Montague, MI 49437 • 231.563.1728 • jesse.d.steele@gmail.com\nREFERENCES\nProfessional\nStacey Mollohan\nGeneral Counsel – Mercedes-Benz USA\nstacey.mollohan@mbusa.com\n470.304.2325\nJennifer Scantling\nAssociate General Counsel – Mercedes-Benz USA\njennifer.scantling@mbusa.com\n202.246.5906\nStephen Juge\nCorporate Co