ory, GPA: 3.912, summa cum laude\n• \tHonored with History Department Merit Scholarship for 2006\nLICENSES AND CERTIFICATIONS\n• \tCertified Information Privacy Professional, US Private Sector August 2021, Canada September 2023 (CIPP/C/US)\n• \tCertified in Healthcare Compliance (CHC), November 2016\n• \tAdmitted to Texas Bar, February 2014\n• \tDomestic and International Commercial Arbitration Certification, August 2012\nSPEAKING ENGAGEMENTS\nHaynes & Boone Crisis Management Academy – Cyber Incident Response \tJan/Feb 2024\n• \tPresented strategies for prevention, communications, maintaining privilege, vendor management and related\ntopics as in-house panelist for 3 sessions in Dallas, Houston and Denver\nRecent Whistleblower Cases: Key Takeaways and Applications \tMarch 2021\n• \tContinuing Legal Education Course at Greater Houston Society for Healthcare Risk Management Education Day\n-- 4 of 11 --\n\nJENNIFER TAVERAS\nJD, CHC, CIPP/C/US\nPERSONAL STATEMENT\nMy teaching philosophy is rooted in the belief that education should be both practical and engaging,\nemphasizing real world applications and critical thinking, and equipping students to excel in their careers\nand be life-long learners.\nPHILOSOPHY AND PLAN FOR TEACHING\nIn my classes, I plan to create an engaging and interactive learning environment where students can\nactively participate and apply knowledge they gain from our discussions and course materials to practical\nscenarios. I believe in the power of experiential learning and will incorporate case studies, simulations,\nand role-playing exercises to help students develop their problem-solving, negotiation and other soft\nskills.\nI would align my class structure to the Texas A&M Law School preferences and needs, but a Privacy\nClass might have the following focus areas:\n1. What is Privacy and Why Does it Matter (1 week)\na. Personal Data and Sensitive Personal Data\nb. Real world privacy issues/case studies/scenarios for discussion and role play\n2. Privacy Laws and Regulations (3 weeks)\na. Key Privacy Laws and Regulations (HIPAA, US State Consumer Privacy Laws,\nGDPR, US CAN-SPAM and TCPA, Canadian PIPEDA and CASL, etc.\nb. Strategies for navigating a complex regulatory landscape\nc. Why are Privacy Laws and Privacy Lawyers important?\nd. Real world compliance issues/case studies/scenarios for discussion and role play\n3. Building a Privacy Compliance Program (3 weeks)\na. Components of an Effective Program, including regulatory expectations and why\nthey matter\nb. Audits and Responding to Regulators\nc. Real world constraints for discussion and role play, including budgets, competing\npriorities, need for business champions, and how to address findings of non-\ncompliance\n4. Privacy by Design (2 weeks)\na. Proactive Privacy Assessments and Data Protection Impact Assessments – what\nthey are and why they matter\nb. Aligning privacy with the product lifecycle\nc. Real world scenarios for discussion and role play\n5. Vendor Due Diligence, Contracting and Management (2 weeks)\na. Vendor Due Diligence and why it matters\nb. Key Contracting Considerations\ni. Privacy and data protection terms required by law\n-- 5 of 11 --\n\nii. Data Use and De-Identification/Anonymization\niii. Data Transfer Considerations\niv. Privacy/Security Indemnification and Limitations of Liability\nc. Vendor Management and Incidents\nd. Real world vendor issues/case studies/scenarios for discussion and role play\n6. Privacy and Security Incidents (2 weeks)\na. Stop the bleed – identification, investigation and remediation\nb. The importance of communication and maintaining privilege\nc. Assessment of applicable laws, notifications, credit monitoring and other\nconsiderations\nd. Learning from the incident and enhancing related controls\ne. Real world incidents/case studies/scenarios for discussion and role play\n7. Mergers and Acquisitions (1 week)\na. Practical privacy considerations when assessing a target\nb. Strategies for addressing the risks in the purchase contract and otherwise\nc. Integration and managing residual risk\nd. Real world acquisition issues/case studies/scenarios for discussion and role play\n8. Data Subject Rights and Ethical Considerations (1 week)\na. Individual rights and related business obligations\nb. Balancing individual privacy with business objectives\nc. Real world issues/case studies/scenarios for discussion and role play\nA Healthcare Compliance class would have a similar structure but the following focus areas:\n1. Healthcare Compliance Overview\n2. Healthcare Compliance Laws, including the Anti-Kickback Statute, the Stark Law, the\nFalse Claims Act, HIPAA, and CMS rules and regulations\n3. Compliance Programs (including DOJ expectations, program components, and practical\nstrategies)\n4. Fraud, Waste and Abuse/Billing and Coding Compliance\n5. Incident Response\n6. Conflicts of Interest\n7. Clinical Documentation\n8. Ethics and Professionalism\nAn AI Law class would have a similar structure but the following focus areas:\n1. Intro to AI (including Gen AI) and why it matters\n2. Applicable Legal Frameworks\n3. Privacy and Data Protection\n4. Bias and Fairness\n5. Liability and Accountability\n6. Safety and Protection of Consumers, Employees, Job Applicants and other Individuals\n7. Intellectual Property\n8. How AI can enhance your legal practice\n-- 6 of 11 --\n\nJENNIFER TAVERAS\nJD, CHC, CIPP/C/US\nPROFESSIONAL CONTACTS\nRichard Kibble\nGlobal Head of Privacy at Alcon\nRichard.Kibble@alcon.com\nRelationship: My boss at Alcon\nLeslie Griffin\nBoyd Professor of Law at UNLV Boyd School of Law\nLeslie.Griffin@unlv.edu\nRelationship: Constitutional Law Professor my 1L year. She also recommended me for the\nHealth Law Research Assistant Position at University of Houston Law School.\nNathan LaComb\nGeneral Counsel at Zeus Company LLC\nnathanlacomb@gmail.com\nRelationship: Former colleague\n-- 7 of 11 --\n\nApplication Forms\nFoster Child Form\nFoster Child\nI was 