101	129	thompson_ashley_5721640.pdf	\N	Re: Adjunct Professor of Law Position\nDear Hiring Committee,\nI am excited to apply for an adjunct professor position at Texas A&M University School of Law. I have a\ndecade of legal experience that includes practicing at the following: Kirkland & Ellis, a late state startup\nreal estate investment company, and a midsize law firm. Translating my experience into coursework will\nallow me to provide my students with a practical real-world understanding of the business of law and the\nimplications of the advice we give - along with a fulsome substantive education. Having worked in some\nof the nation's most fast-paced legal markets - Chicago and Dallas - I have advised on sophisticated real\nestate and corporate transactions. I am thrilled at the opportunity to educate the next generation of\nbusiness and legal leaders.\nI have attached my curriculum vitae, a personal statement, and a list of professional references for your\nreview. I would welcome the opportunity to discuss how my experience aligns with Texas A&M Law’s\ncurriculum needs and how I can contribute to the success of your students.\nThank you for your time and consideration.\nBest regards,\nAshley Thompson, Esq.\n-- 1 of 8 --\n\nASHLEY THOMPSON, ESQ.\nArlington, TX | Ashley.Rouse88@gmail.com | (773) 304-6814\n*Admitted to practice law in Illinois\nPROFESSIONAL EXPERIENCE\nFUNDRISE |Corporate Counsel \tFeb. 2021 - Present\n● Sole real estate attorney for a real estate platform of $3B AUM.\n● Draft, negotiate, and review a wide range of real estate documents including financing documents,\nvendor contracts, property management agreements, commercial leases, and purchase and sale\nagreements.\n● Collaborate with cross-functional teams to structure and strategically advise on fund investments, debt\nfinancing, operations matters, and capital market transactions.\n● Address disputes, tenant claims, and property-related litigation including management of outside\ncounsel as necessary.\nKIRKLAND & ELLIS LLP | Senior Associate Attorney \tFeb. 2018 – Feb. 2021\n● Represented clients, including investment funds, publicly traded groups, and real estate operators in\nthe acquisition and disposition of all asset classes of commercial real estate from the diligence stage\nthrough closing.\n● Negotiated on behalf of borrowers in sophisticated mortgage and mezzanine financing transactions,\nincluding negotiation of loan agreements and corresponding ancillary documents.\n● Advised clients on the real estate aspects of corporate mergers & acquisitions.\n● Supervised junior associates and paralegals throughout the transaction and post-closing process.\n● Firm Leadership: Kirkland & Ellis Associate Committee; Kirkland & Ellis Recruiting Committee.\nBOARDMAN & CLARK LLP | Associate Attorney \tSept. 2015 – Jan. 2018\nAdditional Experience: Summer Associate (Summers 2013 and 2014)\n● Represented entities in commercial real estate transactions, including drafting purchase and sale\nagreements, drafting commercial lease agreements, and easement review.\n● Represented clients on a wide variety of legal issues including corporate matters, employment, and\nlitigation.\n● Firm Leadership: Summer Associate Program Co-Chair; Diversity Recruiting Committee\nPAUL HASTINGS LLP | Law Clerk \tNov. 2010 – July 2012\n● Supported litigation and transactional attorneys, including on-site trial assistance, pleading\npreparation, discovery management, and checklist management.\nEDUCATION\nUNIVERSITY OF WISCONSIN LAW SCHOOL | Madison, WI \tAugust 2012 - May 2015\nHonors: Dean’s List (Fall 2012, Spring 2014); Advanced Opportunity Fellow\nActivities: Mock Trial; Black Law Students Association; Research Assistant (2013–2015)\nUNIVERSITY OF ILLINOIS AT URBANA-CHAMPAIGN | Urbana, IL \tAugust 2006 - May 2010\nBachelor of Arts in Communication\nCollegiate Honors: Jackie Robinson Foundation Scholar: Presidential Merit Scholar\n-- 2 of 8 --\n\nI am thrilled at the opportunity to meaningfully give back to the next generation of lawyers. My career\nbegan at a midsize firm in Wisconsin where I built a strong foundation in commercial transactions and\ngeneral corporate law, before transitioning to the real estate practice group at Kirkland & Ellis, one of the\nmost prestigious law firms in the country. As a senior associate at Kirkland, I represented clients in the\nclosings of billions of dollars in commercial real estate acquisitions and financings. Now, as Corporate\nCounsel at Fundrise, a technology company that is democratizing access to real estate and technology\ninvesting, I advise internal stakeholders on all legal matters relating to our real estate portfolio of\napproximately $3B in AUM. I have firsthand experience in how legal strategy aligns with business\noperations and am confident that I could distill my lessons learned over the years into a useful curriculum\nfor law students of any year. One of the skills that I think is missing from most law school curriculum is\nhow to communicate with non-lawyers and distill key concepts in a way that is efficient. My decade of\nlegal experience has equipped me with many lessons learned that I would be eager to share with students.\nIn addition to my transactional work, I have extensive litigation management experience, helping the\ncompany to navigate disputes. My in-house role has allowed me to advise on business structuring,\ncompliance, and risk mitigation. Some of the courses that would be well-suited for my background\ninclude: Real Estate Transactions, The Junior Lawyer’s Guide to Deal Management, In-House in Tech:\nBalancing Risk and Innovation, From Law School to Career: Crafting Your Career in a Changing Legal\nLandscape.\nBeyond the legal framework, I am passionate about helping students develop their professional identity\nand overcome imposter syndrome—challenges many law students, particularly from underrepresented\nbackgrounds, face when entering the profession. Drawing from my own journey—from midsize firm to\nBigLaw to in-house—I strive to create a dynamic, inclusive learning environment that bridges legal\ntheory with real-world application. I look forward to discussing this opportunity further.\n-- 3 of 8 --\n\nMichelle Mirabal, Esq.\nAffinius Capital/USAA Real Estate, Executive Director\nMichelle.Mirabal@gmail.com\nBackground: Michelle was Deputy General Counsel for several years at Fundrise. As such, she\nhas direct experience working with me in a supervisory role. She can also speak to my\nextensive real estate experience managing the closing of large real estate transactions during\nmy time at Fundrise.\nAndrew Small, P.C.\nKirkland & Ellis LLP, Senior Partner\nandrew.small@kirkland.com\nAndrew Small is a senior partner in the real estate practice group at Kirkland & Ellis. I worked\nwith Andy frequently during my time at the firm. Andrew is a mentor and should have good\ninsight about my substantive real estate knowledge and ability to manage transactions.\nBenjamin St. Angelo, Esq.\nFundrise, Senior Corporate Counsel\nbstangelo@fundrise.com\nBenjamin is a colleague in the legal department at Fundrise. We have worked together during\nthe entirety of my time at Fundrise.\n-- 4 of 8 --\n\nApplication Forms\nFoster Child Form\nFoster Child\nI was not a foster child\n-- 5 of 8 --\n\nVeteran Status/Identification Form\nVoluntary Self-Identification of Veteran Status\nI identify as a veteran, just not a protected veteran\nSurviving Spouse of a Veteran\nI am not a surviving spouse of a veteran\nOrphan of a Veteran\nI am not an orphan of a veteran\n-- 6 of 8 --\n\nClery Act\nAcknowledgement:\nI acknowledge that I have received the above information regarding the Clery Act\n-- 7 of 8 --\n\nNotice of Non-Discrimination\nAcknowledgement:\nI acknowledge that I have received the information above regarding notice of non-discrimination and abuse\n-- 8 of 8 --\n\n	2025-10-12 01:08:45.706037+00	[0.005182477,-0.0026183429,-0.011659166,-0.0222