is Luis Alejandro Urrea, and I am applying for the Adjunct Professor (Academic\nProfessional Track, Non-Tenure) position. I am a graduate of the University of Tennessee College of Law,\nClass of 2023. I am licensed to practice here in Tennessee, and I most recently worked as an associate\nattorney with Bernstein, Stair & McAdams LLP in Knoxville, Tennessee. My wife and I have been in\nKnoxville since 2019, and we have since purchased a home here.\nI have always loved teaching. With two younger brothers at age gaps of six and ten years relative\nto me, they became my first students, and I soon began teaching them about the world. When they had\nquestions about their schoolwork, social interactions, or navigating their lives in general, they usually came\nto me, not our parents. This was not due to our parents’ lack of love or caring, but because they could not\nknow the information my brothers sought. My parents are Mexican immigrants, and when I was born, they\ndid not speak English or have any familiarity with the American education system. So, in a way, I became\na teacher to my parents as well, translating and interpreting English to Spanish, and teaching them the\nEnglish language and American customs.\nAfter completing my undergraduate studies, I became a teacher for Teach For America, teaching\n7th Grade Science in Mission, Texas. Though difficult, it was a privilege to teach, and learn, in what is\nknown as the Rio Grande Valley of Texas (“Valley”). I created lesson plans, painstakingly learned and\nimplemented effective classroom management procedures, and communicated with my department head\nand principal. While in the Valley, I volunteered for a community organization, La Union del Pueblo Entero\n(“LUPE”). With LUPE, I taught adult English and citizenship courses in an effort to prepare those who\nhad achieved permanent residency status for their citizenship exams. After Teach For America, my then\nfiancé, now wife, and I decided to move to Knoxville to start our married lives together in a place entirely\nnew to both of us. I found work at a local non-profit, Centro Hispano de East Tennessee (“Centro”), where,\namong other responsibilities, I had the opportunity to again teach English classes.\nAfter my work at Centro, I felt the call of law school. Like teaching, the law has always been of\ninterest to me. I am fascinated by our collective choice to abide by a set of rules that we, through our\nrepresentatives, create. And so, I now find myself a law school graduate and attorney. However, after\nspending two years as a law clerk, and roughly one year as an associate attorney, I believe I am better suited\nfor a position teaching, and continuing to learn, the law. I certainly realize that I am a newer law school\ngraduate, and I understand the potential pitfalls of being in such a position.\nHowever, I also understand its benefits. Though I am aware that law school students are\nincreasingly diverse in age, I know that most students are still in their twenties and thirties, and as a thirty-\none-year-old myself, the potential for meaningful connection along shared commonalities is vast.\nAdditionally, I also have diverse life experiences which invite respect. I am the oldest child of two Mexican\n-- 2 of 7 --\n\nimmigrants, the first in my family to graduate from college, become a teacher, graduate from law school,\nor become an attorney. I was born and raised in Texas, but moved to Massachusetts for my undergraduate\nstudies, then moved back to Texas to teach along the Texan Mexican border, and now I live in Tennessee.\nWith my background, I believe I have much to offer law students both academically and\ninterpersonally. I also understand the value of an online education and its potential to reach ever more\npeople in this technology age. I am a product of a hybrid education and, though it took some getting used\nto, I am now familiar with online video conferencing interfaces.\nFinally, nearly the entirety of my 