104	132	walker_marnitia_5786940.pdf	\N	Marnitia T. Walker\nmarnitiawalker@gmail.com\n603 Leafy Ridge, San Antonio, TX 78251\n(240)-216-6537\nTo Whom it May Concern,\nI am writing to express my strong interest in the Non-Tenure Adjunct Professor of Law Position\nwith Texas A&M University School of Law. With a background in biology and a passion for\npublic service work, Contract Law and Intellectual Property, particularly patent law, I am\nconfident in my ability to contribute to your team.\nDuring my time at Prairie View A&M University, where I completed my bachelor's degree in\nbiology, I conducted several research projects focusing on the disparities faced by minorities in\nboth the legal and medical fields. These experiences helped me recognize the challenges African\nAmericans and disabled African Americans encounter within the legal system. As someone who\nhas personally faced and overcome difficulties associated with a disability, I am driven to promote\ndiversity, inclusion, and equity in spaces where individuals like me are often overlooked.\nAs a graduate of Southern University Law Center, I actively engaged in various organizations and\ninitiatives. As a former mentee with The Appellate Project, Patent Law Association, and Vice-\nChair for the Southwest Region Black Law Students Association, I am committed to advocating\nfor underrepresented groups and facilitating positive change. Additionally, I was honored to be\nnamed a 2022 Law Scholar by the National Bar Institute, received a Cali Award for Torts, and I\nworked as a Teaching Assistant for the 1L Contracts class and as an interim Torts and Legal\nProcess TA. I have an interest in teaching Contracts, Torts or Intellectual Property. I am flexible\nand can be put in any of these classes if I am needed. I have experience with Contract Law and\nIntellectual Property as I was an extern with the United States Patent and Trademark Office,\nparticipated in my schools Technology clinic where I reviewed contracts on a daily. During my\ntenure as a teaching assistant, I conducted review sessions with students, graded assignments and\nassisted the professor in the preparation and organization of teaching materials.\nDriven by a passion for helping those in need, my unwavering commitment to providing relief and\nsupport is evident in my work. I approach every situation with patience and empathy, and I am\ndetermined to overcome challenges. With previous office and leadership experience, I possess\nexceptional organizational and leadership skills that enable me to excel in diverse environments.\nMoreover, my educational journey has reinforced my belief in the necessity of diversity within the\nlegal profession to ensure the inclusion of minority perspectives in the judiciary. As a graduate of\na historically black university, I have been instilled with the values of excellence, persistence, and\nsetting high personal standards.\n-- 1 of 11 --\n\nI am excited about the opportunity to join the faculty at Texas A&M University School of Law\nand contribute to its mission. I would be honored to be considered , and I sincerely appreciate your\ntime and consideration. Should you have any further questions or require additional information,\nplease do not hesitate to reach me at 240-216-6537 or via email at marnitiawalker@gmail.com\nThank you for your attention.\nSincerely,\nMarnitia T Walker\n-- 2 of 11 --\n\nMarnitia T. Walker\n603 Leafy Ridge San Antonio, TX 78251 70816 Cell: (240) 216-6537\nMarnitiawalker@gmail.com\nEDUCATION\nFranklin Pierce School of Law, Concord, NH\nIntellectual Property LLM, December 2026\nSouthern University Law Center, Baton Rouge, LA\nDoctor of Jurisprudence , December 2024\n• \tThe Appellate Project- Mentee\n• \t2023-2024 Vice-Chair Southwest Region Black Law Students Association\n• \tCALI Award Recipient – Torts\n• \tNational Bar Institute Law Scholar\n• \tSouthern University Law Center Moot Court Board\nPrairie View A&M University, Prairie View, TX\nBachelor of Science, Biology, August 2020\n• \tPrairie View Merit Scholar\n• \tMember, Beta Beta Beta Biological Honor Society\n• \tPanther Student Ambassador\nCERTIFICATIONS\n• \tLexis Nexis Research Proficiency Certification\n• \tWorld Intellectual Property Organization Using and Exploiting Patent Information Certification\nEXPERIENCE\nUSPTO Student Extern, United States Patent and Trademark Office\nPatent Extern\nMay 2024-August 2024\n• \tTraining on how to become an effective writer in drafting various documents and reports,\ncreating spreadsheets, charts and presenting a Varity of data and information.\n• \tTraining and devolvement on various topics relating to the USPTO and government service\nSouthern University Law Center Board of Student Advisors, Baton Rouge, LA\nTeaching Assistant- Contracts I & II\n$10 h/r \tAugust 2022 – December 2024\n• \tAttend class meetings when asked to assist professor.\n• \tConduct small review sessions to further explain concepts and model responses.\n• \tAssist professor in the preparation and organization of teaching materials.\nKaplan Bar Review Student Representative, Baton Rouge, LA\nStudent Rep \tJuly 2024- December 2024\n• \tConduct personalized outreach to discuss the value of Kaplan’s course.\n• \tFacilitate the registration and follow-up of classmates in virtual demos.\n• \tPlan, organize, and host events sponsored by Kaplan Bar Review.\nLawyers for Good Government\n-- 3 of 11 --\n\nPro Bono Student Volunteer \tJanuary 2022- December 2024\n• \tAssisted in mobilizing volunteers to provide legal guidance to healthcare providers\n• \tSupported International Law Attorneys in providing asylum placement for asylum seekers\n• \tProvided Support to Environmental Law Attorneys as they trained communities on how to secure\nfederal climate funding\nABBVIE Intellectual Property Legal Academy, Baton Rouge, LA\nJanuary 2023\n• \tAttended an intensive legal academy related to Intellectual Property where Students prepared a\npatent infringement claim chart, presented mock arguments on claim construction, and concluded\nwith conducting a trademark clearance and validity search after branding the invention.\n• \tParticipated in the patent-focused IP Academy and drafted memorandums of invention,\ninvestigated inventorship contributions, drafted a patent application with claims, and defended\nthe claims in a mock-Patent Examiner interview.\n-- 4 of 11 --\n\nMarnitia Walker\nAs an educator in Contracts and Tort Law, my teaching philosophy is centered on\nfostering critical thinking, practical application, and student engagement. My goal is to help\nstudents understand the principles of law, analyze legal problems effectively, and apply legal\nreasoning to real-world situations. I believe that students learn best when they are actively\nengaged in the learning process. Therefore, I incorporate case studies, interactive discussions,\nand problem-based learning into my teaching approach. Rather than just memorizing legal rules,\nstudents will develop analytical skills by examining how laws apply to actual disputes and legal\ndecisions.\nFurthermore, I emphasize the importance of ethical reasoning and professional\nresponsibility in legal education. Contracts and tort law impact people’s rights and obligations,\nand it is crucial for students to appreciate the broader social and ethical implications of their legal\ndecisions. In my teaching plans, I strive to:\n1. Create an interactive learning environment case simulation.\n2. Use real-world case studies to connect legal principles to current issues in business and\nsociety.\n3. Encourage critical analysis and problem-solving by challenging students with complex\nlegal scenarios.\n4. Incorporate technology and multimedia to enhance student engagement and\nunderstanding.\n5. Provide continuous feedback and support, fostering a growth mindset and confidence\nin legal reasoning.\nUltimately, my goal is to equip students with a deep understanding of contract and tort law,\nstrong analytical skills, and a passion for legal inquiry. By bridging theory and practice, I aim to\nprepare them for successful careers where they can apply legal knowledge responsibly and\neffectively. By the end of my course students should be able to:\n• Understand the essential elements of a valid contract and the consequences of a breach.\n• Analyze key doctrines in contract law, including offer, acceptance, consideration, and\ncapacity.\n• Identify and evaluate various types of contractual terms and defenses.\n• Understand the principles of tort law, including negligence, strict liability, and\nintentional torts.\n• Apply tort and contract law principles to real-world scenarios and case law.\n• Develop critical thinking and problem-solving skills in legal analysis.\nMy teaching plans and objectives for Intellectual Property include:\n1. Build a strong foundation in copyright, trademark, patent, and trade secret law.\n2. Encourage critical thinking about the balance between protecting innovation and\npromoting public access.\n3. Develop practical skills in drafting IP agreements, analyzing infringement cases, and\n-- 5 of 11 --\n\nMarnitia Walker\nadvising on IP strategies.\n4. Prepare students for the future by exploring emerging topics such as AI and IP,\ndigital piracy, and international enforcement.\nBy bridging theory and practice, my goal is to cultivate a deep understanding of IP law,\nContracts and Tort Law, a problem-solving mindset, and a passion for innovation and creativity\nin my students. I aspire to prepare them not only for legal careers but also for leadership roles in\nshaping the future of law and policy.\n-- 6 of 11 --\n\nContact Reference Sheet\nKimberley Lamotte\nProfessor of Law\nSouthern University Law Center\nFormer Supervisor\nKlamotte@sulc.edu\n(225)-771-3133\nToni Brent\nNurse Practitioner\nMentor and Family Friend\nLafayb2@yahoo.com\n(210)-313-7547\nCatherine Rastovski\nSupervisory Patent Examiner\nUnited States Paten