105	133	warren_brinton_5587319.pdf	\N	Brinton T. Warren\n3738 30th Road North, Arlington, Virginia 22207 (703) 346-3655\nDecember 3, 2024\nTerri Lynn Helge\nAssociate Dean of Academic Affairs\nTexas A&M Law School\n1515 Commerce St.\nFt. Worth, TX 76102\nDear Associate Dean Helge,\nI am happy to submit this cover letter, personal statement, and C.V. in support of an application\nfor a part-time, remote faculty position with Texas A&M Law School.\nI have 30 years of experience as an attorney, specializing for most of that time in federal\ntaxation as an IRS Chief Counsel attorney.\nI also have considerable experience teaching. Since 2022, I have been a part-time legal writing\ninstructor at George Mason University’s Scalia Law School.\nI am happy teaching at Scalia Law School, but I am interested in other opportunities for teaching\nJuris Doctor students. I am interested in teaching legal writing, and I am also interested in\nteaching income taxation and federal tax procedure.\nI have taught both in-person and in completely online formats.\nI would like to highlight these points:\n• Since the Fall of 2022, I have been an adjunct professor at the George Mason University\nScalia Law School, where I lead sections in both Appellate Advocacy and Legislative\nand Regulatory Writing.\n• Within IRS Chief Counsel, I lead teams of attorneys in developing federal guidance for\ncomplex tax issues. This includes training junior tax attorneys in the work necessary to\ndevelop these guidance projects.\n• I was also a Branch Chief for almost five years, personally overseeing the onboarding\nand training of newly hired attorneys. This included managing my branch through the\nonce-in-a-generation change in work process resulting from the pandemic.\n-- 1 of 13 --\n\n2\n• I have extensive experience in various federal tax sub-specialties, including income tax\naccounting, procedure and controversy, and professional regulation. This experience\npositions me well to offer a rich real-world practice perspective to students.\n• I have considerable experience teaching at this point, including teaching an internal\ncourse for my office which was offered exclusively virtually. I am interested in teaching\nonline courses for your law school.\nThank you for considering my application. I would be happy to discuss how I can contribute to\nthe success of your students. Please feel free to contact me at (703) 346-3655 or\nbrinton_w@yahoo.com.\nSincerely,\nBrinton T. Warren\nBrinton T. Warren\n-- 2 of 13 --\n\nBrinton Taylor Warren\n3738 30th Road North\nArlington, VA 22207 US\n703-346-3655\nbrinton_w@yahoo.com\nEducation:\nGeorgetown University Law Center Washington, DC\nLL.M (Taxation)\n2002\nHonors: With Distinction.\nGeorge Mason University School of Law\nJuris Doctor\n1994\nHonors: Cum Laude\nUniversity of Virginia\nB.A., Foreign Affairs\n1989\nTeaching Experience:\nAdjunct Professor of Law, George Mason University Antonin Scalia Law School, 2022-present\nSection Leader in 2L program; taught appellate advocacy (Fall) and legislative and regulatory\ndrafting (Spring).\nProfessor, Chief Counsel Scholars, Income Tax Accounting, Fall 2021\nTaught a graduate level income tax accounting course (on a fully virtual basis) to 40-50 attorneys in\nthe IRS Office of Chief Counsel as part of Counsel’s internal LL.M program.\nInstructor, National Office Legal Writing, 2017\nServed as faculty for the IRS Office of Chief Counsel legal writing program for practicing attorneys;\ntaught in both lecture format and worked with students one-on-one for individual projects.\nAdjunct Professor of Law, Georgetown University Law Center, Graduate Tax Program, 2004-\n2006\nTaught the ethics of tax practice and tax lawyering, a graduate-level class that is an elective within\nthe Taxation LL.M.\n-- 3 of 13 --\n\n2\nWork Experience:\nMarch 2022 - Present:\nSpecial Counsel\nIRS Office of Chief Counsel\nOffice of Associate Chief Counsel (Income Tax and Accounting)\n1111 Constitution Avenue, N.W.\nWashington, D.C. 20224\nResponsible for leading teams of attorneys in drafting regulations and other significant items of\nfederal tax guidance in income tax accounting.\nApril 2018 – March 2022:\nBranch Chief\nIRS Office of Chief Counsel\nOffice of Associate Chief Counsel (Income Tax and Accounting)\n1111 Constitution Avenue, N.W.\nWashington, D.C. 20224\nLed a branch of over ten attorneys and other professionals, responsible for all aspects of managing\na national office branch handling work products involving deductions and methods of accounting.\nReturned to the position of special counsel in the wake of numerous departures in the ITA Front\nOffice as the COVID-19 Pandemic ended.\nJanuary 2013 -- March 2018:\nSpecial Counsel\nIRS Office of Chief Counsel\nOffice of Associate Chief Counsel (Income Tax and Accounting)\n1111 Constitution Avenue, N.W.\nWashington, D.C. 20224\nResponsible for leading teams of attorneys in drafting regulations and other significant items of\nfederal tax guidance in income tax accounting.\nApril 2010 -- December 2012:\nIRS Office of Chief Counsel\nSpecial Counsel to the Director, OPR\n1111 Constitution Avenue, N.W.\nWashington, D.C. 20224\nServed as a general legal advisor to the Director of the Office of Professional Responsibility with a\nfocus on IRS enforcement of the rules of tax practice under Circular 230.\nMay 2007 – April 2010:\nSenior Technician Reviewer\nIRS Office of Chief Counsel\nOffice of Associate Chief Counsel (Procedure and Administration)\nBranch reviewer responsible for technical accuracy of work-products of subordinate attorneys. Focus\non IRS Circular 230 rules, penalties, and periods of limitations. Also handled Tax Court practice\nitems, section 6103 disclosure issues, and closing agreements.\n-- 4 of 13 --\n\n3\nJune 2003 – May 2007:\nSpecial Counsel to the Assistant Chief Counsel\nIRS Office of Chief Counsel\nOffice of Associate Chief Counsel (Procedure and Administration)\n1111 Constitution Avenue, N.W.\nWashington, D.C. 20224\nFront office reviewer responsible for leadership over team projects. Focus on IRS Circular 230 rules,\npenalties, and periods of limitations.\nOctober 1999 – May 2003:\nAttorney-Advisor\nIRS Office of Chief Counsel\nOffice of Associate Chief Counsel (Procedure and Administration)\nCo-author of IRS Circular 230 regulations on the regulation of tax practice, including penalty\nprotection opinions. Also handled accuracy-related penalties, and periods of limitations.\nJanuary 1997-March 1999\nGeneral Practice Attorney\nArlington, Virginia\nHandled a variety of civil and criminal matters, including felony and misdemeanor criminal defense in\ncourts across Northern Virginia.\nJanuary 1996-December 1996\nLegislative Assistant\nCongresswoman Enid Greene\nServed as a legislative assistant for Member of Congress from Utah. Handled a variety of matters\nincluding federal agencies, criminal and judicial reform, and science.\n1990-1992\nConstituent Services Assistant\nCongressman Frank Wolf\nServed as a legislative assistant for Member of Congress from Utah. Handled a variety of matters\nincluding federal agencies, criminal and judicial reform, and science.\nRecent Counsel Awards:\nPerformance Award, 2023\nPerformance Award, 2022\nPerformance Award, 2021\nPerformance Award, 2020\nPerformance Award, 2019\nPerformance Award, 2018\n-- 5 of 13 --\n\nPersonal Statement in Support of Application to Teach at Texas A&M University\nLaw School\nBrinton T. Warren\nPersonal Background:\nI have 30 years of experience as an attorney, specializing for most of that time in federal\ntaxation as a manager within the IRS Office of Chief Counsel. Since 2022, I have been\na part-time legal writing instructor at George Mason University’s Scalia Law School,\nwhere I have taught in both the fall and spring semesters.\nI am very happy teaching at Scalia Law School, but I am interested in other\nopportunities for teaching Juris Doctor students. I plan to continue teaching legal writing,\nbut I seek to expand my portfolio to include doctrinal courses, most notably, federal\nincome taxation and federal tax procedure.\nI have been heavily involved in other subject-matter areas over the course of my career\nand would be happy to teach in these as well: civil procedure, property, professional\nregulation and criminal law.\nAs a manager in a federal agency, I have taught subordinate attorneys, both in formal\nand informal settings, both in in-person and in online formats. As part of my agency’s\nlegal training program, I have taught as faculty in areas relating to federal taxation, legal\nwriting, and I have worked extensively in training subordinate managers.\nI very much enjoy teaching and would like to transition to a position in which I am\nworking full-time with law students to prepare them for future success. I am happy to\ncontinue to work part-time assignments as I make this transition. I am interested in\nteaching a course for Texas A&M on a remote basis.\nI know both from colleagues and also from the public record that Texas A&M is a\nfantastic place to teach.\nMy Teaching Philosophy:\nTo be outstanding, a teacher must inspire students, not simply inform them.\nThere is so much information out there. But there is little inspiration.\nI have been successful in a wide variety of positions. I have represented defendants in\ncriminal trials. I have been a constituent services assistant to a Member of Congress. I\nhave worked as a legislative assistant on the Floor of the House of Representatives. I\nhave been a manager within a federal agency. I want to pass along information I have\nlearned.\nBut there is so much more to it than mere information.\n-- 6 of 13 --\n\n2\nI have taught legal writing at the J.D. level for almost three years. And, for more than a\ndecade, I have spent a significant amount of time training and mentoring junior\nattorneys. I have spent a considerable amount of time designing and delivering training\nprograms.\nWith that experience in mind, I have these three specific fundamental points for\nteaching law students:\n1) You need to put yourself in the mind of your students.\n2) You need to get to your points quickly. If you do not get engagement from your\nstudents early on, you likely won’t ever get it.\n3) You need to focus on a few key points of the highest quality, guarding against\ninformation overload and creating overwhelm among your students.\nIf you select me to teach for Texas A&M, I will abide by these three principles. If you\nselect me to teach for you, you can expect me to help to contribute to the success of\nyour students.\nThe number one problem in the legal academy – one which is shared with the legal\nprofession at large – is information overload.\nYour students are drowning in information.\nAnd you are drowning in information.\nThus, a key skill in teaching is curating. You are curating the most important pieces of\ninformation. Then, you are transmitting those pieces to your students with empathy. You\nneed to have empathy first, as the specific techniques you use to teach follow from\nempathy, from being in the mind of your student.\nOf note, it is only within the discipline of legal writing, specifically brief writing, that we\nemphasize the need to tailor the message to take into account the cognitive overload of\nthe audience. That audience is a special one: the judges who decide the cases. So,\nthere, we are sensitive to audience overload. We thusly emphasize techniques for\nconcision and clarity of presentation.\nThat concern –for the cognitive overload of the audience--should take the forefront on a\nmuch wider basis. We should design and deliver a wide variety of law school courses in\nthe way excellent brief writers design and deliver legal briefs.\nEmpathy. Engagement. Brevity.\nInspiration.\nMy Plans for Teaching:\nFor my teaching plans, I prefer to continue to teach legal writing, either by leading a\nlegal writing section or serving a legal writing program in some other capacity. Legal\n-- 7 of 13 --\n\n3\nwriting is fundamental, and I enjoy the opportunity to be engaged with fundamentals on\na weekly basis. Though grading papers on a continual basis throughout the semester is\na burden, I enjoy the connection with students. I enjoy the opportunity to help students\nimprove such a fundamental skill. It is coaching as much as teaching. I use the\nopportunity to grade papers as the opportunity to coach.\nWhile continuing to teach legal writing, I plan to take on an additional course. I am\ninterested in teaching a doctrinal course. My preference would be to teach federal\nincome tax, but I am flexible.\nI have begun to write articles, but I have yet to have anything published. I have\nsubmitted one article to the Legal Writing Institute’s Second Draft. But it was turned\ndown. As an employee of a federal agency, I am under a significant restriction and\nagency review process before I can submit an article to an outside organization for\npublication. My expectation is that I will not be able to produce a large volume of articles\nuntil after my retirement as a federal employee.\nI plan to attend the Legal Writing Institute’s 10th Biennial Applied Legal Storytelling\nConference, which will be held at the University of Michigan Law School in July of 2025.\nI would be pleased to provide any additional information that would be helpful.\n-- 8 of 13 --\n\nBrinton T. Warren\nList of Professional References\nDecember 2024\nScott Vance\nAssociate Chief Counsel, Income Tax Accounting, Office of Chief Counsel, Internal Revenue Service\n(703) 585-5470\nJulie Hanlon-Bolton\nDeputy Associate Chief Counsel, Income Tax Accounting, Office of Chief Counsel, Internal Revenue\nService\n(508) 360-1082\nJack Manhire\nAttorney-Advisor, Taxpayer Advocate Service\n(817) 975-9025\n-- 9 of 13 --\n\nApplication Forms\nFoster Child Form\nFoster Child\nI was not a foster child\n-- 10 of 13 --\n\nVeteran Status/Identification Form\nVol