ticularly in the field of law, I aim to cultivate a\nlearning environment that combines rigorous academic standards with accessible, practical application. My teaching\nphilosophy is rooted in three core principles: teach the foundations of law, foster critical engagement, and nurture\npractical skills.\nAs a first-generation college graduate and lawyer, I understand firsthand the transformative power of education.\nThis personal experience shapes my commitment to teaching foundational concepts in law so as to foster critical\nengagement from students. I believe effective education begins with firm foundations and critical engagement,\nwhich requires creative educational applications that reach students in their context—academically, professionally,\nand personally. For online students, this means creating dynamic and interactive course content that bridges the\nphysical distance and fosters a sense of community. Whether through asynchronous discussion boards, real-time\nvideo conferences, or interactive assignments, my goal is to foster engagement with the student that lays a\nfoundation of knowledge and cultivates critical thinking.\nAnother cornerstone of my teaching philosophy is emphasizing practical application. Law is a living discipline,\ndeeply intertwined with real-world scenarios. As an attorney with extensive experience in tax litigation, domestic and\ninternational business, and wealth management, I draw on these experiences to design courses that equip students\nwith the skills they need to succeed in their careers. For example, in my online Juris Doctor courses, I emphasize\ncase studies, simulations, and problem-solving exercises to help students connect theoretical principles with\npractical legal strategies. I employed various simulations to teach law students Negotiations and Mediation for law\nand business at Trinity Law School.\nI also recognize the unique challenges and opportunities that online learning presents. Distance education often\nattracts a diverse student body, including working professionals and those balancing multiple responsibilities.\nFlexibility and accessibility are critical. I strive to offer clear instructions, timely feedback, and adaptable learning\npaths to accommodate different learning styles and schedules. My experience creating and teaching online\ncourses—including those in estate planning at Texas A&M University and law subjects at Trinity Law School—has\ntaught me the importance of leveraging technology to support student success.\nUltimately, my teaching philosophy reflects my belief that education is not merely the transfer of knowledge but the\ncultivation of critical thinking, ethical reasoning, and professional confidence. It is my hope that every student I\nteach will leave my courses better equipped to serve their communities and make meaningful contributions to their\nprofession and community.\n-- 4 of 9 --\n\nPROFESSIONAL REFERENCES\nJODEY HINZE\nDEAN, COLLEGE OF ARTS AND HUMANITIES\nHOUSTON CHRISTIAN UNIVERSITY\njhinze@hc.edu\nNATHAN HARNESS\nDIRECTOR OF FINANCIAL PLANNING & INSTRUCTIONAL PROFESSOR\nDEPARTMENT OF AGRICULTURAL ECONOMICS\nTEXAS A&M UNIVERISTY – COLLEGE STATION\nnharness@tamu.edu\nMARK BETTENCOURT\nCEO\nBETTENCOURT TAX ADVISORS, LLC\nmbettencourt@btanow.com\n-- 5 of 9 --\n\nApplication Forms\nFoster Child Form\nFoster Child\nI was not a foster child\n-- 6 of 9 --\n\nVeteran Status/Identification Form\nVoluntary Self-Identification of Veteran Status\nI do not wish to specify\nSurviving Spouse of a Veteran\nI am not a surviving spouse of a veteran\nOrphan of a Veteran\nI am not an orphan of a veteran\n-- 7 of 9 --\n\nClery Act\nAcknowledgement:\nI acknowledge that I have received the above information regarding the Clery Act\n-- 8 of 9 --\n\nNotice of Non-Discrimination\nAcknowledgement:\nI acknowledge that I have received the information above regarding notice of non-discrimination and abuse\n-- 9 of 9 --\n\n	2025-10-12 01:08:46.221557+00	[-0.0035301868