107	135	wells_keifer_5539404.pdf	\N	KEIFER BLAKE WELLS\n313 TURTLE CREEK DR. MCKINNEY, TX 75072 • (248) 444-9774 • KEIFERWELLS@ME.COM\nNovember 22, 2024\nHiring Official\nTexas A&M University\nCollege of Law\n1515 Commerce St.\nFort Worth, TX 76102\nDear Hiring Official,\nI currently serve as an Attorney-Advisor with the U.S. Department of the Interior and am writing to\napply for a part time adjunct professor position at the Texas A&M University College of Law. I am\nuniquely interested in this position, as it would allow me to effectively leverage my experience as a\npublic servant, attorney, and military officer with my longstanding passion for training and educating\nothers, through effective mentorship, academic rigor, and leadership.\nAs a military officer, reserve Judge Advocate, former Operations Department Head at a deployable\nspecialized forces Coast Guard unit, and current civilian Attorney-Advisor, I have had the unique\npleasure of leading, training, and mentoring attorneys and law students alike, in addition to non-\nlawyers, law enforcement professionals, and those interested in legal careers. Beginning in my first\ntour as an active-duty Judge Advocate, I played a critical role in Service efforts to develop recruiting\nand training of new Judge Advocates. For example, at the Thirteenth Coast Guard District, I developed\nand led a new regional legal recruiting program focused on leveraging limited resources to engage with\nlaw schools not traditionally recruited by the Coast Guard. As a part of this effort, I travelled\nthroughout disparate regions away from major recruiting centers, visiting law schools, conducting On-\nCampus Interviews, counseling candidates, providing presentations, and developing tracking\nmechanisms to improve engagement. This work resulted in the selection of legal interns from new and\ndiverse backgrounds, including some who would later be commissioned as Judge Advocates, providing\nlong-term benefit to the public for years to come. I would later offer critical legal training to some of\nthese newly selected Judge Advocates, as they began their legal careers.\nIn recognition of all of those who helped me achieve my own dream to become an attorney, I have also\ncommitted myself to supporting teaching and mentoring others. In attempting to live up to this goal, I\nhave collaterally engaged in countless activities to mentor a range of individuals by serving as board\nmember on selection panels, leading mock interview boards, and reviewing and commenting on\napplication packages. Finally, I have a proven record of providing more formal functional legal\ntraining to diverse audiences as a part of my official duties as an Attorney-Advisor. Included among\nthis is my work providing authority and jurisdiction, liability, and use of force legal training to law\nenforcement officers through the Bureau of Land Management’s In-Service Legal Update Training,\nLaw Enforcement for Managers, Introduction to Resource Protection, and previously ethics, as a part\nof Annual Ethics Training.\nI would appreciate an opportunity to meet with you to discuss my qualifications and the position.\nThank you for your consideration.\nSincerely,\nKeifer B. Wells\n-- 1 of 8 --\n\nKEIFER BLAKE WELLS\n313 TURTLE CREEK DR. MCKINNEY, TX 75072 • (248) 444-9774 • KEIFERWELLS@ME.COM\nEDUCATION\nUnited States Naval War College \tNewport, RI\nMaster of Arts, National Defense and Strategic Studies \tJune 2020\nUniversity of Iowa College of Law \tIowa City, IA\nJuris Doctor; Willard L. Boyd Public Service Award with Highest Distinction \tMay 2015\nBerklee College of Music \tBoston, MA\nBachelor of Music, Music Business and Management \tMay 2012\nEXPERIENCE\nUnited States Department of the Interior, Office of the Solicitor\nLaw Enforcement Attorney-Advisor \tJanuary 2024 - Present\nCivil Service (GS-14/0905), Division of General Law \tMcKinney, TX\n• Primary attorney supporting and advising over 200 Bureau of Land Management (BLM) law enforcement officers nationwide\n• Drafts and presents agency-wide training on law enforcement issues, case developments, and legal considerations for operations\n• Represents BLM as agency liaison to Department of Justice and other prosecuting entities on major cases\n• Advises BLM law enforcement senior leadership on legal issues, reviews agency enforcement policy, and develops case strategies\n• Reviews terms and conditions of BLM memoranda agreements to ensure legal authority and consistency with Federal standards\nPublic Lands Attorney-Advisor \tJanuary 2023 - January 2024\nCivil Service (GS-14/0905), Pacific Southwest Region \tSacramento, CA\n• Provided counsel interpreting regulations pertaining to land, environment, resources, energy, compliance, and enforcement\n• Conducted legal research and analyzed statutes, regulations, and case law to produce opinions and memoranda for leadership\n• Represented BLM before range of outside entities, including Federal, state, and local entities, non-profits, tribes, and attorneys\n• Reviewed, modified, and executed range of complex inter-agency agreements with Federal, state and local partners\nEthics Attorney-Advisor \tJanuary 2021 - January 2023\nCivil Service (GS-14/0905), Departmental Ethics Office \tSacramento, CA\n• Served as primary attorney responsible for providing ethics advice to BLM employees in California, Montana, and the Dakotas\n• Drafted detailed post-government ethics advice for departing BLM personnel for representational and contracting activities\n• Served as BLM Acting Deputy Ethics Counselor during supervisor absences, managing diverse team of attorneys and specialists\nUnited States Coast Guard\nNational Security Law Attorney \tOctober 2024 – Present\nReady Reserve (O4/Lieutenant Commander), United States Indo-Pacific Command \tHonolulu, HI\n• Augments Joint Operational Law Team providing operational legal support to joint units of major U.S. Combatant Command\n• Only Coast Guard reserve Judge Advocate on legal staff, integrating reserve and agency legal equities into decision-making\nOperations Department Head \tOctober 2023 – October 2024\nReady Reserve (O-4/Lieutenant Commander), Port Security Unit 312 \tSouth San Francisco, CA\n• Led three Divisions, comprised of 65 officer and enlisted members, in combined and joint expeditionary port security operations\n• Directly responsible for unit tactical operations, operational planning, and command and control over core unit mission functions\n• Implemented and oversaw unit operational training, including waterborne tactics and integrated anti-terrorism/force protection\nShoreside Security Division Officer / Assistant Division Officer \tMarch 2021 - October 2023\nReady Reserve (O-4/Lieutenant Commander, O-3/ Lieutenant), Port Security Unit 312 \tSouth San Francisco, CA\n• Led 27 members in port security operations, including deployment to participate in major international military exercise\n• Ensured effective management of Division personnel, evaluations, discipline, field training, and operations\nJudge Advocate / MARPOL Enforcement Attorney \tJune 2018 - December 2020\nActive Duty (O-3/Lieutenant), Thirteenth Coast Guard District \tSeattle, WA\n• Provided full-scope legal support to 42 operational units throughout the Pacific Northwest, comprised of over 3,000 personnel\n• Served as operational law attorney on interdiction and prosecution of largest maritime drug seizure in area, valued at $48 million\n• Developed and implemented area procedures for surety bond and undertaking requirements in environmental pollution cases\nJudge Advocate / Claims Settlement Officer \tJuly 2015 - May 2018\nActive Duty (O-3/Lieutenant), Coast Guard Legal Service Command \tNorfolk, VA\n• Adjudicated Federal claims against the government as claims settlement officer and oversaw 118 claims\n• Led four legal support teams and coordinated deployment of 24 attorneys in response to three major hurricane seasons\n• Advised 76 mission support units, managing approximately 200 general law matters as Judge Advocate\nADDITIONAL INFORMATION\nBar Admissions: \tState of Minnesota; Court of Appeals for the Armed Forces; Eligible for other States and Jurisdictions\nSelect Awards: \tA.B.A. Distinguished Legal Assistance Team Award; Coast Guard Commendation Medal (three awards)\n-- 2 of 8 --\n\nKEIFER BLAKE WELLS\n313 TURTLE CREEK DR. MCKINNEY, TX 75072 • (248) 444-9774 • KEIFERWELLS@ME.COM\nPersonal Statement: Translating Law into Action\nThrough my experience as an attorney primarily supporting military, government, and law\nenforcement organizations, I’ve found that legal practice is very different than what I envisioned it\nwould be 10 years ago during law school. More specifically, through both legal and professional\nmilitary training and experience, I have learned that the practice of law is not merely being able to\nrecite a compilation of cases and statutory references by rote. While comprehensive knowledge of the\nlaw remains a baseline element of effective practice, the ability to think critically and accurately weigh\nlegal risk separates the legal advisor sitting at the decision-maker’s table from a search engine.\nAccordingly, if selected as an adjunct professor, I would leverage these areas of focus, in addition to\ntraditional means of legal education, to effectively train and mentor law students.\nCritical thinking skills are the bedrock upon which a student or new legal professional can\nbuild a foundation of effective practice. To develop critical thinking skills, one must learn to\nunderstand ambiguities, ask relevant and perceptive questions, and challenge assumptions. In legal\neducation, this comes from facilitating free thought through open ended inquiry, while encouraging\nstudents to understand their own inclinations and predispositions in response. As summarized in the\nteachings of Sun Tzu, to be successful in battle requires that a military officer know both the enemy\nand themselves; in legal practice, I’ve found that it requires a lawyer to be introspective and self-aware\nof both themselves and their legal position, while simultaneously understanding alternative viewpoints.\nIn addition to critical thinking skills, it also is essential for law students to remember that in\nmany cases, consultation with an attorney is merely one element of a client’s decision matrix. In my\nexperience, I’ve found that lawyers are rarely the decision-maker, and instead are charged with making\na legally-sufficient recommendation to align with their client’s desired end-state. Further, while legal\nconsiderations are often a critical element to addressing a problem, the law does not always offer a\nsolution. This combination of factors requires an attorney to think outside the box, communicate\neffectively with diverse audiences, and always thoughtfully assess the legal risks of numerous courses\nof action. In practice, I like to discuss this with my clients as the “range of reasonable,” with each\noption tailored to the specific desired outcome of the client, along with a legal risk assessment for each\ncourse of action. As an adjunct professor, I would teach this by integrating policy and operational\nconsiderations into legal training scenarios, in support of the student’s development of a\ncomprehensive set of legal recommendations.\nHopefully, this brief personal statement touches on some of the important elements of my\nteaching philosophy. I look forward to the opportunity to meet with you to discuss this philosophy in\ngreater detail. Thank you for your consideration.\nSincerely,\nKeifer B. Wells\n-- 3 of 8 --\n\nKEIFER BLAKE WELLS\n313 TURTLE CREEK DR. MCKINNEY, TX 75072 • (248) 444-9774 • KEIFERWELLS@ME.COM\nReferences\n1. LCDR Stonie Carlson, Executive Officer, Port Security Unit 312, U.S. Coast Guard (Prior\nSupervisor)\na. Phone: (916) 996-4102\nb. Email: stoniecarlson@yahoo.com\n2. Janell Bogue, Supervisory Attorney Advisor, Pacific S